{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928476248,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"skill","callID":"call_X2luSu2gxM3kgU3SyGPZBchB","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"name":"sk-code-review"},"output":"<skill_content name=\"sk-code-review\">\n# Skill: sk-code-review\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-code-review, code-review, pull-request, findings-first, security-review, quality-gate, stack-agnostic, baseline-surface, sk-code -->\n\n# Code Review Baseline - Stack-Agnostic Findings-First Review\n\nUniversal findings-first review baseline paired with `sk-code` surface standards evidence for the detected code surface.\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers\n\nUse this skill when:\n- A user asks for code review, PR review, quality gate, or merge readiness.\n- A workflow dispatches `@review` for pre-commit or gate validation.\n- A user requests security/correctness risk analysis before merge.\n- A user wants severity-ranked findings with file:line evidence.\n\n### Keyword Triggers\n\n`review`, `code review`, `pr review`, `audit`, `security review`, `quality gate`, `request changes`, `findings`, `blocking issues`, `merge readiness`\n\n### Use Cases\n\n1. Review-only pass: findings-first output with no code edits.\n2. Gate validation: score + pass/fail recommendation for orchestrated workflows.\n3. Focused risk pass: security, concurrency, correctness, or removal-focused review.\n\n### When NOT to Use\n\n- Feature implementation without review intent.\n- Pure documentation editing where code behavior is not being assessed.\n- Git-only workflow tasks (branching, rebasing, commit hygiene) without code-quality evaluation intent.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\n\n### Primary Detection Signal\n\nReview behavior follows a baseline+surface-evidence model:\n\n- Baseline (always): `sk-code-review` findings-first doctrine.\n- Surface standards evidence (when available): `sk-code` detected surface resources.\n- Unknown surfaces: review against baseline security/correctness only and disclose uncertainty.\n\n### Phase Detection\n\n```text\nTASK CONTEXT\n    |\n    +- STEP 0: Load `sk-code-review` baseline + `sk-code` surface evidence. The dispatcher / agent assembling the sk-code-review prompt MUST prepend `CODE-REVIEW\\n\\n` as the first two lines of the rendered prompt before the reviewer LLM sees it. Reference resources stay unchanged.\n    +- STEP 1: Score intents (top-2 when ambiguity delta <= 1.0)\n    +- Phase 1: Scope and baseline checks\n    +- Phase 2: Overlay alignment\n    +- Phase 3: Findings-first analysis\n    +- Phase 4: Output contract and next action\n```\n\n### Resource Domains\n\nThe router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/`, then applies weighted intent scoring.\n\nKnowledge is organized by domain mapping:\n\n```text\nreferences/review_core.md\nreferences/review_ux_single_pass.md\nreferences/*_checklist.md\nassets/review/...\n```\n\n- `references/review_core.md` for shared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n- `references/review_ux_single_pass.md` for interactive single-pass review behavior.\n- `references/` for baseline review flow, severity contracts, and risk checklists.\n- `assets/` for optional reusable templates/checklists (if present in this skill).\n\n### Resource Loading Levels\n\n| Level | When to Load | Resources |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| ALWAYS | Every invocation, including security/correctness reviews | `references/review_core.md`, `references/review_ux_single_pass.md`, `references/security_checklist.md`, `references/code_quality_checklist.md`, `references/fix-completeness-checklist.md` |\n| CONDITIONAL | Intent score indicates need | `references/solid_checklist.md`, `references/code_quality_checklist.md`, `references/removal_plan.md`, `references/test_quality_checklist.md` |\n| ON_DEMAND | Explicit deep-dive request | Full mapped reference set |\n\n### Precedence Matrix\n\n| Rule Type | Source of Truth | Behavior |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Security/correctness minimums | `sk-code-review` baseline | Always enforced; never relaxed by surface guidance |\n| Surface style/process conventions | `sk-code` detected surface | Surface guidance overrides baseline generic style/process advice |\n| Verification/build/test commands | `sk-code` detected surface | Surface commands are authoritative for the detected surface |\n| Ambiguous conflicts | Escalation | Ask for clarification; do not guess |\n\n### Unknown Fallback Checklist\n\nIf intent/stack detection is unclear, request:\n\n1. Review target scope (full diff, staged files, commit range, or explicit file list).\n2. Primary risk class (security, correctness, performance, maintainability).\n3. Architecture lens priority (KISS/DRY/SOLID strict or optional).\n4. Stack/context (system code, web/frontend, or other/full-stack).\n5. Desired output mode (findings-only or findings + gated fix follow-up).\n\n### Smart Router Pseudocode\n\n```python\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nSKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n# Discover resources recursively across references and assets.\nRESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\nDEFAULT_RESOURCES = [\n    \"references/review_core.md\",\n    \"references/review_ux_single_pass.md\",\n    \"references/security_checklist.md\",\n    \"references/code_quality_checklist.md\",\n    \"references/fix-completeness-checklist.md\",\n]\n\nINTENT_SIGNALS = {\n    \"SECURITY\": {\"weight\": 5, \"keywords\": [\"security\", \"auth\", \"injection\", \"vulnerability\", \"race\"]},\n    \"QUALITY\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"correctness\", \"bug\", \"regression\", \"performance\", \"boundary\", \"contract\", \"breaking change\", \"backward compatible\", \"compatibility\"]},\n    \"KISS\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"kiss\", \"simple\", \"simplicity\", \"over-engineer\", \"overengineering\"]},\n    \"DRY\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"dry\", \"duplication\", \"duplicate\", \"copy-paste\", \"repeated logic\"]},\n    \"SOLID\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"solid\", \"architecture\", \"design\", \"coupling\", \"cohesion\", \"module\", \"adapter\", \"interface\", \"abstraction\", \"responsibility\", \"dependency\", \"boundary\"]},\n    \"REMOVAL\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"remove\", \"dead code\", \"cleanup\", \"deprecate\"]},\n    \"TESTING\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"test\", \"tests\", \"testing\", \"coverage\", \"assertion\", \"mock\", \"stub\", \"fixture\", \"test quality\", \"brittle\"]},\n}\n\nRESOURCE_MAP = {\n    \"SECURITY\": [\"references/security_checklist.md\"],\n    \"QUALITY\": [\"references/code_quality_checklist.md\"],\n    \"KISS\": [\"references/code_quality_checklist.md\"],\n    \"DRY\": [\"references/code_quality_checklist.md\"],\n    \"SOLID\": [\"references/solid_checklist.md\"],\n    \"REMOVAL\": [\"references/removal_plan.md\"],\n    \"TESTING\": [\"references/test_quality_checklist.md\"],\n}\n\nON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS = [\"deep review\", \"full review\", \"all checks\", \"comprehensive\", \"flag false positives\", \"blocking regressions\", \"list findings\", \"read-only only\", \"underrepresented\", \"scope correctly\"]\nUNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n    \"Confirm review scope (diff/staged/files/commit range)\",\n    \"Confirm risk priority (security/correctness/performance/maintainability/test quality/contract safety)\",\n    \"Confirm architecture lens (KISS/DRY/SOLID required or optional)\",\n    \"Confirm stack context (system-code/web/full-stack)\",\n    \"Confirm findings-only vs findings+fix follow-up\",\n]\n\ndef _task_text(task) -> str:\n    return \" \".join([\n        str(getattr(task, \"text\", \"\")),\n        str(getattr(task, \"query\", \"\")),\n        str(getattr(task, \"description\", \"\")),\n        \" \".join(getattr(task, \"keywords\", []) or []),\n    ]).lower()\n\ndef _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n    resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n    resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n    if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n        raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n    return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n\ndef discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n    docs = []\n    for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n        if base.exists():\n            docs.extend(path for path in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if path.is_file())\n    return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n\ndef score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:\n    text = _task_text(task)\n    scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n    for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n        for keyword in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n            if keyword in text:\n                scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n    return scores\n\ndef select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:\n    ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n    if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:\n        return [\"QUALITY\"]\n    selected = [ranked[0][0]]\n    if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:\n        selected.append(ranked[1][0])\n    return selected[:max_intents]\n\ndef detect_surface_evidence(task, workspace_files=None, changed_files=None) -> str:\n    text = _task_text(task)\n    files = \" \".join((workspace_files or []) + (changed_files or [])).lower()\n\n    if \".opencode/\" in files or \"jsonc\" in text or \"mcp\" in text:\n        return \"sk-code:<surface>\"\n    if any(term in text for term in [\"frontend\", \"web\", \"css\", \"dom\", \"browser\"]) or any(\n        marker in files for marker in [\"next.config\", \"vite.config\", \"package.json\", \"src/\"]\n    ):\n        return \"sk-code:<surface>\"\n    return \"sk-code:<surface>\"\n\ndef route_review_resources(task, workspace_files=None, changed_files=None):\n    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n    text = _task_text(task)\n    scores = score_intents(task)\n    intents = select_intents(scores, ambiguity_delta=1.0)\n\n    loaded = []\n    seen = set()\n\n    def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n        guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n        if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n            load(guarded)\n            loaded.append(guarded)\n            seen.add(guarded)\n\n    for relative_path in DEFAULT_RESOURCES:\n        load_if_available(relative_path)\n\n    if sum(scores.values()) < 0.5:\n        return {\n            \"intents\": [\"QUALITY\"],\n            \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n            \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n            \"surface_evidence\": detect_surface_evidence(task, workspace_files, changed_files),\n            \"resources\": loaded,\n        }\n\n    for intent in intents:\n        for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n            load_if_available(relative_path)\n\n    if any(keyword in text for keyword in ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS):\n        for paths in RESOURCE_MAP.values():\n            for relative_path in paths:\n                load_if_available(relative_path)\n\n    surface_evidence = detect_surface_evidence(task, workspace_files, changed_files)\n\n    precedence = {\n        \"baseline_minimums\": [\"security\", \"correctness\"],\n        \"surface_overrides\": [\"style\", \"build\", \"test_commands\", \"surface_process\"],\n        \"on_conflict\": \"escalate\",\n    }\n\n    return {\n        \"intents\": intents,\n        \"scores\": scores,\n        \"surface_evidence\": surface_evidence,\n        \"precedence\": precedence,\n        \"resources\": loaded,\n    }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### Phase 1: Scope and Baseline\n\n1. Inspect the review target (`git diff`, staged diff, file list, or commit range).\n2. Load baseline standards from this skill (`sk-code-review`).\n3. Load `sk-code` surface standards evidence when a surface is detected.\n\n### Phase 2: Surface Alignment\n\n1. Load standards from `sk-code` for the detected surface only.\n2. Apply precedence matrix:\n   - Baseline security/correctness minimums always apply.\n   - Surface style/process/verification conventions win on conflicts.\n3. If precedence cannot be resolved deterministically, escalate before scoring.\n\n### Phase 3: Findings-First Analysis\n\n1. Analyze for security and correctness first.\n2. Analyze quality/performance, test adequacy, contract safety, and architecture concerns.\n3. Analyze KISS/DRY and SOLID violations (SRP/OCP/LSP/ISP/DIP) with evidence.\n4. Analyze removal opportunities with safe-now vs deferred classification.\n5. Produce findings ordered by severity (`P0`, `P1`, `P2`).\n6. For every actionable finding, classify fix scope as `instance-only`, `class-of-bug`, `cross-consumer`, `algorithmic`, `matrix/evidence`, or `test-isolation`. If unknown, default to class/cross-consumer until a producer/consumer inventory proves instance-only.\n\n#### Instance-Only Opt-Out\n\nA finding may use the narrow fix path only when all are true:\n\n- It is not P0/P1 security, path, auth/authz, sandboxing, env precedence, schema, persistence, or public-response behavior.\n- `rg` proves no same-class producer or consumer.\n- Verification is local and cheap: one focused test, one doc row, or one static audit command.\n- The fix response includes the exact command evidence for the opt-out.\n\nOtherwise, run the full fix completeness checklist.\n\n### Phase 4: Output and Next Action\n\nRequired output contract:\n\n```markdown\n## Code Review Summary\n\n**Files reviewed**: X files, Y lines changed\n**Overall assessment**: [APPROVE / REQUEST_CHANGES / COMMENT]\n**Baseline used**: [sk-code (`sk-code-review`)]\n**Surface evidence used**: [sk-code:<surface>]\n\n## Findings\n\n### P0 - Critical\n1. [path:line] Title\n   - Risk\n   - User impact\n   - Finding class: [instance-only | class-of-bug | cross-consumer | algorithmic | matrix/evidence | test-isolation]\n   - Scope proof: [grep/test evidence proving class coverage or instance-only status]\n   - affectedSurfaceHints: [optional string array of short producer/consumer surface names; recommended for actionable findings, required for cross-consumer findings]\n   - Recommended fix\n\n### P1 - High\n...\n\n## Removal/Iteration Plan\n\n## Next Steps\n```\n\nAfter reporting findings, request explicit next action before any implementation follow-up.\n\n### Final-line exact-string contract (MANDATORY)\n\nEvery review MUST end with exactly one of the following plain-text lines as the **absolute final line** of the output (no trailing whitespace, no variation):\n\n```\nReview status: APPROVED\n```\n\n```\nReview status: REQUESTED_CHANGES\n```\n\n```\nReview status: COMMENTED\n```\n\n**Example output bottom:**\n\n```\n...\n## Next Steps\n1. Fix the null-deref at src/foo.ts:42\n2. Add input validation for the `/api/bar` endpoint\n\nReview status: REQUESTED_CHANGES\n```\n\nDownstream automation parses this final line via exact string match — do not vary the format, add trailing punctuation, or wrap in Markdown formatting.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ✅ ALWAYS\n\n- Keep findings first; summaries follow findings.\n- Enforce baseline security/correctness minimums regardless of surface.\n- Include file:line evidence for actionable findings.\n- State assumptions when evidence is incomplete.\n- Identify `sk-code` surface evidence used for standards alignment.\n\n### ❌ NEVER\n\n- Override surface-specific conventions with generic baseline style preferences.\n- Approve code with unaddressed P0 security/correctness defects.\n- Produce vague findings without concrete evidence.\n- Mix unrelated cleanup into targeted fix recommendations.\n- Do not implement fixes during review. Report findings only; implementation is a separate follow-up step.\n\n### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n\n- Surface detection is ambiguous and affects standards or verification commands.\n- Baseline and surface guidance conflict in a non-deterministic way.\n- Large diff size prevents reliable severity assignment without narrowed scope.\n- Requested remediation exceeds review scope and becomes architecture redesign.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n### Core References\n\n- [review_core.md](./references/review_core.md) - Shared review doctrine: severity model, evidence rules, precedence, and finding schema.\n- [review_ux_single_pass.md](./references/review_ux_single_pass.md) - Interactive single-pass review flow, presentation modes, and PR/pre-commit behavior.\n- [quick_reference.md](./references/quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index for routing between shared doctrine and single-pass UX guidance.\n- [security_checklist.md](./references/security_checklist.md) - Mandatory security and reliability checks.\n- [code_quality_checklist.md](./references/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, performance, KISS, and DRY checks.\n- [solid_checklist.md](./references/solid_checklist.md) - SOLID (SRP/OCP/LSP/ISP/DIP) and architecture assessment prompts.\n- [removal_plan.md](./references/removal_plan.md) - Safe-now vs deferred removal planning template.\n- [test_quality_checklist.md](./references/test_quality_checklist.md) - Test quality, coverage, and anti-pattern detection.\n\n### Reference Loading Notes\n\n- Load only the references needed for the selected intents.\n- Keep Section 2 (`SMART ROUTING`) as the authoritative routing source.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- Review output is findings-first and severity-ordered.\n- `sk-code-review` baseline + `sk-code` surface evidence contract is explicit in report context.\n- Security/correctness minimums are always covered.\n- Recommended fixes are actionable and scope-proportional.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n- Primary review baseline for `@review` agents in `.opencode/agents/review.md`.\n- Referenced by review-dispatch steps in `spec_kit` and `create` command YAML workflows.\n- Complements, but does not replace, `sk-code` surface-specific standards evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n\nThe router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/quick_reference.md`, `references/review_core.md`, `references/code_quality_checklist.md`, `references/fix-completeness-checklist.md`, `references/removal_plan.md`, `references/review_ux_single_pass.md`, `references/security_checklist.md`, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n\n### Manual Testing Playbook\n\nManual testing scenarios for this skill live in `manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md` (root index) plus 18 per-feature sub-files under `manual_testing_playbook/<NN>--<topic>/<NNN>-<scenario>.md`. Run scenarios via `bash .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md` for structural validation; execute scenarios in opencode/Claude/Codex sessions for behavioral verification.\n\n---\n\n## 9. PR-STATE EFFICIENCY GATES (Packet 110)\n\n### 9.1 M-1: PR-State Content-Hash Dedup\n\nPrevents redundant re-reviews when a PR has not changed since the last review.\n\n**Signature computation:**\n```\ndiff_content_hash = sha256(git diff <base-ref>...HEAD)\nsignature         = sha256(commit_subject + \"\\u001f\" + diff_content_hash)\n```\nWhere `commit_subject` is the first line of `git log <base-ref>...HEAD --format=%s` (latest commit subject).\n\n**Cache storage:**\n- Path: `.opencode/.sk-code-review-cache/<repo-ref>.jsonl`\n- `<repo-ref>` is computed as `sha256(git remote get-url origin).slice(0, 12)`\n- Each line is a JSON object: `{\"signature\": \"<sha256-hex>\", \"timestamp\": \"<ISO-8601>\", \"prev_sha\": \"<commit-sha>\"}`\n- Retention: keep last **100 entries** per repo-ref, prune older entries on write\n\n**Skip behavior:**\nWhen the current signature matches a prior cache entry, the review emits:\n```\nReview status: COMMENTED (no changes since last review at <prev_sha>)\n```\nNo full review analysis runs. Automation may treat `COMMENTED` as a pass (no new findings).\n\n**Cache write:** After each full review completes, write the current signature + timestamp + HEAD SHA to the cache file.\n\n### 9.2 M-2: Opt-In Minimum Evidence Gate\n\nSkips full review for trivially small diffs to save compute, with a conservative taxonomy that **never skips** high-risk changes.\n\n**Enable gate:**\n```bash\nexport SK_CODE_REVIEW_MIN_CHANGED_LINES=50  # >0 enables; default 0 = disabled\n```\n\n**Changed-line counting command:**\n```bash\ngit diff --numstat <base-ref>...HEAD | awk '{added+=$1; removed+=$2} END {print added+removed}'\n```\n\n**Conservative skip taxonomy — NEVER skip when diff touches:**\n\n| Risk Class | Path/File Patterns | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Security / Authentication / Authorization | `auth*`, `*-auth-*`, `*permission*`, `*credential*`, `*token*`, `*secret*`, `*oauth*`, `*sso*`, `*login*`, `*session*` | Compromised auth defeats everything |\n| Config files | `*.config.*`, `*config*.json`, `*config*.yaml`, `*config*.toml`, `*.env*`, `*.ini`, `*.cfg` | One-line config change can break production |\n| Persistence | `*.sql`, `*migration*`, `*schema*`, `*db*.ts`, `*repository*`, paths under `/db/` or `/migrations/` | Schema changes risk data loss |\n| Dependency manifests | `package.json`, `package-lock.json`, `Cargo.toml`, `Cargo.lock`, `pyproject.toml`, `poetry.lock`, `requirements.txt`, `*.lock`, `Gemfile`, `Gemfile.lock` | Transitive dependency changes are high-risk |\n| Sandboxing / Subprocess | `*sandbox*`, `*subprocess*`, `*exec*`, `*spawn*`, `*eval*` | Arbitrary code execution boundaries |\n| Public-facing responses | `*.handler.ts`, `*-api*`, `*-route*`, `*-controller*`, paths under `/handlers/`, `/routes/`, `/api/` | User-visible behavior changes |\n\n**Skip behavior:**\nWhen `SK_CODE_REVIEW_MIN_CHANGED_LINES > 0`, total changed lines < threshold, AND no sensitive paths are touched:\n```\nReview status: COMMENTED (skipped: diff below evidence threshold of N lines, no sensitive paths touched)\n```\nIf sensitive paths ARE touched, the full review runs regardless of line count.\n\n**Gate is ALWAYS opt-in.** Without `SK_CODE_REVIEW_MIN_CHANGED_LINES` set, M-2 has zero effect — all diffs receive full reviews.\n\n---\n\n## 10. REFERENCES: EFFICIENCY GATES\n\n- [pr_state_dedup.md](./references/pr_state_dedup.md) — Detailed M-1 signature scheme, cache format, and retention rules.\n\nRelated skills: `sk-doc` for skill authoring and packaging standards, `sk-code` for surface-aware standards, and `system-spec-kit` for packet-governed review workflows.\n\nBase directory for this skill: file:///Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review\nRelative paths in this skill (e.g., scripts/, reference/) are relative to this base directory.\nNote: file list is sampled.\n\n<skill_files>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/04--scope-and-precedence/test-code-review.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/04--scope-and-precedence/baseline-vs-surface-precedence.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/04--scope-and-precedence/explicit-scope-security-only.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/03--severity-and-evidence-discipline/class-of-bug-vs-instance-only.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/03--severity-and-evidence-discipline/cross-consumer-affected-surface.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/03--severity-and-evidence-discipline/p0-blocker-with-file-line.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/02--security-and-correctness-minimums/secrets-and-hardcoded-creds.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/02--security-and-correctness-minimums/input-validation-injection.md</file>\n<file>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/02--security-and-correctness-minimums/security-sensitive-auth.md</file>\n</skill_files>\n</skill_content>","metadata":{"name":"sk-code-review","dir":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review","truncated":false},"title":"Loaded skill: sk-code-review","time":{"start":1780928476216,"end":1780928476246}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0465ee379f89142c016a26cfdbe108819796909ca1efc64019"}},"id":"prt_ea79bf3270015ErafVrgzN7vrz","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79be968001h2296dX2d7WOLP"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780928476669,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"id":"prt_ea79bf5fa001IyncdeH7rjW5n8","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"5e467b51f30f9e12f69f9c7e526096759f81a05a","messageID":"msg_ea79be968001h2296dX2d7WOLP","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":34798,"input":3035,"output":19,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":31744}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780928483222,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"id":"prt_ea79c0f8e001NLwqyE3u7Y1TAD","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","snapshot":"0b851cb9d9c00a5bc51683b73e6ef2a1346bfdf0","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928491760,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ejutLJaKVPQ6BRbQ11t3QKOr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: /**\n2:  * db.ts — Global long-term memory (learned insights, patterns, preferences)\n3:  * Replaces skills/learned/*.md with structured SQLite + FTS5.\n4:  */\n5: import type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\n6: import { existsSync, mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from \"fs\";\n7: import { join } from \"path\";\n8: import { normalizeKey } from \"./dedup.js\";\n9: import { getDb, DB_PATH, configure as configureDb } from \"./shared-db.js\";\n10: import { enqueueEmbedding } from \"./queue/index.js\";\n11: import { notifyLtm, notifyMemoryAdded } from \"./events/index.js\";\n12: import { scrubSecrets } from \"./secretsScrubber.js\";\n13: import { insertProvenance, insertAudit, snapshotMemory, listProvenanceBatch } from \"./dao/provenanceAudit.js\";\n14: import type { ProvenanceSourceType } from \"./dao/types.js\";\n15: import type { LtmCoreConfig } from \"./adapterTypes.js\";\n16: import { tmpdir } from \"os\";\n17: \n18: export { DB_PATH };\n19: /** Adapters can override via configureDocs() or LtmCoreConfig.docsDir. */\n20: let DOCS_DIR = join(tmpdir(), \"ltm-docs\");\n21: \n22: export function configureDocs(dir: string): void { DOCS_DIR = dir; }\n23: \n24: export function configureCore(config: LtmCoreConfig): void {\n25:   configureDb(config);\n26:   if (config.docsDir) DOCS_DIR = config.docsDir;\n27: }\n28: \n29: export type MemoryCategory = \"preference\" | \"architecture\" | \"gotcha\" | \"pattern\" | \"workflow\" | \"constraint\";\n30: export type RelationshipType = \"supports\" | \"contradicts\" | \"refines\" | \"depends_on\" | \"related_to\" | \"supersedes\";\n31: \n32: export interface Memory {\n33:   id: number;\n34:   content: string;\n35:   category: MemoryCategory;\n36:   importance: number;\n37:   confidence: number;\n38:   source: string | null;\n39:   project_scope: string | null;\n40:   dedup_key: string | null;\n41:   created_at: string;\n42:   last_confirmed_at: string;\n43:   last_used_at: string;\n44:   confirm_count: number;\n45:   status: \"active\" | \"pending\" | \"deprecated\" | \"superseded\";\n46:   first_recalled_at?: string;\n47:   last_recalled_at?: string;\n48:   recall_count?: number;\n49:   superseded_by?: number;\n50:   superseded_at?: string;\n51:   workspace_id?: string;\n52:   agent_id?: string;\n53:   decay_score?: number;\n54: }\n55: \n56: export interface MemoryRelation {\n57:   id: number;\n58:   source_memory_id: number;\n59:   target_memory_id: number;\n60:   relationship_type: RelationshipType;\n61:   created_at: string;\n62: }\n63: \n64: export interface MemoryWithRelations extends Memory {\n65:   tags: string[];\n66:   relations: Array<{ memory: Memory; relationship_type: RelationshipType; direction: \"outgoing\" | \"incoming\" }>;\n67:   /** Populated only when recall({ includeProvenance: true }) is requested. */\n68:   provenance?: import(\"./dao/types.js\").ProvenanceRow[];\n69:   /** Score breakdown + temperature — always populated by recall(). */\n70:   explainer?: import(\"./recall/explainer.js\").RecallExplainer;\n71: }\n72: \n73: export interface LearnInput {\n74:   content: string;\n75:   /** Short human-readable label (≤60 chars). Agent-supplied; falls back to heuristic. */\n76:   title?: string;\n77:   category: MemoryCategory;\n78:   importance?: number;\n79:   confidence?: number;\n80:   source?: string;\n81:   project_scope?: string;\n82:   workspace_id?: string;\n83:   agent_id?: string;\n84:   tags?: string[];\n85:   relate_to?: Array<{ id: number; relationship_type: RelationshipType }>;\n86:   /** Skip regenerating docs/memory-long-term.md (use during bulk imports) */\n87:   skipExport?: boolean;\n88:   /** Audit/provenance — all optional; safe to omit from existing callers. */\n89:   actor?: string;\n90:   sessionId?: string;\n91:   provenanceSourceType?: ProvenanceSourceType;\n92:   provenanceSourceRef?: string;\n93:   provenanceMetadata?: string;\n94: }\n95: \n96: export interface LearnResult {\n97:   action: \"created\" | \"reinforced\";\n98:   id: number;\n99:   confirm_count: number;\n100: }\n101: \n102: export interface RecallInput {\n103:   since?: string;\n104:   until?: string;\n105:   sort_by?: \"relevance\" | \"created\" | \"last_recalled\" | \"recall_count\";\n106: \n107:   query?: string;\n108:   tags?: string[];\n109:   category?: MemoryCategory;\n110:   project?: string;\n111:   limit?: number;\n112:   workspace_id?: string;\n113:   agent_id?: string;\n114:   /** When true, each result includes a `provenance` array. Off by default to preserve latency. */\n115:   includeProvenance?: boolean;\n116: }\n117: \n118: \n119: /** Derive a short title from content when none is agent-supplied. */\n120: export function deriveTitle(content: string): string {\n121:   const trimmed = content.trim();\n122:   const dot = trimmed.indexOf('.');\n123:   const nl = trimmed.indexOf('\\n');\n124:   const boundary = [dot, nl].filter(i => i > 1 && i <= 60).sort((a, b) => a - b)[0];\n125:   if (boundary !== undefined) return trimmed.slice(0, boundary).trim();\n126:   if (trimmed.length <= 60) return trimmed;\n127:   const cut = trimmed.slice(0, 57);\n128:   const lastSpace = cut.lastIndexOf(' ');\n129:   return (lastSpace > 20 ? cut.slice(0, lastSpace) : cut) + '…';\n130: }\n131: \n132: function tryAudit(fn: () => void): void {\n133:   try { fn(); } catch (e) { process.stderr.write(`[audit] write failed: ${e}\\n`); }\n134: }\n135: \n136: function upsertTag(db: Database, name: string): number {\n137:   db.run(`INSERT OR IGNORE INTO tags (name) VALUES (?)`, [name]);\n138:   return db.query<{ id: number }, [string]>(`SELECT id FROM tags WHERE name=?`).get(name)!.id;\n139: }\n140: \n141: function attachTags(db: Database, memoryId: number, tags: string[]): void {\n142:   for (const tag of tags) {\n143:     const tagId = upsertTag(db, tag.toLowerCase().trim());\n144:     db.run(`INSERT OR IGNORE INTO memory_tags (memory_id, tag_id) VALUES (?, ?)`, [memoryId, tagId]);\n145:   }\n146: }\n147: \n148: /** Fetch tags for a single memory — used in recall() results. */\n149: function getTagsForMemory(db: Database, memoryId: number): string[] {\n150:   return db.query<{ name: string }, [number]>(\n151:     `SELECT t.name FROM tags t JOIN memory_tags mt ON t.id=mt.tag_id WHERE mt.memory_id=?`\n152:   ).all(memoryId).map(r => r.name);\n153: }\n154: \n155: /** Batch-fetch tags for many memories — used in exportMarkdown to avoid N+1. */\n156: function getTagsBatch(db: Database, ids: number[]): Map<number, string[]> {\n157:   if (ids.length === 0) return new Map();\n158:   const placeholders = ids.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n159:   const rows = db.query<{ memory_id: number; name: string }, number[]>(\n160:     `SELECT mt.memory_id, t.name FROM memory_tags mt JOIN tags t ON t.id=mt.tag_id\n161:      WHERE mt.memory_id IN (${placeholders})`\n162:   ).all(...ids);\n163:   const result = new Map<number, string[]>();\n164:   for (const r of rows) {\n165:     if (!result.has(r.memory_id)) result.set(r.memory_id, []);\n166:     result.get(r.memory_id)!.push(r.name);\n167:   }\n168:   return result;\n169: }\n170: \n171: function getRelationsForMemory(db: Database, memoryId: number): MemoryWithRelations[\"relations\"] {\n172:   const outgoing = db.query<{ target_memory_id: number; relationship_type: string }, [number]>(\n173:     `SELECT target_memory_id, relationship_type FROM memory_relations WHERE source_memory_id=?`\n174:   ).all(memoryId);\n175: \n176:   const incoming = db.query<{ source_memory_id: number; relationship_type: string }, [number]>(\n177:     `SELECT source_memory_id, relationship_type FROM memory_relations WHERE target_memory_id=?`\n178:   ).all(memoryId);\n179: \n180:   const results: MemoryWithRelations[\"relations\"] = [];\n181: \n182:   for (const r of outgoing) {\n183:     const mem = db.query<Memory, [number]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(r.target_memory_id);\n184:     if (mem) results.push({ memory: mem, relationship_type: r.relationship_type as RelationshipType, direction: \"outgoing\" });\n185:   }\n186:   for (const r of incoming) {\n187:     const mem = db.query<Memory, [number]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(r.source_memory_id);\n188:     if (mem) results.push({ memory: mem, relationship_type: r.relationship_type as RelationshipType, direction: \"incoming\" });\n189:   }\n190: \n191:   return results;\n192: }\n193: \n194: function enrichMemory(db: Database, mem: Memory): MemoryWithRelations {\n195:   return { ...mem, tags: getTagsForMemory(db, mem.id), relations: getRelationsForMemory(db, mem.id) };\n196: }\n197: \n198: // --- Decay / relevance scoring ---\n199: \n200: /** Half-life in days by importance level. Infinity = never decays. */\n201: const HALF_LIVES: Record<number, number> = {\n202:   5: Infinity,\n203:   4: 180,\n204:   3: 90,\n205:   2: 30,\n206:   1: 14,\n207: };\n208: \n209: /** Memories below this score are soft-deprecated (not deleted). */\n210: const DEPRECATION_THRESHOLD = 0.25;\n211: \n212: /**\n213:  * Compute effective relevance score.\n214:  * score = importance × confidence × decay\n215:  * decay = 0.5 ^ (days_since / half_life)  (1.0 for importance=5)\n216:  */\n217: export function computeDecayScore(memory: Memory): number {\n218:   const halfLife = HALF_LIVES[memory.importance] ?? 90;\n219:   if (halfLife === Infinity) {\n220:     return memory.importance * memory.confidence;\n221:   }\n222:   const latestTs = [memory.last_used_at, memory.last_confirmed_at, memory.created_at]\n223:     .map(t => new Date(t).getTime())\n224:     .reduce((a, b) => Math.max(a, b), 0);\n225:   const daysSince = (Date.now() - latestTs) / 86_400_000;\n226:   const decay = Math.pow(0.5, daysSince / halfLife);\n227:   return memory.importance * memory.confidence * decay;\n228: }\n229: \n230: /** Update last_used_at for a batch of memory IDs. */\n231: export function updateLastUsed(ids: number[]): void {\n232:   if (ids.length === 0) return;\n233:   const db = getDb();\n234:   const placeholders = ids.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n235:   db.run(\n236:     `UPDATE memories SET last_used_at = datetime('now') WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n237:     ids\n238:   );\n239: }\n240: \n241: export interface DecayResult {\n242:   deprecated: number;\n243:   scored: number;\n244: }\n245: \n246: /**\n247:  * Compute decay scores for all active memories. Deprecate those below threshold.\n248:  * Protection: importance=5 OR confirm_count>=5 are never deprecated.\n249:  */\n250: export function decayMemories(): DecayResult {\n251:   const db = getDb();\n252: \n253:   const rows = db.query<Memory, []>(\n254:     `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE status = 'active'`\n255:   ).all();\n256: \n257:   const toDeprecate = rows\n258:     .filter(mem => mem.importance !== 5 && mem.confirm_count < 5)\n259:     .filter(mem => computeDecayScore(mem) < DEPRECATION_THRESHOLD)\n260:     .map(mem => mem.id);\n261: \n262:   if (toDeprecate.length > 0) {\n263:     const placeholders = toDeprecate.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n264:     db.run(\n265:       `UPDATE memories SET status = 'deprecated' WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n266:       toDeprecate\n267:     );\n268:   }\n269: \n270:   return { deprecated: toDeprecate.length, scored: rows.length };\n271: }\n272: \n273: // Auto-relation detection — called fire-and-forget from learn()\n274: async function autoDetectRelations(\n275:   newId: number,\n276:   content: string,\n277:   getSimilarMemories: (text: string, topN: number, threshold: number) => Promise<Array<{ id: number; content: string; similarity: number }>>,\n278:   classifyRelation: (a: string, b: string) => Promise<RelationshipType | null>,\n279: ): Promise<void> {\n280:   try {\n281:     const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n282:     if (readConfigSync().ltm?.autoRelate === false) return;\n283: \n284:     const candidates = await getSimilarMemories(content, 5, 0.6);\n285:     const others = candidates.filter(c => c.id !== newId);\n286:     if (!others.length) return;\n287: \n288:     await Promise.allSettled(\n289:       others.map(async (candidate) => {\n290:         const relType = await classifyRelation(content, candidate.content);\n291:         if (!relType) return;\n292:         try {\n293:           relate({ source_id: newId, target_id: candidate.id, relationship_type: relType });\n294:         } catch {\n295:           // Memory may have been deleted between detection and insertion — ignore\n296:         }\n297:       })\n298:     );\n299:   } catch (err) {\n300:     process.stderr.write(`[autoDetectRelations] error for memory ${newId}: ${err}\\n`);\n301:   }\n302: }\n303: \n304: export function learn(input: LearnInput): LearnResult {\n305:   const db = getDb();\n306: \n307:   // Scrub secrets before any DB write or dedup check\n308:   const { scrubbed, redactions } = scrubSecrets(input.content);\n309:   if (redactions.length > 0) {\n310:     process.stderr.write(`[learn] Scrubbed ${redactions.length} secret(s): ${redactions.join(\", \")}\\n`);\n311:   }\n312:   const content = scrubbed;\n313: \n314:   const dedupKey = normalizeKey(content);\n315:   const skipExport = input.skipExport ?? false;\n316: \n317:   const existing = db.query<Memory, [string]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE dedup_key=?`).get(dedupKey);\n318: \n319:   const actor = input.actor ?? \"mcp:ltm_learn\";\n320: \n321:   if (existing) {\n322:     const beforeSnap = snapshotMemory(db, existing.id);\n323:     db.run(\n324:       `UPDATE memories SET confirm_count=confirm_count+1, last_confirmed_at=datetime('now'),\n325:        confidence=MIN(1.0, confidence+0.05) WHERE id=?`,\n326:       [existing.id]\n327:     );\n328:     if (input.tags) attachTags(db, existing.id, input.tags);\n329:     if (input.relate_to) {\n330:       for (const rel of input.relate_to) {\n331:         relate({ source_id: existing.id, target_id: rel.id, relationship_type: rel.relationship_type });\n332:       }\n333:     }\n334:     tryAudit(() => {\n335:       const afterSnap = snapshotMemory(db, existing.id);\n336:       insertAudit(db, {\n337:         memory_id: existing.id, op: \"update\", actor,\n338:         session_id: input.sessionId,\n339:         before_json: beforeSnap ? JSON.stringify(beforeSnap) : null,\n340:         after_json: afterSnap ? JSON.stringify(afterSnap) : null,\n341:       });\n342:     });\n343:     if (!skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n344:     const updated = db.query<{ confirm_count: number }, [number]>(\n345:       `SELECT confirm_count FROM memories WHERE id=?`\n346:     ).get(existing.id);\n347:     return { action: \"reinforced\", id: existing.id, confirm_count: updated?.confirm_count ?? existing.confirm_count + 1 };\n348:   }\n349: \n350:   const title = input.title?.trim().slice(0, 60) || deriveTitle(content);\n351: \n352:   const result = db.run(\n353:     `INSERT INTO memories (content, title, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key, created_by)\n354:      VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)`,\n355:     [\n356:       content,\n357:       title,\n358:       input.category,\n359:       input.importance ?? 3,\n360:       input.confidence ?? 1.0,\n361:       input.source ?? null,\n362:       input.project_scope ?? null,\n363:       dedupKey,\n364:       actor,\n365:     ]\n366:   );\n367: \n368:   const newId = Number(result.lastInsertRowid);\n369: \n370:   if (input.tags) attachTags(db, newId, input.tags);\n371:   if (input.relate_to) {\n372:     for (const rel of input.relate_to) {\n373:       relate({ source_id: newId, target_id: rel.id, relationship_type: rel.relationship_type });\n374:     }\n375:   }\n376: \n377:   tryAudit(() => {\n378:     insertProvenance(db, {\n379:       memory_id: newId,\n380:       source_type: input.provenanceSourceType ?? \"learn\",\n381:       source_ref: input.provenanceSourceRef ?? input.sessionId ?? null,\n382:       actor,\n383:       metadata: input.provenanceMetadata ?? null,\n384:     });\n385:     const afterSnap = snapshotMemory(db, newId);\n386:     insertAudit(db, {\n387:       memory_id: newId, op: \"insert\", actor,\n388:       session_id: input.sessionId,\n389:       before_json: null,\n390:       after_json: afterSnap ? JSON.stringify(afterSnap) : null,\n391:     });\n392:   });\n393: \n394:   if (!skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n395: \n396:   // Embedding generation: prefer the durable Honker queue (a long-lived worker\n397:   // claims + embeds with retry/dead-letter — short-lived hooks just enqueue and\n398:   // exit). When no queue is available, embed inline as before. Auto-relate runs\n399:   // inline regardless: it embeds the query text fresh and compares against other\n400:   // memories' stored vectors, so it does not depend on this memory's own row.\n401:   const enqueuedJobId = enqueueEmbedding(newId);\n402:   import(\"./embeddings.js\").then(async ({ embedMemory, getSimilarMemories, classifyRelation }) => {\n403:     if (enqueuedJobId === null) await embedMemory(db, newId);\n404:     await autoDetectRelations(newId, content, getSimilarMemories, classifyRelation);\n405:   }).catch(err => process.stderr.write(`[learn] Background task failed for memory ${newId}: ${err}\\n`));\n406: \n407:   // Push a cross-process liveness event so any graph-app listener refreshes\n408:   // without waiting on the file-watcher. No-op when Honker is unavailable.\n409:   notifyLtm({ type: \"refresh\", reason: \"memory_created\", id: newId });\n410:   // Opt-in cross-agent sync: notify sibling processes of the new memory. No-op\n411:   // unless the ltm.crossProcessSync flag is on AND Honker is available.\n412:   notifyMemoryAdded({ id: newId, project_scope: input.project_scope ?? null });\n413: \n414:   return { action: \"created\", id: newId, confirm_count: 1 };\n415: }\n416: \n417: export async function recall(input: RecallInput = {}): Promise<MemoryWithRelations[]> {\n418:   const db = getDb();\n419:   const limit = input.limit ?? 10;\n420: \n421:   let ids: Set<number> | null = null;\n422:   const ftsRanks = new Map<number, number>();      // id → normalized [0,1]\n423:   const semanticScores = new Map<number, number>(); // id → cosine similarity [0,1]\n424: \n425:   if (input.query) {\n426:     // Sanitize for FTS5: quote each token (prevents reserved-word errors) and join with OR\n427:     const ftsQuery = input.query\n428:       .trim()\n429:       .split(/\\s+/)\n430:       .filter(Boolean)\n431:       .map(t => `\"${t.replace(/\"/g, '\"\"')}\"`)\n432:       .join(\" OR \");\n433:     const ftsResults = db.query<{ rowid: number; rank: number }, [string]>(\n434:       `SELECT rowid, rank FROM memories_fts WHERE memories_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50`\n435:     ).all(ftsQuery);\n436:     ids = new Set<number>();\n437:     for (const r of ftsResults) {\n438:       ids.add(r.rowid);\n439:       // FTS5 BM25 rank is a negative number (closer to 0 = better).\n440:       // Math.exp maps it to (0, 1] where 1 is a perfect match.\n441:       ftsRanks.set(r.rowid, Math.exp(r.rank));\n442:     }\n443: \n444:     // Semantic fallback: if FTS5 returned fewer results than requested, augment with vector search\n445:     if (ids.size < limit) {\n446:       const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n447:       const cfg = readConfigSync();\n448:       const semanticEnabled = cfg.ltm?.semanticFallback !== false; // default true\n449:       if (semanticEnabled) {\n450:         try {\n451:           const { getSimilarMemories } = await import(\"./embeddings.js\");\n452:           const semantic = await getSimilarMemories(input.query, limit * 2, 0.5);\n453:           for (const m of semantic) {\n454:             ids.add(m.id);\n455:             semanticScores.set(m.id, m.similarity);\n456:           }\n457:         } catch (err) {\n458:           process.stderr.write(`[recall] Semantic fallback failed: ${err}\\n`);\n459:         }\n460:       }\n461:     }\n462:   }\n463: \n464:   if (input.tags && input.tags.length > 0) {\n465:     const tagIds = input.tags.map(t => {\n466:       const row = db.query<{ id: number }, [string]>(`SELECT id FROM tags WHERE name=?`).get(t.toLowerCase());\n467:       return row?.id;\n468:     }).filter((id): id is number => id !== undefined);\n469: \n470:     if (tagIds.length > 0) {\n471:       const placeholders = tagIds.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n472:       const tagMemIds = db.query<{ memory_id: number }, number[]>(\n473:         `SELECT DISTINCT memory_id FROM memory_tags WHERE tag_id IN (${placeholders})`\n474:       ).all(...tagIds).map(r => r.memory_id);\n475: \n476:       const tagSet = new Set(tagMemIds);\n477:       ids = ids ? new Set([...ids].filter(id => tagSet.has(id))) : tagSet;\n478:     }\n479:   }\n480: \n481:   const conditions: string[] = [];\n482:   const params: (string | number | null)[] = [];\n483: \n484:   if (ids !== null) {\n485:     if (ids.size === 0) return [];\n486:     const placeholders = [...ids].map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n487:     conditions.push(`id IN (${placeholders})`);\n488:     params.push(...ids);\n489:   }\n490: \n491:   if (input.category) {\n492:     conditions.push(\"category=?\");\n493:     params.push(input.category);\n494:   }\n495: \n496:   if (input.project) {\n497:     conditions.push(\"(project_scope IS NULL OR project_scope=?)\");\n498:     params.push(input.project);\n499:   }\n500: \n501:   if (input.workspace_id) {\n502:     conditions.push(\"(workspace_id IS NULL OR workspace_id=?)\");\n503:     params.push(input.workspace_id);\n504:   }\n505:   if (input.agent_id) {\n506:     conditions.push(\"(agent_id IS NULL OR agent_id=?)\");\n507:     params.push(input.agent_id);\n508:   }\n509: \n510:   conditions.push(\"status = 'active'\");\n511: \n512:   if (input.since) {\n513:     conditions.push(\"(created_at > ? OR last_recalled_at > ?)\");\n514:     params.push(input.since, input.since);\n515:   }\n516:   if (input.until) {\n517:     conditions.push(\"(created_at < ? OR last_recalled_at < ?)\");\n518:     params.push(input.until, input.until);\n519:   }\n520: \n521:   const where = `WHERE ${conditions.join(\" AND \")}`;\n522:   // Explicit columns — excludes embedding blob (~260 KB/row) from hot recall path.\n523:   // Use getById(id, { withEmbedding: true }) when the blob is needed.\n524:   // default sort (no query): ORDER BY decay_score DESC pushed to SQL → O(log N)\n525:   const defaultSqlSort = (!input.sort_by || input.sort_by === \"relevance\") && ids === null;\n526:   const orderBy = defaultSqlSort ? \"ORDER BY decay_score DESC\" : \"\";\n527:   const rows = db.query<Memory, typeof params>(\n528:     `SELECT id, content, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key,\n529:             created_at, last_confirmed_at, last_used_at, confirm_count, status,\n530:             first_recalled_at, last_recalled_at, recall_count, superseded_by, superseded_at,\n531:             workspace_id, agent_id, decay_score\n532:      FROM memories ${where} ${orderBy} LIMIT ${limit}`\n533:   ).all(...params);\n534: \n535:   let sorted: typeof rows;\n536:   if (defaultSqlSort) {\n537:     sorted = rows; // already ordered by decay_score DESC in SQL\n538:   } else if (input.sort_by === \"created\") {\n539:     sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => new Date(b.created_at).getTime() - new Date(a.created_at).getTime());\n540:   } else if (input.sort_by === \"last_recalled\") {\n541:     sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => new Date(b.last_recalled_at ?? \"1970\").getTime() - new Date(a.last_recalled_at ?? \"1970\").getTime());\n542:   } else if (input.sort_by === \"recall_count\") {\n543:     sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => (b.recall_count ?? 0) - (a.recall_count ?? 0));\n544:   } else {\n545:     // FTS/semantic path: small result set (≤50), JS sort is O(k log k) — negligible.\n546:     // Use materialised decay_score if available, fall back to computing it.\n547:     sorted = rows\n548:       .map(m => ({ m, score: m.decay_score ?? computeDecayScore(m) }))\n549:       .sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)\n550:       .map(({ m }) => m);\n551:   }\n552:   if (sorted.length > 0) {\n553:     const placeholders = sorted.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n554:     db.run(\n555:       `UPDATE memories SET last_used_at = datetime('now'), last_recalled_at = datetime('now'),\n556:               recall_count = recall_count + 1,\n557:               first_recalled_at = COALESCE(first_recalled_at, datetime('now'))\n558:        WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n559:       sorted.map(m => m.id),\n560:     );\n561:   }\n562:   const enriched = sorted.map(m => enrichMemory(db, m));\n563:   if (input.includeProvenance) {\n564:     const provMap = listProvenanceBatch(db, enriched.map(m => m.id));\n565:     for (const m of enriched) {\n566:       m.provenance = provMap.get(m.id) ?? [];\n567:     }\n568:   }\n569: \n570:   // Attach explainer (pure function — no extra DB calls).\n571:   if (enriched.length > 0) {\n572:     const { buildExplainer } = await import(\"./recall/explainer.js\");\n573:     for (const m of enriched) {\n574:       m.explainer = buildExplainer({\n575:         importance: m.importance,\n576:         recall_count: m.recall_count ?? 0,\n577:         last_recalled_at: m.last_recalled_at,\n578:         ftsRank: ftsRanks.get(m.id) ?? null,\n579:         semanticScore: semanticScores.get(m.id) ?? null,\n580:       });\n581:     }\n582:   }\n583: \n584:   return enriched;\n585: }\n586: \n587: export function relate(input: {\n588:   source_id: number;\n589:   target_id: number;\n590:   relationship_type: RelationshipType;\n591: }): void {\n592:   const db = getDb();\n593:   if (!db.query<{ id: number }, [number]>(`SELECT id FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(input.source_id)) {\n594:     throw new Error(`Source memory ${input.source_id} not found`);\n595:   }\n596:   if (!db.query<{ id: number }, [number]>(`SELECT id FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(input.target_id)) {\n597:     throw new Error(`Target memory ${input.target_id} not found`);\n598:   }\n599:   db.run(\n600:     `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO memory_relations (source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n601:      VALUES (?, ?, ?)`,\n602:     [input.source_id, input.target_id, input.relationship_type]\n603:   );\n604: }\n605: \n606: export function forget(input: { id: number; reason?: string; skipExport?: boolean; actor?: string; sessionId?: string }): void {\n607:   const db = getDb();\n608:   const snap = snapshotMemory(db, input.id);\n609:   if (!snap) throw new Error(`Memory ${input.id} not found`);\n610:   db.run(`DELETE FROM memories WHERE id=?`, [input.id]);\n611:   tryAudit(() => insertAudit(db, {\n612:     memory_id: input.id,\n613:     op: \"forget\",\n614:     actor: input.actor ?? \"mcp:ltm_forget\",\n615:     session_id: input.sessionId,\n616:     before_json: JSON.stringify(snap),\n617:     after_json: null,\n618:   }));\n619:   if (!input.skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n620: }\n621: \n622: export function getSimilarMemories(\n623:   db: Database,\n624:   queryVec: Float32Array,\n625:   opts: { projectScope?: string; limit?: number; minImportance?: number }\n626: ): Memory[] {\n627:   const { projectScope, limit = 15, minImportance = 2 } = opts;\n628:   const { blobToVec, cosineSimilarity } = require(\"./embeddings.js\") as typeof import(\"./embeddings.js\");\n629: \n630:   let query: string;\n631:   let params: (string | number)[];\n632: \n633:   if (projectScope) {\n634:     query = `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE project_scope=? AND importance>=? AND embedding IS NOT NULL AND status='active' LIMIT ${limit * 3}`;\n635:     params = [projectScope, minImportance];\n636:   } else {\n637:     query = `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE project_scope IS NULL AND importance>=? AND embedding IS NOT NULL AND status='active' LIMIT ${limit * 3}`;\n638:     params = [minImportance];\n639:   }\n640: \n641:   const rows = db.query<Memory & { embedding: Buffer }, typeof params>(query).all(...params);\n642: \n643:   const scored = rows.map(row => {\n644:     const { embedding, ...mem } = row as Memory & { embedding: Buffer };\n645:     const sim = cosineSimilarity(queryVec, blobToVec(embedding));\n646:     return { mem, sim };\n647:   });\n648: \n649:   scored.sort((a, b) => b.sim - a.sim);\n650:   return scored.slice(0, limit).map(s => s.mem);\n651: }\n652: \n653: export function getContextMerge(project: string): { globals: Memory[]; scoped: Memory[] } {\n654:   const db = getDb();\n655:   const sortByDecay = (arr: Memory[]) =>\n656:     arr.map(m => ({ m, score: computeDecayScore(m) }))\n657:        .sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)\n658:        .map(({ m }) => m);\n659: \n660:   const SLIM = `id, content, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key,\n661:                created_at, last_confirmed_at, last_used_at, confirm_count, status,\n662:                first_recalled_at, last_recalled_at, recall_count, superseded_by, superseded_at,\n663:                workspace_id, agent_id`;\n664:   const globals = sortByDecay(db.query<Memory, []>(\n665:     `SELECT ${SLIM} FROM memories WHERE importance >= 4 AND project_scope IS NULL AND status = 'active'`\n666:   ).all());\n667: \n668:   const scoped = sortByDecay(db.query<Memory, [string]>(\n669:     `SELECT ${SLIM} FROM memories WHERE project_scope=? AND importance >= 3 AND status = 'active' LIMIT 15`\n670:   ).all(project));\n671: \n672:   const allIds = [...globals, ...scoped].map(m => m.id);\n673:   updateLastUsed(allIds);\n674: \n675:   return { globals, scoped };\n676: }\n677: \n678: /**\n679:  * Async variant: returns getContextMerge result plus graph insights block.\n680:  * Used by SessionStart hook when graphReasoning is enabled.\n681:  */\n682: export async function getContextMergeWithGraph(project: string): Promise<{ globals: Memory[]; scoped: Memory[]; graphInsights?: string }> {\n683:   const base = getContextMerge(project);\n684: \n685:   const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n686:   if (!readConfigSync().ltm?.graphReasoning) return base;\n687: \n688:   const seeds = [...base.globals.slice(0, 2), ...base.scoped.slice(0, 1)].map(m => m.id);\n689:   if (seeds.length === 0) return base;\n690: \n691:   try {\n692:     const { traverseGraph, buildReasoningContext } = await import(\"./graph.js\");\n693:     const results = await Promise.allSettled(seeds.map(id => traverseGraph(id, 2, false)));\n694:     const lines: string[] = [];\n695:     for (const r of results) {\n696:       if (r.status === \"fulfilled\") {\n697:         const block = buildReasoningContext(r.value);\n698:         if (block) lines.push(block);\n699:       }\n700:     }\n701:     const graphInsights = lines.slice(0, 5).join(\"\\n\") || undefined;\n702:     return { ...base, graphInsights };\n703:   } catch (err) {\n704:     process.stderr.write(`[getContextMergeWithGraph] error: ${err}\\n`);\n705:     return base;\n706:   }\n707: }\n708: \n709: /** Write docs/memory-long-term-dump.md — auto-generated snapshot (never overwrites the architecture doc). */\n710: export function exportMarkdown(): void {\n711:   const db = getDb();\n712:   if (!existsSync(DOCS_DIR)) mkdirSync(DOCS_DIR, { recursive: true });\n713: \n714:   const rows = db.query<Memory, []>(\n715:     `SELECT * FROM memories ORDER BY importance DESC, category ASC, created_at DESC LIMIT 500`\n716:   ).all();\n717: \n718:   // Batch-fetch all tags in one query to avoid N+1\n719:   const tagsByMemory = getTagsBatch(db, rows.map(r => r.id));\n720: \n721:   const timestamp = new Date().toISOString().replace(\"T\", \" \").replace(/\\..+/, \"\");\n722:   const lines: string[] = [\n723:     `# Long-Term Memory — Generated Dump`,\n724:     ``,\n725:     `> Auto-generated by \\`memory/db.ts\\`. Last updated: ${timestamp}`,\n726:     `> This is a raw data export. For the architecture guide see \\`docs/memory-long-term.md\\`.`,\n727:     `> Edit via \\`/learn\\`, \\`/forget\\`, \\`/relate\\` commands — do not edit directly.`,\n728:     ``,\n729:   ];\n730: \n731:   const byCategory = new Map<string, Memory[]>();\n732:   for (const m of rows) {\n733:     if (!byCategory.has(m.category)) byCategory.set(m.category, []);\n734:     byCategory.get(m.category)!.push(m);\n735:   }\n736: \n737:   for (const [cat, mems] of byCategory) {\n738:     lines.push(`## ${cat.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + cat.slice(1)}`);\n739:     lines.push(\"\");\n740:     for (const m of mems) {\n741:       const tags = tagsByMemory.get(m.id) ?? [];\n742:       const tagStr = tags.length > 0 ? ` \\`[${tags.join(\", \")}]\\`` : \"\";\n743:       const scope = m.project_scope ? ` *(${m.project_scope})*` : \"\";\n744:       const imp = \"★\".repeat(m.importance) + \"☆\".repeat(5 - m.importance);\n745:       lines.push(`- **[${m.id}]** ${m.content}${scope}${tagStr} ${imp} (conf: ${m.confidence.toFixed(2)}, confirmed: ${m.confirm_count}x)`);\n746:     }\n747:     lines.push(\"\");\n748:   }\n749: \n750:   if (rows.length === 0) {\n751:     lines.push(\"*No memories stored yet. Use `/learn` to add insights.*\");\n752:     lines.push(\"\");\n753:   }\n754: \n755:   writeFileSync(join(DOCS_DIR, \"memory-long-term-dump.md\"), lines.join(\"\\n\"));\n756: }\n757: \n758: /** Write docs/memory-graph.json — nodes + links for Force-Graph visualization. */\n759: export function exportGraphJson(): void {\n760:   const db = getDb();\n761:   if (!existsSync(DOCS_DIR)) mkdirSync(DOCS_DIR, { recursive: true });\n762: \n763:   const memories = db.query<Memory, []>(`SELECT * FROM memories`).all();\n764:   const relations = db.query<MemoryRelation, []>(`SELECT * FROM memory_relations`).all();\n765: \n766:   writeFileSync(join(DOCS_DIR, \"memory-graph.json\"), JSON.stringify({\n767:     nodes: memories.map(m => ({\n768:       id: m.id,\n769:       label: m.content.substring(0, 60),\n770:       category: m.category,\n771:       importance: m.importance,\n772:       project_scope: m.project_scope,\n773:     })),\n774:     links: relations.map(r => ({\n775:       source: r.source_memory_id,\n776:       target: r.target_memory_id,\n777:       type: r.relationship_type,\n778:     })),\n779:   }, null, 2));\n780: }\n\n(End of file - total 780 lines)\n</content>\n\n<system-reminder>\nInstructions from: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/AGENTS.md\n# OpenLTM — agent instructions\n\nHost-agnostic guidance for any AI coding agent working in this repo (Claude Code reads `CLAUDE.md`; OpenCode and other tools read this file). OpenLTM gives agents persistent semantic memory across sessions via a local SQLite database.\n\n## Using memory\n\nThe memory tools are exposed over MCP as `recall`, `learn`, `context`, `forget`, `relate` (in Claude Code, prefixed `mcp__plugin_openltm_memory__*`). The goal is automatic knowledge retrieval and capture — use judgment, not a call before every sentence.\n\n- **`recall`** before a non-trivial task, or when the work touches past decisions or an unfamiliar area. Skip for trivial one-liners.\n- **`learn`** after discovering a non-obvious pattern, architectural decision, or gotcha worth keeping across sessions.\n- **`context`** at session start or when switching projects, to restore goals, decisions, and gotchas.\n\nCategories: `preference | architecture | gotcha | pattern | workflow | constraint`. Importance `5` never decays; everything else ages out as it goes unused.\n\n## Working in this repo\n\n- **Runtime is Bun**, not npm/node. Use `bun`, `bunx`, `bun test`.\n- **Tests + typecheck must pass**: `bun test && bun run typecheck`.\n- **Version bumps are mandatory** on any change — `bun run bump <version>` then `bun run verify-version` (it gates all version sources: `package.json`, `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`, `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`, every `packages/*/package.json`, and the README badge).\n- **No secrets, no database files** in commits. `data/*.db*` is gitignored; keep it that way.\n\n## Shipping to OpenCode\n\nInstalling OpenLTM into OpenCode (`bunx @rohirik/openltm-core --opencode`) does two things: registers the `@rohirik/opencode-ltm` plugin in `opencode.json`, and deploys the bundled customization (agents, skills, plugins) from the package's `assets/opencode/` into the user's OpenCode config directory.\n\n## Releasing\n\nTag-driven and tokenless: bump versions, add a `CHANGELOG.md` entry, then `git tag vX.Y.Z && git push origin main vX.Y.Z`. The tag fires the Release and Publish workflows; npm packages publish via OIDC trusted publishing with provenance — no stored token. Full detail in `CONTRIBUTING.md`.\n\n## Docs\n\nUser-facing docs are in [`docs/`](docs/README.md); internal design specs in [`docs/internal/`](docs/internal/README.md).\n\n</system-reminder>","metadata":{"preview":"/**\n * db.ts — Global long-term memory (learned insights, patterns, preferences)\n * Replaces skills/learned/*.md with structured SQLite + FTS5.\n */\nimport type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\nimport { existsSync, mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from \"fs\";\nimport { join } from \"path\";\nimport { normalizeKey } from \"./dedup.js\";\nimport { getDb, DB_PATH, configure as configureDb } from \"./shared-db.js\";\nimport { enqueueEmbedding } from \"./queue/index.js\";\nimport { notifyLtm, notifyMemoryAdded } from \"./events/index.js\";\nimport { scrubSecrets } from \"./secretsScrubber.js\";\nimport { insertProvenance, insertAudit, snapshotMemory, listProvenanceBatch } from \"./dao/provenanceAudit.js\";\nimport type { ProvenanceSourceType } from \"./dao/types.js\";\nimport type { LtmCoreConfig } from \"./adapterTypes.js\";\nimport { tmpdir } from \"os\";\n\nexport { DB_PATH };\n/** Adapters can override via configureDocs() or LtmCoreConfig.docsDir. */\nlet DOCS_DIR = join(tmpdir(), \"ltm-docs\");","truncated":false,"loaded":["/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/AGENTS.md"],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts","text":"/**\n * db.ts — Global long-term memory (learned insights, patterns, preferences)\n * Replaces skills/learned/*.md with structured SQLite + FTS5.\n */\nimport type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\nimport { existsSync, mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from \"fs\";\nimport { join } from \"path\";\nimport { normalizeKey } from \"./dedup.js\";\nimport { getDb, DB_PATH, configure as configureDb } from \"./shared-db.js\";\nimport { enqueueEmbedding } from \"./queue/index.js\";\nimport { notifyLtm, notifyMemoryAdded } from \"./events/index.js\";\nimport { scrubSecrets } from \"./secretsScrubber.js\";\nimport { insertProvenance, insertAudit, snapshotMemory, listProvenanceBatch } from \"./dao/provenanceAudit.js\";\nimport type { ProvenanceSourceType } from \"./dao/types.js\";\nimport type { LtmCoreConfig } from \"./adapterTypes.js\";\nimport { tmpdir } from \"os\";\n\nexport { DB_PATH };\n/** Adapters can override via configureDocs() or LtmCoreConfig.docsDir. */\nlet DOCS_DIR = join(tmpdir(), \"ltm-docs\");\n\nexport function configureDocs(dir: string): void { DOCS_DIR = dir; }\n\nexport function configureCore(config: LtmCoreConfig): void {\n  configureDb(config);\n  if (config.docsDir) DOCS_DIR = config.docsDir;\n}\n\nexport type MemoryCategory = \"preference\" | \"architecture\" | \"gotcha\" | \"pattern\" | \"workflow\" | \"constraint\";\nexport type RelationshipType = \"supports\" | \"contradicts\" | \"refines\" | \"depends_on\" | \"related_to\" | \"supersedes\";\n\nexport interface Memory {\n  id: number;\n  content: string;\n  category: MemoryCategory;\n  importance: number;\n  confidence: number;\n  source: string | null;\n  project_scope: string | null;\n  dedup_key: string | null;\n  created_at: string;\n  last_confirmed_at: string;\n  last_used_at: string;\n  confirm_count: number;\n  status: \"active\" | \"pending\" | \"deprecated\" | \"superseded\";\n  first_recalled_at?: string;\n  last_recalled_at?: string;\n  recall_count?: number;\n  superseded_by?: number;\n  superseded_at?: string;\n  workspace_id?: string;\n  agent_id?: string;\n  decay_score?: number;\n}\n\nexport interface MemoryRelation {\n  id: number;\n  source_memory_id: number;\n  target_memory_id: number;\n  relationship_type: RelationshipType;\n  created_at: string;\n}\n\nexport interface MemoryWithRelations extends Memory {\n  tags: string[];\n  relations: Array<{ memory: Memory; relationship_type: RelationshipType; direction: \"outgoing\" | \"incoming\" }>;\n  /** Populated only when recall({ includeProvenance: true }) is requested. */\n  provenance?: import(\"./dao/types.js\").ProvenanceRow[];\n  /** Score breakdown + temperature — always populated by recall(). */\n  explainer?: import(\"./recall/explainer.js\").RecallExplainer;\n}\n\nexport interface LearnInput {\n  content: string;\n  /** Short human-readable label (≤60 chars). Agent-supplied; falls back to heuristic. */\n  title?: string;\n  category: MemoryCategory;\n  importance?: number;\n  confidence?: number;\n  source?: string;\n  project_scope?: string;\n  workspace_id?: string;\n  agent_id?: string;\n  tags?: string[];\n  relate_to?: Array<{ id: number; relationship_type: RelationshipType }>;\n  /** Skip regenerating docs/memory-long-term.md (use during bulk imports) */\n  skipExport?: boolean;\n  /** Audit/provenance — all optional; safe to omit from existing callers. */\n  actor?: string;\n  sessionId?: string;\n  provenanceSourceType?: ProvenanceSourceType;\n  provenanceSourceRef?: string;\n  provenanceMetadata?: string;\n}\n\nexport interface LearnResult {\n  action: \"created\" | \"reinforced\";\n  id: number;\n  confirm_count: number;\n}\n\nexport interface RecallInput {\n  since?: string;\n  until?: string;\n  sort_by?: \"relevance\" | \"created\" | \"last_recalled\" | \"recall_count\";\n\n  query?: string;\n  tags?: string[];\n  category?: MemoryCategory;\n  project?: string;\n  limit?: number;\n  workspace_id?: string;\n  agent_id?: string;\n  /** When true, each result includes a `provenance` array. Off by default to preserve latency. */\n  includeProvenance?: boolean;\n}\n\n\n/** Derive a short title from content when none is agent-supplied. */\nexport function deriveTitle(content: string): string {\n  const trimmed = content.trim();\n  const dot = trimmed.indexOf('.');\n  const nl = trimmed.indexOf('\\n');\n  const boundary = [dot, nl].filter(i => i > 1 && i <= 60).sort((a, b) => a - b)[0];\n  if (boundary !== undefined) return trimmed.slice(0, boundary).trim();\n  if (trimmed.length <= 60) return trimmed;\n  const cut = trimmed.slice(0, 57);\n  const lastSpace = cut.lastIndexOf(' ');\n  return (lastSpace > 20 ? cut.slice(0, lastSpace) : cut) + '…';\n}\n\nfunction tryAudit(fn: () => void): void {\n  try { fn(); } catch (e) { process.stderr.write(`[audit] write failed: ${e}\\n`); }\n}\n\nfunction upsertTag(db: Database, name: string): number {\n  db.run(`INSERT OR IGNORE INTO tags (name) VALUES (?)`, [name]);\n  return db.query<{ id: number }, [string]>(`SELECT id FROM tags WHERE name=?`).get(name)!.id;\n}\n\nfunction attachTags(db: Database, memoryId: number, tags: string[]): void {\n  for (const tag of tags) {\n    const tagId = upsertTag(db, tag.toLowerCase().trim());\n    db.run(`INSERT OR IGNORE INTO memory_tags (memory_id, tag_id) VALUES (?, ?)`, [memoryId, tagId]);\n  }\n}\n\n/** Fetch tags for a single memory — used in recall() results. */\nfunction getTagsForMemory(db: Database, memoryId: number): string[] {\n  return db.query<{ name: string }, [number]>(\n    `SELECT t.name FROM tags t JOIN memory_tags mt ON t.id=mt.tag_id WHERE mt.memory_id=?`\n  ).all(memoryId).map(r => r.name);\n}\n\n/** Batch-fetch tags for many memories — used in exportMarkdown to avoid N+1. */\nfunction getTagsBatch(db: Database, ids: number[]): Map<number, string[]> {\n  if (ids.length === 0) return new Map();\n  const placeholders = ids.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n  const rows = db.query<{ memory_id: number; name: string }, number[]>(\n    `SELECT mt.memory_id, t.name FROM memory_tags mt JOIN tags t ON t.id=mt.tag_id\n     WHERE mt.memory_id IN (${placeholders})`\n  ).all(...ids);\n  const result = new Map<number, string[]>();\n  for (const r of rows) {\n    if (!result.has(r.memory_id)) result.set(r.memory_id, []);\n    result.get(r.memory_id)!.push(r.name);\n  }\n  return result;\n}\n\nfunction getRelationsForMemory(db: Database, memoryId: number): MemoryWithRelations[\"relations\"] {\n  const outgoing = db.query<{ target_memory_id: number; relationship_type: string }, [number]>(\n    `SELECT target_memory_id, relationship_type FROM memory_relations WHERE source_memory_id=?`\n  ).all(memoryId);\n\n  const incoming = db.query<{ source_memory_id: number; relationship_type: string }, [number]>(\n    `SELECT source_memory_id, relationship_type FROM memory_relations WHERE target_memory_id=?`\n  ).all(memoryId);\n\n  const results: MemoryWithRelations[\"relations\"] = [];\n\n  for (const r of outgoing) {\n    const mem = db.query<Memory, [number]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(r.target_memory_id);\n    if (mem) results.push({ memory: mem, relationship_type: r.relationship_type as RelationshipType, direction: \"outgoing\" });\n  }\n  for (const r of incoming) {\n    const mem = db.query<Memory, [number]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(r.source_memory_id);\n    if (mem) results.push({ memory: mem, relationship_type: r.relationship_type as RelationshipType, direction: \"incoming\" });\n  }\n\n  return results;\n}\n\nfunction enrichMemory(db: Database, mem: Memory): MemoryWithRelations {\n  return { ...mem, tags: getTagsForMemory(db, mem.id), relations: getRelationsForMemory(db, mem.id) };\n}\n\n// --- Decay / relevance scoring ---\n\n/** Half-life in days by importance level. Infinity = never decays. */\nconst HALF_LIVES: Record<number, number> = {\n  5: Infinity,\n  4: 180,\n  3: 90,\n  2: 30,\n  1: 14,\n};\n\n/** Memories below this score are soft-deprecated (not deleted). */\nconst DEPRECATION_THRESHOLD = 0.25;\n\n/**\n * Compute effective relevance score.\n * score = importance × confidence × decay\n * decay = 0.5 ^ (days_since / half_life)  (1.0 for importance=5)\n */\nexport function computeDecayScore(memory: Memory): number {\n  const halfLife = HALF_LIVES[memory.importance] ?? 90;\n  if (halfLife === Infinity) {\n    return memory.importance * memory.confidence;\n  }\n  const latestTs = [memory.last_used_at, memory.last_confirmed_at, memory.created_at]\n    .map(t => new Date(t).getTime())\n    .reduce((a, b) => Math.max(a, b), 0);\n  const daysSince = (Date.now() - latestTs) / 86_400_000;\n  const decay = Math.pow(0.5, daysSince / halfLife);\n  return memory.importance * memory.confidence * decay;\n}\n\n/** Update last_used_at for a batch of memory IDs. */\nexport function updateLastUsed(ids: number[]): void {\n  if (ids.length === 0) return;\n  const db = getDb();\n  const placeholders = ids.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n  db.run(\n    `UPDATE memories SET last_used_at = datetime('now') WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n    ids\n  );\n}\n\nexport interface DecayResult {\n  deprecated: number;\n  scored: number;\n}\n\n/**\n * Compute decay scores for all active memories. Deprecate those below threshold.\n * Protection: importance=5 OR confirm_count>=5 are never deprecated.\n */\nexport function decayMemories(): DecayResult {\n  const db = getDb();\n\n  const rows = db.query<Memory, []>(\n    `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE status = 'active'`\n  ).all();\n\n  const toDeprecate = rows\n    .filter(mem => mem.importance !== 5 && mem.confirm_count < 5)\n    .filter(mem => computeDecayScore(mem) < DEPRECATION_THRESHOLD)\n    .map(mem => mem.id);\n\n  if (toDeprecate.length > 0) {\n    const placeholders = toDeprecate.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n    db.run(\n      `UPDATE memories SET status = 'deprecated' WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n      toDeprecate\n    );\n  }\n\n  return { deprecated: toDeprecate.length, scored: rows.length };\n}\n\n// Auto-relation detection — called fire-and-forget from learn()\nasync function autoDetectRelations(\n  newId: number,\n  content: string,\n  getSimilarMemories: (text: string, topN: number, threshold: number) => Promise<Array<{ id: number; content: string; similarity: number }>>,\n  classifyRelation: (a: string, b: string) => Promise<RelationshipType | null>,\n): Promise<void> {\n  try {\n    const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n    if (readConfigSync().ltm?.autoRelate === false) return;\n\n    const candidates = await getSimilarMemories(content, 5, 0.6);\n    const others = candidates.filter(c => c.id !== newId);\n    if (!others.length) return;\n\n    await Promise.allSettled(\n      others.map(async (candidate) => {\n        const relType = await classifyRelation(content, candidate.content);\n        if (!relType) return;\n        try {\n          relate({ source_id: newId, target_id: candidate.id, relationship_type: relType });\n        } catch {\n          // Memory may have been deleted between detection and insertion — ignore\n        }\n      })\n    );\n  } catch (err) {\n    process.stderr.write(`[autoDetectRelations] error for memory ${newId}: ${err}\\n`);\n  }\n}\n\nexport function learn(input: LearnInput): LearnResult {\n  const db = getDb();\n\n  // Scrub secrets before any DB write or dedup check\n  const { scrubbed, redactions } = scrubSecrets(input.content);\n  if (redactions.length > 0) {\n    process.stderr.write(`[learn] Scrubbed ${redactions.length} secret(s): ${redactions.join(\", \")}\\n`);\n  }\n  const content = scrubbed;\n\n  const dedupKey = normalizeKey(content);\n  const skipExport = input.skipExport ?? false;\n\n  const existing = db.query<Memory, [string]>(`SELECT * FROM memories WHERE dedup_key=?`).get(dedupKey);\n\n  const actor = input.actor ?? \"mcp:ltm_learn\";\n\n  if (existing) {\n    const beforeSnap = snapshotMemory(db, existing.id);\n    db.run(\n      `UPDATE memories SET confirm_count=confirm_count+1, last_confirmed_at=datetime('now'),\n       confidence=MIN(1.0, confidence+0.05) WHERE id=?`,\n      [existing.id]\n    );\n    if (input.tags) attachTags(db, existing.id, input.tags);\n    if (input.relate_to) {\n      for (const rel of input.relate_to) {\n        relate({ source_id: existing.id, target_id: rel.id, relationship_type: rel.relationship_type });\n      }\n    }\n    tryAudit(() => {\n      const afterSnap = snapshotMemory(db, existing.id);\n      insertAudit(db, {\n        memory_id: existing.id, op: \"update\", actor,\n        session_id: input.sessionId,\n        before_json: beforeSnap ? JSON.stringify(beforeSnap) : null,\n        after_json: afterSnap ? JSON.stringify(afterSnap) : null,\n      });\n    });\n    if (!skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n    const updated = db.query<{ confirm_count: number }, [number]>(\n      `SELECT confirm_count FROM memories WHERE id=?`\n    ).get(existing.id);\n    return { action: \"reinforced\", id: existing.id, confirm_count: updated?.confirm_count ?? existing.confirm_count + 1 };\n  }\n\n  const title = input.title?.trim().slice(0, 60) || deriveTitle(content);\n\n  const result = db.run(\n    `INSERT INTO memories (content, title, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key, created_by)\n     VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)`,\n    [\n      content,\n      title,\n      input.category,\n      input.importance ?? 3,\n      input.confidence ?? 1.0,\n      input.source ?? null,\n      input.project_scope ?? null,\n      dedupKey,\n      actor,\n    ]\n  );\n\n  const newId = Number(result.lastInsertRowid);\n\n  if (input.tags) attachTags(db, newId, input.tags);\n  if (input.relate_to) {\n    for (const rel of input.relate_to) {\n      relate({ source_id: newId, target_id: rel.id, relationship_type: rel.relationship_type });\n    }\n  }\n\n  tryAudit(() => {\n    insertProvenance(db, {\n      memory_id: newId,\n      source_type: input.provenanceSourceType ?? \"learn\",\n      source_ref: input.provenanceSourceRef ?? input.sessionId ?? null,\n      actor,\n      metadata: input.provenanceMetadata ?? null,\n    });\n    const afterSnap = snapshotMemory(db, newId);\n    insertAudit(db, {\n      memory_id: newId, op: \"insert\", actor,\n      session_id: input.sessionId,\n      before_json: null,\n      after_json: afterSnap ? JSON.stringify(afterSnap) : null,\n    });\n  });\n\n  if (!skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n\n  // Embedding generation: prefer the durable Honker queue (a long-lived worker\n  // claims + embeds with retry/dead-letter — short-lived hooks just enqueue and\n  // exit). When no queue is available, embed inline as before. Auto-relate runs\n  // inline regardless: it embeds the query text fresh and compares against other\n  // memories' stored vectors, so it does not depend on this memory's own row.\n  const enqueuedJobId = enqueueEmbedding(newId);\n  import(\"./embeddings.js\").then(async ({ embedMemory, getSimilarMemories, classifyRelation }) => {\n    if (enqueuedJobId === null) await embedMemory(db, newId);\n    await autoDetectRelations(newId, content, getSimilarMemories, classifyRelation);\n  }).catch(err => process.stderr.write(`[learn] Background task failed for memory ${newId}: ${err}\\n`));\n\n  // Push a cross-process liveness event so any graph-app listener refreshes\n  // without waiting on the file-watcher. No-op when Honker is unavailable.\n  notifyLtm({ type: \"refresh\", reason: \"memory_created\", id: newId });\n  // Opt-in cross-agent sync: notify sibling processes of the new memory. No-op\n  // unless the ltm.crossProcessSync flag is on AND Honker is available.\n  notifyMemoryAdded({ id: newId, project_scope: input.project_scope ?? null });\n\n  return { action: \"created\", id: newId, confirm_count: 1 };\n}\n\nexport async function recall(input: RecallInput = {}): Promise<MemoryWithRelations[]> {\n  const db = getDb();\n  const limit = input.limit ?? 10;\n\n  let ids: Set<number> | null = null;\n  const ftsRanks = new Map<number, number>();      // id → normalized [0,1]\n  const semanticScores = new Map<number, number>(); // id → cosine similarity [0,1]\n\n  if (input.query) {\n    // Sanitize for FTS5: quote each token (prevents reserved-word errors) and join with OR\n    const ftsQuery = input.query\n      .trim()\n      .split(/\\s+/)\n      .filter(Boolean)\n      .map(t => `\"${t.replace(/\"/g, '\"\"')}\"`)\n      .join(\" OR \");\n    const ftsResults = db.query<{ rowid: number; rank: number }, [string]>(\n      `SELECT rowid, rank FROM memories_fts WHERE memories_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50`\n    ).all(ftsQuery);\n    ids = new Set<number>();\n    for (const r of ftsResults) {\n      ids.add(r.rowid);\n      // FTS5 BM25 rank is a negative number (closer to 0 = better).\n      // Math.exp maps it to (0, 1] where 1 is a perfect match.\n      ftsRanks.set(r.rowid, Math.exp(r.rank));\n    }\n\n    // Semantic fallback: if FTS5 returned fewer results than requested, augment with vector search\n    if (ids.size < limit) {\n      const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n      const cfg = readConfigSync();\n      const semanticEnabled = cfg.ltm?.semanticFallback !== false; // default true\n      if (semanticEnabled) {\n        try {\n          const { getSimilarMemories } = await import(\"./embeddings.js\");\n          const semantic = await getSimilarMemories(input.query, limit * 2, 0.5);\n          for (const m of semantic) {\n            ids.add(m.id);\n            semanticScores.set(m.id, m.similarity);\n          }\n        } catch (err) {\n          process.stderr.write(`[recall] Semantic fallback failed: ${err}\\n`);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  if (input.tags && input.tags.length > 0) {\n    const tagIds = input.tags.map(t => {\n      const row = db.query<{ id: number }, [string]>(`SELECT id FROM tags WHERE name=?`).get(t.toLowerCase());\n      return row?.id;\n    }).filter((id): id is number => id !== undefined);\n\n    if (tagIds.length > 0) {\n      const placeholders = tagIds.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n      const tagMemIds = db.query<{ memory_id: number }, number[]>(\n        `SELECT DISTINCT memory_id FROM memory_tags WHERE tag_id IN (${placeholders})`\n      ).all(...tagIds).map(r => r.memory_id);\n\n      const tagSet = new Set(tagMemIds);\n      ids = ids ? new Set([...ids].filter(id => tagSet.has(id))) : tagSet;\n    }\n  }\n\n  const conditions: string[] = [];\n  const params: (string | number | null)[] = [];\n\n  if (ids !== null) {\n    if (ids.size === 0) return [];\n    const placeholders = [...ids].map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n    conditions.push(`id IN (${placeholders})`);\n    params.push(...ids);\n  }\n\n  if (input.category) {\n    conditions.push(\"category=?\");\n    params.push(input.category);\n  }\n\n  if (input.project) {\n    conditions.push(\"(project_scope IS NULL OR project_scope=?)\");\n    params.push(input.project);\n  }\n\n  if (input.workspace_id) {\n    conditions.push(\"(workspace_id IS NULL OR workspace_id=?)\");\n    params.push(input.workspace_id);\n  }\n  if (input.agent_id) {\n    conditions.push(\"(agent_id IS NULL OR agent_id=?)\");\n    params.push(input.agent_id);\n  }\n\n  conditions.push(\"status = 'active'\");\n\n  if (input.since) {\n    conditions.push(\"(created_at > ? OR last_recalled_at > ?)\");\n    params.push(input.since, input.since);\n  }\n  if (input.until) {\n    conditions.push(\"(created_at < ? OR last_recalled_at < ?)\");\n    params.push(input.until, input.until);\n  }\n\n  const where = `WHERE ${conditions.join(\" AND \")}`;\n  // Explicit columns — excludes embedding blob (~260 KB/row) from hot recall path.\n  // Use getById(id, { withEmbedding: true }) when the blob is needed.\n  // default sort (no query): ORDER BY decay_score DESC pushed to SQL → O(log N)\n  const defaultSqlSort = (!input.sort_by || input.sort_by === \"relevance\") && ids === null;\n  const orderBy = defaultSqlSort ? \"ORDER BY decay_score DESC\" : \"\";\n  const rows = db.query<Memory, typeof params>(\n    `SELECT id, content, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key,\n            created_at, last_confirmed_at, last_used_at, confirm_count, status,\n            first_recalled_at, last_recalled_at, recall_count, superseded_by, superseded_at,\n            workspace_id, agent_id, decay_score\n     FROM memories ${where} ${orderBy} LIMIT ${limit}`\n  ).all(...params);\n\n  let sorted: typeof rows;\n  if (defaultSqlSort) {\n    sorted = rows; // already ordered by decay_score DESC in SQL\n  } else if (input.sort_by === \"created\") {\n    sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => new Date(b.created_at).getTime() - new Date(a.created_at).getTime());\n  } else if (input.sort_by === \"last_recalled\") {\n    sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => new Date(b.last_recalled_at ?? \"1970\").getTime() - new Date(a.last_recalled_at ?? \"1970\").getTime());\n  } else if (input.sort_by === \"recall_count\") {\n    sorted = rows.sort((a, b) => (b.recall_count ?? 0) - (a.recall_count ?? 0));\n  } else {\n    // FTS/semantic path: small result set (≤50), JS sort is O(k log k) — negligible.\n    // Use materialised decay_score if available, fall back to computing it.\n    sorted = rows\n      .map(m => ({ m, score: m.decay_score ?? computeDecayScore(m) }))\n      .sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)\n      .map(({ m }) => m);\n  }\n  if (sorted.length > 0) {\n    const placeholders = sorted.map(() => \"?\").join(\",\");\n    db.run(\n      `UPDATE memories SET last_used_at = datetime('now'), last_recalled_at = datetime('now'),\n              recall_count = recall_count + 1,\n              first_recalled_at = COALESCE(first_recalled_at, datetime('now'))\n       WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,\n      sorted.map(m => m.id),\n    );\n  }\n  const enriched = sorted.map(m => enrichMemory(db, m));\n  if (input.includeProvenance) {\n    const provMap = listProvenanceBatch(db, enriched.map(m => m.id));\n    for (const m of enriched) {\n      m.provenance = provMap.get(m.id) ?? [];\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Attach explainer (pure function — no extra DB calls).\n  if (enriched.length > 0) {\n    const { buildExplainer } = await import(\"./recall/explainer.js\");\n    for (const m of enriched) {\n      m.explainer = buildExplainer({\n        importance: m.importance,\n        recall_count: m.recall_count ?? 0,\n        last_recalled_at: m.last_recalled_at,\n        ftsRank: ftsRanks.get(m.id) ?? null,\n        semanticScore: semanticScores.get(m.id) ?? null,\n      });\n    }\n  }\n\n  return enriched;\n}\n\nexport function relate(input: {\n  source_id: number;\n  target_id: number;\n  relationship_type: RelationshipType;\n}): void {\n  const db = getDb();\n  if (!db.query<{ id: number }, [number]>(`SELECT id FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(input.source_id)) {\n    throw new Error(`Source memory ${input.source_id} not found`);\n  }\n  if (!db.query<{ id: number }, [number]>(`SELECT id FROM memories WHERE id=?`).get(input.target_id)) {\n    throw new Error(`Target memory ${input.target_id} not found`);\n  }\n  db.run(\n    `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO memory_relations (source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n     VALUES (?, ?, ?)`,\n    [input.source_id, input.target_id, input.relationship_type]\n  );\n}\n\nexport function forget(input: { id: number; reason?: string; skipExport?: boolean; actor?: string; sessionId?: string }): void {\n  const db = getDb();\n  const snap = snapshotMemory(db, input.id);\n  if (!snap) throw new Error(`Memory ${input.id} not found`);\n  db.run(`DELETE FROM memories WHERE id=?`, [input.id]);\n  tryAudit(() => insertAudit(db, {\n    memory_id: input.id,\n    op: \"forget\",\n    actor: input.actor ?? \"mcp:ltm_forget\",\n    session_id: input.sessionId,\n    before_json: JSON.stringify(snap),\n    after_json: null,\n  }));\n  if (!input.skipExport) exportMarkdown();\n}\n\nexport function getSimilarMemories(\n  db: Database,\n  queryVec: Float32Array,\n  opts: { projectScope?: string; limit?: number; minImportance?: number }\n): Memory[] {\n  const { projectScope, limit = 15, minImportance = 2 } = opts;\n  const { blobToVec, cosineSimilarity } = require(\"./embeddings.js\") as typeof import(\"./embeddings.js\");\n\n  let query: string;\n  let params: (string | number)[];\n\n  if (projectScope) {\n    query = `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE project_scope=? AND importance>=? AND embedding IS NOT NULL AND status='active' LIMIT ${limit * 3}`;\n    params = [projectScope, minImportance];\n  } else {\n    query = `SELECT * FROM memories WHERE project_scope IS NULL AND importance>=? AND embedding IS NOT NULL AND status='active' LIMIT ${limit * 3}`;\n    params = [minImportance];\n  }\n\n  const rows = db.query<Memory & { embedding: Buffer }, typeof params>(query).all(...params);\n\n  const scored = rows.map(row => {\n    const { embedding, ...mem } = row as Memory & { embedding: Buffer };\n    const sim = cosineSimilarity(queryVec, blobToVec(embedding));\n    return { mem, sim };\n  });\n\n  scored.sort((a, b) => b.sim - a.sim);\n  return scored.slice(0, limit).map(s => s.mem);\n}\n\nexport function getContextMerge(project: string): { globals: Memory[]; scoped: Memory[] } {\n  const db = getDb();\n  const sortByDecay = (arr: Memory[]) =>\n    arr.map(m => ({ m, score: computeDecayScore(m) }))\n       .sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)\n       .map(({ m }) => m);\n\n  const SLIM = `id, content, category, importance, confidence, source, project_scope, dedup_key,\n               created_at, last_confirmed_at, last_used_at, confirm_count, status,\n               first_recalled_at, last_recalled_at, recall_count, superseded_by, superseded_at,\n               workspace_id, agent_id`;\n  const globals = sortByDecay(db.query<Memory, []>(\n    `SELECT ${SLIM} FROM memories WHERE importance >= 4 AND project_scope IS NULL AND status = 'active'`\n  ).all());\n\n  const scoped = sortByDecay(db.query<Memory, [string]>(\n    `SELECT ${SLIM} FROM memories WHERE project_scope=? AND importance >= 3 AND status = 'active' LIMIT 15`\n  ).all(project));\n\n  const allIds = [...globals, ...scoped].map(m => m.id);\n  updateLastUsed(allIds);\n\n  return { globals, scoped };\n}\n\n/**\n * Async variant: returns getContextMerge result plus graph insights block.\n * Used by SessionStart hook when graphReasoning is enabled.\n */\nexport async function getContextMergeWithGraph(project: string): Promise<{ globals: Memory[]; scoped: Memory[]; graphInsights?: string }> {\n  const base = getContextMerge(project);\n\n  const { readConfigSync } = await import(\"./config.js\");\n  if (!readConfigSync().ltm?.graphReasoning) return base;\n\n  const seeds = [...base.globals.slice(0, 2), ...base.scoped.slice(0, 1)].map(m => m.id);\n  if (seeds.length === 0) return base;\n\n  try {\n    const { traverseGraph, buildReasoningContext } = await import(\"./graph.js\");\n    const results = await Promise.allSettled(seeds.map(id => traverseGraph(id, 2, false)));\n    const lines: string[] = [];\n    for (const r of results) {\n      if (r.status === \"fulfilled\") {\n        const block = buildReasoningContext(r.value);\n        if (block) lines.push(block);\n      }\n    }\n    const graphInsights = lines.slice(0, 5).join(\"\\n\") || undefined;\n    return { ...base, graphInsights };\n  } catch (err) {\n    process.stderr.write(`[getContextMergeWithGraph] error: ${err}\\n`);\n    return base;\n  }\n}\n\n/** Write docs/memory-long-term-dump.md — auto-generated snapshot (never overwrites the architecture doc). */\nexport function exportMarkdown(): void {\n  const db = getDb();\n  if (!existsSync(DOCS_DIR)) mkdirSync(DOCS_DIR, { recursive: true });\n\n  const rows = db.query<Memory, []>(\n    `SELECT * FROM memories ORDER BY importance DESC, category ASC, created_at DESC LIMIT 500`\n  ).all();\n\n  // Batch-fetch all tags in one query to avoid N+1\n  const tagsByMemory = getTagsBatch(db, rows.map(r => r.id));\n\n  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString().replace(\"T\", \" \").replace(/\\..+/, \"\");\n  const lines: string[] = [\n    `# Long-Term Memory — Generated Dump`,\n    ``,\n    `> Auto-generated by \\`memory/db.ts\\`. Last updated: ${timestamp}`,\n    `> This is a raw data export. For the architecture guide see \\`docs/memory-long-term.md\\`.`,\n    `> Edit via \\`/learn\\`, \\`/forget\\`, \\`/relate\\` commands — do not edit directly.`,\n    ``,\n  ];\n\n  const byCategory = new Map<string, Memory[]>();\n  for (const m of rows) {\n    if (!byCategory.has(m.category)) byCategory.set(m.category, []);\n    byCategory.get(m.category)!.push(m);\n  }\n\n  for (const [cat, mems] of byCategory) {\n    lines.push(`## ${cat.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + cat.slice(1)}`);\n    lines.push(\"\");\n    for (const m of mems) {\n      const tags = tagsByMemory.get(m.id) ?? [];\n      const tagStr = tags.length > 0 ? ` \\`[${tags.join(\", \")}]\\`` : \"\";\n      const scope = m.project_scope ? ` *(${m.project_scope})*` : \"\";\n      const imp = \"★\".repeat(m.importance) + \"☆\".repeat(5 - m.importance);\n      lines.push(`- **[${m.id}]** ${m.content}${scope}${tagStr} ${imp} (conf: ${m.confidence.toFixed(2)}, confirmed: ${m.confirm_count}x)`);\n    }\n    lines.push(\"\");\n  }\n\n  if (rows.length === 0) {\n    lines.push(\"*No memories stored yet. Use `/learn` to add insights.*\");\n    lines.push(\"\");\n  }\n\n  writeFileSync(join(DOCS_DIR, \"memory-long-term-dump.md\"), lines.join(\"\\n\"));\n}\n\n/** Write docs/memory-graph.json — nodes + links for Force-Graph visualization. */\nexport function exportGraphJson(): void {\n  const db = getDb();\n  if (!existsSync(DOCS_DIR)) mkdirSync(DOCS_DIR, { recursive: true });\n\n  const memories = db.query<Memory, []>(`SELECT * FROM memories`).all();\n  const relations = db.query<MemoryRelation, []>(`SELECT * FROM memory_relations`).all();\n\n  writeFileSync(join(DOCS_DIR, \"memory-graph.json\"), JSON.stringify({\n    nodes: memories.map(m => ({\n      id: m.id,\n      label: m.content.substring(0, 60),\n      category: m.category,\n      importance: m.importance,\n      project_scope: m.project_scope,\n    })),\n    links: relations.map(r => ({\n      source: r.source_memory_id,\n      target: r.target_memory_id,\n      type: r.relationship_type,\n    })),\n  }, null, 2));\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":780,"totalLines":780,"truncated":false}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts","time":{"start":1780928491734,"end":1780928491757}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b38135ca386cce6016a26cfeb86e88191b5b70829bb428360"}},"id":"prt_ea79c30780011gSxcIjblr8wYP","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928491792,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ZNKM6uRsVXs7ltP4h6lM9z4u","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: -- Long-Term Memory Schema\n2: -- Two-table design: context_items (per-project context) + memories (global learned insights)\n3: \n4: -- ============================================================\n5: -- schema_migrations: versioned migration tracking\n6: -- ============================================================\n7: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n8:   id         INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n9:   version    TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n10:   applied_at INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT (unixepoch()),\n11:   checksum   TEXT\n12: );\n13: \n14: -- ============================================================\n15: -- context_items: replaces the 4 per-project Markdown context files\n16: -- ============================================================\n17: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS context_items (\n18:   id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n19:   project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n20:   type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n21:   content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n22:   title        TEXT,\n23:   session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup\n24:   permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-delete (decisions, gotchas)\n25:   memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n26:   status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN ('active','pending_promotion','promoted')),\n27:   created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n28: );\n29: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ctx_project ON context_items(project_name);\n30: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ctx_type    ON context_items(project_name, type);\n31: \n32: -- ============================================================\n33: -- memories: global + project-scoped learned insights\n34: -- ============================================================\n35: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memories (\n36:   id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n37:   content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n38:   title             TEXT,\n39:   category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n40:                       'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n41:   importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n42:   confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n43:   source            TEXT,\n44:   project_scope     TEXT,                     -- NULL = global, else project name\n45:   dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,\n46:   created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n47:   last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n48:   confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n49:   -- Phase 2: janitor fields\n50:   status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN ('active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n51:   embedding         BLOB,                     -- float32 vector for semantic search\n52:   last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n53:   -- Phase 3: temporal metadata\n54:   first_recalled_at  TEXT,\n55:   last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n56:   recall_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n57:   superseded_by    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n58:   superseded_at    TEXT,\n59:   -- Phase 7: graph humanization\n60:   hidden     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n61:   color      TEXT,\n62:   icon       TEXT,\n63:   user_note  TEXT,\n64:   -- Personal relevance signal: 'works' | 'doesnt' | NULL (unrated)\n65:   relevance_signal     TEXT,\n66:   relevance_signal_at  TEXT\n67: );\n68: \n69: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_category   ON memories(category);\n70: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_project    ON memories(project_scope);\n71: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_importance ON memories(importance DESC);\n72: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_confidence ON memories(confidence DESC);\n73: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_status     ON memories(status);\n74: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_last_used  ON memories(last_used_at);\n75: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_superseded ON memories(superseded_by);\n76: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_recall_count ON memories(recall_count DESC);\n77: \n78: -- ============================================================\n79: -- tags + memory_tags: many-to-many tagging for memories\n80: -- ============================================================\n81: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS tags (\n82:   id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n83:   name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n84: );\n85: \n86: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_tags (\n87:   memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n88:   tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n89:   PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n90: );\n91: \n92: -- ============================================================\n93: -- memory_relations: knowledge graph edges\n94: -- ============================================================\n95: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_relations (\n96:   id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n97:   source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n98:   target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n99:   relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n100:                       'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n101:   note             TEXT,\n102:   weight           REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(weight BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n103:   created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n104:   UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n105: );\n106: \n107: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_relations_source ON memory_relations(source_memory_id);\n108: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_relations_target ON memory_relations(target_memory_id);\n109: \n110: -- ============================================================\n111: -- memory_layout: per-view position persistence (Phase 7)\n112: -- Only saved on explicit drag/pin — simulation-placed nodes have no row.\n113: -- ============================================================\n114: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_layout (\n115:   memory_id  INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n116:   view       TEXT    NOT NULL,\n117:   x          REAL    NOT NULL,\n118:   y          REAL    NOT NULL,\n119:   pinned     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n120:   updated_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n121:   PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, view)\n122: );\n123: \n124: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_layout_view ON memory_layout(view);\n125: \n126: -- ============================================================\n127: -- FTS5 virtual table for full-text search on memories (includes title)\n128: -- ============================================================\n129: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memories_fts USING fts5(\n130:   title,\n131:   content,\n132:   content='memories',\n133:   content_rowid='id'\n134: );\n135: \n136: -- Triggers to keep FTS in sync with memories table\n137: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n138:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, title, content)\n139:     VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\n140: END;\n141: \n142: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n143:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, title, content)\n144:     VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n145: END;\n146: \n147: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n148:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, title, content)\n149:     VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n150:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, title, content)\n151:     VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\n152: END;\n153: \n154: -- ============================================================\n155: -- FTS5 for context_items\n156: -- ============================================================\n157: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS context_items_fts USING fts5(\n158:   title,\n159:   content,\n160:   content='context_items',\n161:   content_rowid='id'\n162: );\n163: \n164: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_ai AFTER INSERT ON context_items BEGIN\n165:   INSERT INTO context_items_fts(rowid, title, content)\n166:     VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\n167: END;\n168: \n169: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_ad AFTER DELETE ON context_items BEGIN\n170:   INSERT INTO context_items_fts(context_items_fts, rowid, title, content)\n171:     VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n172: END;\n173: \n174: CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_au AFTER UPDATE ON context_items BEGIN\n175:   INSERT INTO context_items_fts(context_items_fts, rowid, title, content)\n176:     VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n177:   INSERT INTO context_items_fts(rowid, title, content)\n178:     VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\n179: END;\n180: \n181: -- ============================================================\n182: -- settings: key-value store for janitor/provider configuration\n183: -- ============================================================\n184: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS settings (\n185:   key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n186:   value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n187:   updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n188: );\n189: \n190: -- workspace_id + agent_id indexes are created by migration 007_workspaces.sql\n191: -- after the columns are added via ALTER TABLE. Do not add them here.\n\n(End of file - total 191 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"-- Long-Term Memory Schema\n-- Two-table design: context_items (per-project context) + memories (global learned insights)\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- schema_migrations: versioned migration tracking\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n  id         INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  version    TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n  applied_at INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT (unixepoch()),\n  checksum   TEXT\n);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- context_items: replaces the 4 per-project Markdown context files\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS context_items (\n  id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql","text":"-- Long-Term Memory Schema\n-- Two-table design: context_items (per-project context) + memories (global learned insights)\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- schema_migrations: versioned migration tracking\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n  id         INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  version    TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n  applied_at INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT (unixepoch()),\n  checksum   TEXT\n);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- context_items: replaces the 4 per-project Markdown context files\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS context_items (\n  id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n  content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  title        TEXT,\n  session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup\n  permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-delete (decisions, gotchas)\n  memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN ('active','pending_promotion','promoted')),\n  created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ctx_project ON context_items(project_name);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ctx_type    ON context_items(project_name, type);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- memories: global + project-scoped learned insights\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memories (\n  id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  title             TEXT,\n  category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n                      'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n  importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n  confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n  source            TEXT,\n  project_scope     TEXT,                     -- NULL = global, else project name\n  dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,\n  created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n  -- Phase 2: janitor fields\n  status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN ('active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n  embedding         BLOB,                     -- float32 vector for semantic search\n  last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  -- Phase 3: temporal metadata\n  first_recalled_at  TEXT,\n  last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n  recall_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n  superseded_by    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  superseded_at    TEXT,\n  -- Phase 7: graph humanization\n  hidden     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n  color      TEXT,\n  icon       TEXT,\n  user_note  TEXT,\n  -- Personal relevance signal: 'works' | 'doesnt' | NULL (unrated)\n  relevance_signal     TEXT,\n  relevance_signal_at  TEXT\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_category   ON memories(category);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_project    ON memories(project_scope);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_importance ON memories(importance DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_confidence ON memories(confidence DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_status     ON memories(status);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_last_used  ON memories(last_used_at);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_superseded ON memories(superseded_by);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_memories_recall_count ON memories(recall_count DESC);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- tags + memory_tags: many-to-many tagging for memories\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS tags (\n  id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_tags (\n  memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- memory_relations: knowledge graph edges\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_relations (\n  id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n                      'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n  note             TEXT,\n  weight           REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(weight BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n  created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_relations_source ON memory_relations(source_memory_id);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_relations_target ON memory_relations(target_memory_id);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- memory_layout: per-view position persistence (Phase 7)\n-- Only saved on explicit drag/pin — simulation-placed nodes have no row.\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_layout (\n  memory_id  INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  view       TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  x          REAL    NOT NULL,\n  y          REAL    NOT NULL,\n  pinned     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n  updated_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, view)\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_layout_view ON memory_layout(view);\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- FTS5 virtual table for full-text search on memories (includes title)\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memories_fts USING fts5(\n  title,\n  content,\n  content='memories',\n  content_rowid='id'\n);\n\n-- Triggers to keep FTS in sync with memories table\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\nEND;\n\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\nEND;\n\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\nEND;\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- FTS5 for context_items\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS context_items_fts USING fts5(\n  title,\n  content,\n  content='context_items',\n  content_rowid='id'\n);\n\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_ai AFTER INSERT ON context_items BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO context_items_fts(rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\nEND;\n\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_ad AFTER DELETE ON context_items BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO context_items_fts(context_items_fts, rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\nEND;\n\nCREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS context_items_au AFTER UPDATE ON context_items BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO context_items_fts(context_items_fts, rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES ('delete', old.id, coalesce(old.title, ''), old.content);\n  INSERT INTO context_items_fts(rowid, title, content)\n    VALUES (new.id, coalesce(new.title, ''), new.content);\nEND;\n\n-- ============================================================\n-- settings: key-value store for janitor/provider configuration\n-- ============================================================\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS settings (\n  key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n  value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n  updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n\n-- workspace_id + agent_id indexes are created by migration 007_workspaces.sql\n-- after the columns are added via ALTER TABLE. Do not add them here.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":191,"totalLines":191,"truncated":false}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql","time":{"start":1780928491769,"end":1780928491783}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b38135ca386cce6016a26cfeb86f4819183acfa254d0cfb94"}},"id":"prt_ea79c30da001FyxXpC0jWbYHBK","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928491810,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_avqVA3GMQXnfqhQ1xCY7qJzZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: /**\n2:  * writeQueue.ts — Serialises all DB writes through a promise-chain queue.\n3:  * Prevents concurrent write corruption (W12).\n4:  */\n5: import type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\n6: \n7: export class WriteQueue {\n8:   private tail: Promise<unknown> = Promise.resolve();\n9: \n10:   enqueue<T>(fn: () => T | Promise<T>, db?: Database): Promise<T> {\n11:     const next = this.tail.then(async () => {\n12:       if (!db) return fn();\n13:       db.exec(\"BEGIN IMMEDIATE\");\n14:       try {\n15:         const result = await Promise.resolve(fn());\n16:         db.exec(\"COMMIT\");\n17:         return result;\n18:       } catch (err) {\n19:         try { db.exec(\"ROLLBACK\"); } catch {}\n20:         throw err;\n21:       }\n22:     });\n23:     this.tail = next.catch(() => {}); // prevent unhandled rejection on queue\n24:     return next as Promise<T>;\n25:   }\n26: }\n27: \n28: export const writeQueue = new WriteQueue();\n\n(End of file - total 28 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"/**\n * writeQueue.ts — Serialises all DB writes through a promise-chain queue.\n * Prevents concurrent write corruption (W12).\n */\nimport type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\n\nexport class WriteQueue {\n  private tail: Promise<unknown> = Promise.resolve();\n\n  enqueue<T>(fn: () => T | Promise<T>, db?: Database): Promise<T> {\n    const next = this.tail.then(async () => {\n      if (!db) return fn();\n      db.exec(\"BEGIN IMMEDIATE\");\n      try {\n        const result = await Promise.resolve(fn());\n        db.exec(\"COMMIT\");\n        return result;\n      } catch (err) {\n        try { db.exec(\"ROLLBACK\"); } catch {}\n        throw err;","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts","text":"/**\n * writeQueue.ts — Serialises all DB writes through a promise-chain queue.\n * Prevents concurrent write corruption (W12).\n */\nimport type { Database } from \"bun:sqlite\";\n\nexport class WriteQueue {\n  private tail: Promise<unknown> = Promise.resolve();\n\n  enqueue<T>(fn: () => T | Promise<T>, db?: Database): Promise<T> {\n    const next = this.tail.then(async () => {\n      if (!db) return fn();\n      db.exec(\"BEGIN IMMEDIATE\");\n      try {\n        const result = await Promise.resolve(fn());\n        db.exec(\"COMMIT\");\n        return result;\n      } catch (err) {\n        try { db.exec(\"ROLLBACK\"); } catch {}\n        throw err;\n      }\n    });\n    this.tail = next.catch(() => {}); // prevent unhandled rejection on queue\n    return next as Promise<T>;\n  }\n}\n\nexport const writeQueue = new WriteQueue();","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":28,"totalLines":28,"truncated":false}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts","time":{"start":1780928491777,"end":1780928491804}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b38135ca386cce6016a26cfeb87008191a4679155b5753e54"}},"id":"prt_ea79c30fb001GirnuBFhOqTySk","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928491831,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5CIsWSCPMYiSSavlR4d9Z5Mi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n2: \n3: **Version:** 1.0\n4: **Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n5: **Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n6: **Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n7: **Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n8: \n9: This document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\n10: the current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\n11: the migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\n12: at scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n13: \n14: `ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\n15: doc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\n16: in §9 below.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## Table of Contents\n21: \n22: 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n23: 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n24: 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n25: 4. Memory Decay Model\n26: 5. Migration System\n27: 6. Concurrency and Safety\n28: 7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n29: 8. Performance at Scale\n30: 9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n35: \n36: The entire data store is one SQLite file: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/OpenLtm-openltm/openltm.db`.\n37: Accessed exclusively through `src/shared-db.ts:getDb()`. WAL mode, foreign keys on,\n38: busy_timeout 5 000 ms set on every connection.\n39: \n40: Schema source of truth: `src/schema.sql` (initial tables + FTS + triggers).\n41: Migration overlay: `src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` (idempotent column adds).\n42: \n43: ### 1.1 `memories`\n44: \n45: The core table. Every durable insight the plugin has stored, whether from `learn`,\n46: GitLearn backfill, EvaluateSession, or bundle import.\n47: \n48: ```sql\n49: CREATE TABLE memories (\n50:   id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n51:   -- Content and classification\n52:   content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n53:   category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n54:                       'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n55:   importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n56:   confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n57:   source            TEXT,                       -- free-text provenance hint (pre-Phase 2)\n58:   project_scope     TEXT,                       -- NULL = global; else project_name\n59:   dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,             -- normalised hash; prevents repeat learns\n60: \n61:   -- Timestamps\n62:   created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n63:   last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n64:   confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n65: \n66:   -- Lifecycle (Phase 2 migration, now in schema.sql)\n67:   status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n68:                       'active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n69: \n70:   -- Embedding (Phase 1 split candidate)\n71:   embedding         BLOB,                       -- float32 vector; stripped from MCP responses\n72: \n73:   -- Recall telemetry (Phase 3 migration)\n74:   last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n75:   first_recalled_at TEXT,\n76:   last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n77:   recall_count      INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n78: \n79:   -- Supersession chain (Phase 2 migration)\n80:   superseded_by     INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n81:   superseded_at     TEXT,\n82: \n83:   -- Multi-agent metadata (T16 migration)\n84:   workspace_id      TEXT,\n85:   agent_id          TEXT\n86: );\n87: ```\n88: \n89: **Column rationale**\n90: \n91: | Column | Rationale |\n92: |--------|-----------|\n93: | `category` | Six-value enum enforced by CHECK; drives the SessionStart injection filter (importance-5 + category) |\n94: | `importance` | 1–5 ordinal; 5 = immortal (no decay); drives every-session injection threshold |\n95: | `confidence` | Reserved for EvaluateSession and the future janitor's auto-demotion logic; not yet surfaced to users |\n96: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents a session that keeps re-learning the same fact from polluting the table; computed by the Learn Engine as a normalised content hash |\n97: | `project_scope` | NULL = global (injected in all sessions); non-null = scoped to one project (joined against the `registry.json` project_name) |\n98: | `status` | Soft-delete / workflow state; recall queries filter to `status = 'active'` |\n99: | `embedding` | Stored as a raw BLOB (float32 array). At 1536 dimensions = ~6 KB per row; serialised to JSON over MCP it becomes ~260 KB. The compact formatter strips it before every MCP response. Phase 1 moves it to a separate table. |\n100: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Inputs to the recall-time decay calculation. `last_used_at` covers both learn-time touch and recall-time touch; `last_recalled_at` covers recall only. |\n101: | `superseded_by` | Self-referential FK; forms the supersession chain for time-travel (Phase 7) |\n102: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | Multi-agent isolation (ROADMAP Phase 5 / T16); both indexed |\n103: \n104: ### 1.2 `context_items`\n105: \n106: Per-project short-term context. Replaces the four Markdown files that existed before v1.0.\n107: \n108: ```sql\n109: CREATE TABLE context_items (\n110:   id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n111:   project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n112:   type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n113:   content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n114:   session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup across same session\n115:   permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-trim (decision, gotcha)\n116:   memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,  -- Phase 1 migration\n117:   status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n118:                  'active','pending_promotion','promoted')),          -- Phase 2 migration\n119:   created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n120:   workspace_id TEXT,                          -- T16 multi-agent isolation\n121:   agent_id     TEXT                           -- T16\n122: );\n123: ```\n124: \n125: **Lifecycle by type**\n126: \n127: | Type | `permanent` | Trim rule |\n128: |------|-------------|-----------|\n129: | `goal` | 0 | Replaced when a new goal is written |\n130: | `decision` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed; manual removal only |\n131: | `progress` | 0 | Trimmed to last 20 per project by UpdateContext hook |\n132: | `gotcha` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed |\n133: \n134: **`status` flow**\n135: \n136: ```\n137: active -> pending_promotion -> promoted\n138:                            (memory_id set once promoted to memories table)\n139: ```\n140: \n141: ### 1.3 `tags` and `memory_tags`\n142: \n143: Many-to-many tagging for memories. Tags are auto-created on use; the dictionary is normalised to avoid duplication.\n144: \n145: ```sql\n146: CREATE TABLE tags (\n147:   id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n148:   name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n149: );\n150: \n151: CREATE TABLE memory_tags (\n152:   memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n153:   tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n154:   PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n155: );\n156: ```\n157: \n158: No additional indexes needed: the composite PK covers `(memory_id, tag_id)` lookup; `ON DELETE CASCADE` keeps the join table clean without a separate job.\n159: \n160: ### 1.4 `memory_relations`\n161: \n162: Knowledge graph edges. Six typed relationship directions. Used by `relate` and traversed by `graph` (BFS via `src/graph.ts`).\n163: \n164: ```sql\n165: CREATE TABLE memory_relations (\n166:   id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n167:   source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n168:   target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n169:   relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n170:                       'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n171:   created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n172:   UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n173: );\n174: ```\n175: \n176: The UNIQUE constraint on the triple prevents duplicate edges for the same relationship type. Cascade on both FKs means deleting a memory automatically prunes all edges.\n177: \n178: ### 1.5 `memories_fts`\n179: \n180: FTS5 external-content virtual table. Shadows `memories.content`. Maintained by three triggers.\n181: \n182: ```sql\n183: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n184:   content,\n185:   content='memories',\n186:   content_rowid='id'\n187: );\n188: \n189: CREATE TRIGGER memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n190:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n191: END;\n192: CREATE TRIGGER memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n193:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n194: END;\n195: CREATE TRIGGER memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n196:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n197:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n198: END;\n199: ```\n200: \n201: See §3 for full FTS5 configuration analysis.\n202: \n203: ### 1.6 `settings`\n204: \n205: Key-value store for janitor configuration, provider selection, decay parameters, and\n206: feature flags.\n207: \n208: ```sql\n209: CREATE TABLE settings (\n210:   key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n211:   value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n212:   updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n213: );\n214: ```\n215: \n216: Known keys (as of v1.4.20):\n217: \n218: | Key | Expected type | Purpose |\n219: |-----|--------------|---------|\n220: | `decay.half_life_days` | integer | Days before a non-recalled memory halves its rank boost |\n221: | `decay.immortal_importance` | integer | Importance threshold above which decay is skipped |\n222: | `embedding.provider` | string | `null` / `local-hash` / `claude-tool` / `onnx` |\n223: | `janitor.enabled` | boolean | Master switch for Phase 4 janitor |\n224: | `janitor.last_run_at` | ISO8601 | Timestamp of last janitor pass |\n225: \n226: ---\n227: \n228: ## 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n229: \n230: ### 2.1 Existing indexes\n231: \n232: | Index | Table | Columns | Rationale |\n233: |-------|-------|---------|-----------|\n234: | `idx_ctx_project` | `context_items` | `project_name` | SessionStart: `WHERE project_name = ?` |\n235: | `idx_ctx_type` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type)` | SessionStart per-type fetch; composite covers both equality predicates |\n236: | `idx_memories_category` | `memories` | `category` | Filter by category in recall and health commands |\n237: | `idx_memories_project` | `memories` | `project_scope` | Scoped recall: `WHERE project_scope = ? OR project_scope IS NULL` |\n238: | `idx_memories_importance` | `memories` | `importance DESC` | SessionStart global injection (`importance = 5`); importance ordering |\n239: | `idx_memories_confidence` | `memories` | `confidence DESC` | Future janitor demotion; currently unused on hot path |\n240: | `idx_memories_status` | `memories` | `status` | All read paths filter `status = 'active'` |\n241: | `idx_memories_last_used` | `memories` | `last_used_at` | Decay input; janitor staleness scan |\n242: | `idx_memories_superseded` | `memories` | `superseded_by` | Supersession chain traversal |\n243: | `idx_memories_recall_count` | `memories` | `recall_count DESC` | Health reporting: top-recalled memories |\n244: | `idx_memories_workspace` | `memories` | `workspace_id` | T16 multi-agent isolation |\n245: | `idx_memories_agent` | `memories` | `agent_id` | T16 |\n246: | `idx_relations_source` | `memory_relations` | `source_memory_id` | BFS forward traversal |\n247: | `idx_relations_target` | `memory_relations` | `target_memory_id` | BFS reverse traversal |\n248: \n249: ### 2.2 Hot-path scan analysis\n250: \n251: **Hot path 1: `recall` (most frequent)**\n252: \n253: Query skeleton:\n254: ```sql\n255: SELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.last_recalled_at, m.recall_count\n256: FROM memories_fts\n257: JOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\n258: WHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n259:   AND m.status = 'active'\n260:   AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)\n261: ORDER BY memories_fts.rank, m.importance DESC\n262: LIMIT 10;\n263: ```\n264: \n265: Hits: `memories_fts` (FTS5 own index), `idx_memories_status`, `idx_memories_project`.\n266: Gap: the `ORDER BY` applies FTS5 BM25 rank then falls back to a table scan for `importance DESC`. A covering index on `(status, project_scope, importance DESC)` would eliminate the table scan for the secondary sort. This is a low-priority improvement since FTS5 already constrains the result set to a small rowid list.\n267: \n268: **Hot path 2: SessionStart context injection**\n269: \n270: Query skeleton:\n271: ```sql\n272: SELECT * FROM context_items\n273: WHERE project_name = ? AND status = 'active'\n274: ORDER BY type, created_at;\n275: \n276: SELECT * FROM memories\n277: WHERE status = 'active' AND importance = 5 AND project_scope IS NULL\n278: ORDER BY importance DESC, last_recalled_at DESC\n279: LIMIT 15;\n280: ```\n281: \n282: Hits: `idx_ctx_type` (covers both predicates), `idx_memories_importance` + `idx_memories_status`.\n283: Gap: the memories query uses a range scan on importance filtered by status. A compound index `(status, importance DESC)` would be a covering scan. Add in Phase 0.\n284: \n285: **Hot path 3: UpdateContext progress trim**\n286: \n287: ```sql\n288: DELETE FROM context_items\n289: WHERE project_name = ? AND type = 'progress'\n290:   AND id NOT IN (\n291:     SELECT id FROM context_items\n292:     WHERE project_name = ? AND type = 'progress'\n293:     ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 20\n294:   );\n295: ```\n296: \n297: Hits: `idx_ctx_type`. Sub-select is a sequential scan of the progress partition per project. At <= 20 rows per project this is fine; the outer DELETE hit count is always near zero.\n298: \n299: ### 2.3 Missing indexes (to add in migrations)\n300: \n301: | Index to add | Table | Columns | Why |\n302: |---|---|---|---|\n303: | `idx_memories_status_importance` | `memories` | `(status, importance DESC)` | Hot path 2: eliminates filter + sort split |\n304: | `idx_memories_created_at` | `memories` | `created_at` | Decay calculation, janitor oldest-first scan |\n305: | `idx_memories_last_recalled_at` | `memories` | `last_recalled_at` | Decay input; janitor stale scan |\n306: | `idx_ctx_project_type_created` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type, created_at DESC)` | UpdateContext trim sub-select; also SessionStart per-type ordered fetch |\n307: \n308: Phase 0 migration file: `0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql`.\n309: \n310: ---\n311: \n312: ## 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n313: \n314: ### 3.1 Current configuration\n315: \n316: ```sql\n317: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n318:   content,\n319:   content='memories',\n320:   content_rowid='id'\n321: );\n322: ```\n323: \n324: - **Tokenizer:** SQLite default (`unicode61`). Handles Unicode casing and stemming at the Unicode 6.1 level. Adequate for English natural-language memories; does not do language-specific stemming.\n325: - **Content mode:** External-content (`content='memories'`). The FTS index does not store original text; it defers to the base table for snippets. This halves FTS storage cost at the price of a join on every snippet request.\n326: - **`content_rowid='id'`:** Maps FTS rowids directly to `memories.id`. The JOIN in recall queries is a rowid lookup — O(log N) on the B-tree.\n327: - **Triggers:** Three triggers keep the index in sync (insert, delete, update). These are synchronous — no async lag. They run inside the same transaction as the base table write.\n328: \n329: ### 3.2 BM25 ranking\n330: \n331: FTS5's built-in `rank` function is BM25. Default parameters: `b=0.75, k1=1.2`. No column weights configured (single-column index).\n332: \n333: The Recall Engine applies a post-BM25 multiplier in TypeScript:\n334: \n335: ```\n336: final_score = bm25_rank * importance_weight * decay_factor * recency_boost\n337: ```\n338: \n339: Where:\n340: - `importance_weight` = 1.0 + (importance - 1) * 0.25 (range 1.0–2.0)\n341: - `decay_factor` = computed per §4\n342: - `recency_boost` = 1.0 + clamp(30 - days_since_recalled, 0, 30) / 30 * 0.5\n343: \n344: ### 3.3 Query patterns\n345: \n346: **Primary (keyword):**\n347: ```sql\n348: SELECT memories_fts.rowid, memories_fts.rank\n349: FROM memories_fts\n350: WHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n351: ORDER BY rank;\n352: ```\n353: \n354: FTS5 MATCH operators in use: phrase search (`\"exact phrase\"`), prefix (`word*`), implicit AND for multi-word queries.\n355: \n356: **Semantic fallback (triggered when FTS5 returns < 3 results):**\n357: \n358: The semantic path reads all active memories with an `embedding` BLOB, computes cosine similarity in TypeScript against the query embedding, and merges with the FTS5 results. This is an O(N) scan — see §4.2 for the scale problem and §7 for the Phase 1 `memory_embeddings` split that isolates this cost.\n359: \n360: **Merge and dedup:**\n361: \n362: Results from both paths are merged by `id`. Duplicates are resolved by taking the higher score. The combined list is re-ranked by `final_score` before top-N truncation.\n363: \n364: ### 3.4 FTS5 integrity\n365: \n366: External-content tables are not self-healing: if the base table is modified outside the trigger path (e.g., a direct `UPDATE` via `sqlite3` CLI), the FTS index will drift. Detection:\n367: \n368: ```sql\n369: INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts) VALUES ('integrity-check');\n370: ```\n371: \n372: Returns OK if the shadow tables are consistent. A Phase 0 `ltm:admin` sub-command should run this check on demand.\n373: \n374: ### 3.5 Planned improvements\n375: \n376: - **Phase 0:** Add a `PRAGMA integrity_check` wrapper and an FTS integrity check to `/openltm:admin`.\n377: - **Phase 3:** Add a `category` column to `memories_fts` so category filtering can be pushed into the FTS query rather than applied as a post-filter join:\n378:   ```sql\n379:   CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n380:     content, category,\n381:     content='memories', content_rowid='id'\n382:   );\n383:   ```\n384:   This doubles the trigger complexity (both columns must be maintained) but enables:\n385:   ```sql\n386:   WHERE memories_fts MATCH 'category:gotcha AND <query>'\n387:   ```\n388: \n389: ---\n390: \n391: ## 4. Memory Decay Model\n392: \n393: ### 4.1 Current implementation\n394: \n395: Decay is computed **at recall time** in TypeScript. No stored score. The inputs are columns already on `memories`:\n396: \n397: | Input | Column | Role |\n398: |-------|---------|------|\n399: | Age | `created_at` | Base staleness |\n400: | Last touched | `last_recalled_at` | Freshness signal |\n401: | Frequency | `recall_count` | Utility signal |\n402: | Weight | `importance` | Override signal |\n403: \n404: **Current rules (approximate, inferred from Recall Engine source):**\n405: \n406: 1. If `importance == 5`, skip decay entirely. Score = BM25 * importance_weight.\n407: 2. Else compute `days_stale = (now - last_recalled_at) in days`.\n408: 3. If `days_stale > 90 AND importance < 3`:\n409:    ```\n410:    decay_factor = max(0.1, 1 - (days_stale - 90) / 365)\n411:    ```\n412:    Linear decay from 1.0 at day 90 to ~0.1 at day 455.\n413: 4. If `days_stale <= 30`: apply recency boost (`+0 to +50%`).\n414: 5. Else: `decay_factor = 1.0` (no decay for mid-range memories).\n415: \n416: **Decay function shape:** piecewise linear. The exact shape remains OQ3 (open question in ROADMAP §5) to be resolved in Phase 4 with real recall telemetry.\n417: \n418: ### 4.2 The O(N) problem (Architecture W4)\n419: \n420: The current implementation fetches the full FTS5 result set (typically up to 50 rows from a BM25 scan), then applies the decay multiplier in JavaScript for each row. At 10k memories the FTS5 result set is well-bounded; the JS multiplication is negligible.\n421: \n422: At 100k+ memories, the semantic fallback path scans all rows with an embedding BLOB, computing cosine similarity for each. This is O(N) and breaks the 200 ms recall budget.\n423: \n424: The problem has two distinct components:\n425: \n426: | Component | Current | At 100k |\n427: |-----------|---------|---------|\n428: | FTS5 BM25 scan | O(log N + k) rowids | Bounded; fast |\n429: | JavaScript decay multiply | O(k) where k = result set | Bounded; fast |\n430: | Semantic fallback (embedding scan) | O(N) across all rows | **Slow: ~500ms estimated** |\n431: | Final merge and sort | O(k log k) | Bounded |\n432: \n433: ### 4.3 Fix spec: materialised `decay_score` (Phase 4)\n434: \n435: Add a `decay_score REAL` column to `memories`. A low-frequency janitor process refreshes it on a schedule (nightly by default, configurable via `settings`).\n436: \n437: **Migration:** `0012_add_decay_score.sql`\n438: ```sql\n439: ALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN decay_score REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0;\n440: CREATE INDEX idx_memories_decay_score ON memories(decay_score DESC);\n441: ```\n442: \n443: **Janitor refresh logic (pseudo-SQL):**\n444: ```sql\n445: UPDATE memories\n446: SET decay_score = CASE\n447:   WHEN importance = 5 THEN 1.0\n448:   WHEN julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) > 90\n449:     AND importance < 3\n450:     THEN MAX(0.1,\n451:       1.0 - (julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) - 90.0) / 365.0\n452:     )\n453:   WHEN julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) <= 30\n454:     THEN MIN(1.5,\n455:       1.0 + (30.0 - (julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at))) / 30.0 * 0.5\n456:     )\n457:   ELSE 1.0\n458: END\n459: WHERE status = 'active';\n460: ```\n461: \n462: **Recall query after Phase 4:**\n463: ```sql\n464: SELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.decay_score,\n465:        (memories_fts.rank * (1.0 + (m.importance - 1) * 0.25) * m.decay_score) AS final_score\n466: FROM memories_fts\n467: JOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\n468: WHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n469:   AND m.status = 'active'\n470:   AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)\n471: ORDER BY final_score DESC\n472: LIMIT 10;\n473: ```\n474: \n475: The decay multiply moves into SQL, uses the pre-materialised `decay_score`, and the query becomes O(log N + k). The semantic fallback becomes the only O(N) path, resolved by the `memory_embeddings` split (Phase 1) and an ANN index (Phase 3 stretch goal).\n476: \n477: **Trade-off:** Write amplification. Every `learn` does not update `decay_score` — the janitor does. There is a staleness window of up to 24 hours. This is acceptable: decay is a rank modifier, not a hard filter. A freshly-learned memory has `decay_score = 1.0` (default) which is correct.\n478: \n479: **Janitor run record:** stored in `settings` as `janitor.last_run_at`. The `/openltm:health` command surfaces it.\n480: \n481: ---\n482: \n483: ## 5. Migration System\n484: \n485: ### 5.1 Current risks (Architecture W3)\n486: \n487: `src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` is an imperative list of `hasColumn` guards followed by `ALTER TABLE` statements. Problems:\n488: \n489: 1. **No migration history.** There is no record of which migrations have run against a given DB. If a migration is renamed or reordered, it may re-run or be skipped silently.\n490: 2. **No version table.** Impossible to answer \"what schema version is this DB?\" from outside the code.\n491: 3. **No rollback path.** Each migration is a one-way `ALTER TABLE`. There is no down-migration.\n492: 4. **Order coupling.** Migrations are ordered by their position in a single function. Adding a migration in the middle risks breaking callers that depend on run order.\n493: 5. **No checksum.** A migration can be silently edited after it has run; there is no detection.\n494: 6. **Testing gap.** The migration function is tested only indirectly via integration tests on the full DB. No isolated migration unit test.\n495: \n496: ### 5.2 Spec: `schema_migrations` table (Phase 0)\n497: \n498: Add a `schema_migrations` table that is the source of truth for migration state.\n499: \n500: ```sql\n501: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n502:   version     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,             -- monotonic integer, e.g. 1, 2, 3\n503:   name        TEXT    NOT NULL,                -- human-readable slug, e.g. 'add_hot_path_indexes'\n504:   applied_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n505:   checksum    TEXT    NOT NULL                 -- SHA-256 hex of the migration SQL file content\n506: );\n507: ```\n508: \n509: **Migration file naming convention:**\n510: ```\n511: db/migrations/NNNN_<slug>.sql\n512: ```\n513: \n514: Where `NNNN` is a zero-padded four-digit integer. Example:\n515: ```\n516: db/migrations/0001_initial_schema.sql\n517: db/migrations/0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql\n518: db/migrations/0003_schema_migrations_table.sql\n519: ```\n520: \n521: The migration runner (`src/migrator.ts`, Phase 0):\n522: \n523: 1. Ensure `schema_migrations` table exists (self-bootstrapping DDL).\n524: 2. Read all `db/migrations/*.sql` files, sorted by version number.\n525: 3. For each file: check if `version` exists in `schema_migrations`. If not:\n526:    - Compute SHA-256 of file content.\n527:    - Execute the SQL inside a transaction.\n528:    - INSERT into `schema_migrations(version, name, checksum)`.\n529: 4. If `version` exists: compare stored checksum vs. current file checksum. If mismatch, log a warning (do not fail; the file may have been legitimately patched post-apply with a comment).\n530: 5. Replace `runMigrations()` in `shared-db.ts` with a call to `runMigrator(db)`.\n531: \n532: **Backfill migration (0001):** represents the state after all current `hasColumn` guards have run. No SQL needed; just insert a sentinel row:\n533: ```sql\n534: INSERT OR IGNORE INTO schema_migrations(version, name, checksum)\n535: VALUES (1, 'initial_schema_backfill', 'backfilled');\n536: ```\n537: \n538: **Rollback posture.** SQLite does not support `DROP COLUMN` before version 3.35.0 and many embeddings use older versions. Rollback migrations are therefore not always possible. The policy:\n539: \n540: - Additive migrations (ADD COLUMN, CREATE TABLE, CREATE INDEX): always rollback-possible with a companion `_down.sql` file (not executed automatically; manual emergency only).\n541: - Destructive migrations (DROP TABLE, DROP COLUMN): must include an explicit \"data loss acknowledged\" comment in the migration file and must be gated on a major version bump.\n542: \n543: ### 5.3 Migration runner location\n544: \n545: `src/migrator.ts` — called from `shared-db.ts:getDb()` after WAL mode and foreign keys are set, before `schema.sql` is executed. Sequence:\n546: \n547: ```\n548: getDb()\n549:   -> PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL; foreign_keys=ON; busy_timeout=5000;\n550:   -> runMigrator(db)           // versioned migrations first\n551:   -> exec(schema.sql)          // idempotent CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS (no-ops after first run)\n552: ```\n553: \n554: The `schema.sql` file must remain idempotent (`CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`, `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS`) so it is safe to re-execute after migrations.\n555: \n556: ---\n557: \n558: ## 6. Concurrency and Safety\n559: \n560: ### 6.1 WAL mode\n561: \n562: Set at connection open:\n563: ```sql\n564: PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL;\n565: PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;\n566: PRAGMA busy_timeout=5000;\n567: ```\n568: \n569: WAL mode permits concurrent readers with a single writer. Multiple readers never block each other. A writer blocks only other writers. The 5 000 ms busy timeout provides graceful retry for the second writer rather than an immediate `SQLITE_BUSY` error.\n570: \n571: ### 6.2 Current race conditions\n572: \n573: **Race 1: Two Claude Code sessions starting simultaneously.**\n574: \n575: Both spawn a `SessionStart` hook. Both call `runMigrations()` concurrently against the same DB. `ALTER TABLE` statements inside migrations are not atomic across processes.\n576: \n577: Risk: one process runs `ALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN workspace_id TEXT` while the other is mid-read. With WAL, the ALTER acquires an EXCLUSIVE lock momentarily; the reader retries. The busy_timeout absorbs this for 5 s. Actual risk of corruption: low. Actual risk of a 5 s stall on session start: real.\n578: \n579: **Fix (Phase 0):** Wrap `runMigrations()` (replaced by `runMigrator()`) in an advisory lock:\n580: ```sql\n581: BEGIN IMMEDIATE;\n582: -- migration DDL here\n583: COMMIT;\n584: ```\n585: \n586: `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` acquires a RESERVED lock, blocking other writers without blocking readers. If a second migrator tries `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` concurrently, it waits up to `busy_timeout` (5 s). After Phase 0, migration runs are idempotent checks (row existence) so the critical section is tiny.\n587: \n588: **Race 2: Concurrent writes to `registry.json` (Architecture W2).**\n589: \n590: Two sessions auto-registering different cwds simultaneously use a read-modify-write pattern with no file lock. Last writer wins; the other registration is silently lost.\n591: \n592: Fix (Phase 0): Replace `fs.writeFileSync` with an atomic rename pattern:\n593: ```typescript\n594: const tmp = `${registryPath}.tmp.${process.pid}`;\n595: fs.writeFileSync(tmp, JSON.stringify(updated, null, 2));\n596: fs.renameSync(tmp, registryPath);  // atomic on POSIX\n597: ```\n598: \n599: `rename()` is atomic on POSIX for files on the same filesystem. On Windows, `fs.renameSync` is not atomic; the fix there is to use a platform-specific file lock. Note: the long-term fix (Phase 1) moves the registry into the DB as a `projects` table, making this moot.\n600: \n601: **Race 3: Multiple MCP server instances (Architecture W12).**\n602: \n603: Two Claude Code windows against the same project each start an MCP server. Each holds a connection. Both have WAL readers; writes are serialised by WAL automatically. Risk of data corruption: none (SQLite guarantees this). Risk of stale reads: possible if one writer commits while the other is mid-query. WAL snapshot isolation per transaction means neither session sees a partial write.\n604: \n605: Accepted posture (Phase 0): document WAL semantics; no application-level coordinator. Phase 1 DAO introduction is the natural place to add optional write queuing if metrics show contention.\n606: \n607: ### 6.3 `withRetry` helper (already implemented)\n608: \n609: `src/shared-db.ts:withRetry<T>(fn, maxRetries=3)` wraps any DB operation with exponential backoff on `SQLITE_BUSY`. Spin-wait between retries: 50 ms, 100 ms, 200 ms. Sufficient for the single-developer concurrency model. Not sufficient for a team sharing a DB file over a network filesystem (that scenario is out of scope; cloud sync uses CRDT, not shared filesystem).\n610: \n611: ### 6.4 Foreign key enforcement\n612: \n613: `PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON` is set on every connection. SQLite does not enforce FKs by default; this pragma must be set per-connection, not per-database. All cascade rules (`ON DELETE CASCADE`, `ON DELETE SET NULL`) depend on this being set before any write.\n614: \n615: Risk: a third-party tool (e.g., `sqlite3` CLI) that omits the pragma can silently break FK invariants. The Phase 2 audit table catches this after the fact; there is no pre-connection enforcement short of triggers.\n616: \n617: ---\n618: \n619: ## 7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n620: \n621: This section specifies the target DDL for all new tables introduced across Phases 0–7.\n622: These are not yet in `schema.sql`; they are introduced via numbered migrations (§9).\n623: \n624: ### 7.1 `schema_migrations` (Phase 0)\n625: \n626: ```sql\n627: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n628:   version     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n629:   name        TEXT    NOT NULL,\n630:   applied_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n631:   checksum    TEXT    NOT NULL\n632: );\n633: ```\n634: \n635: ### 7.2 `projects` (Phase 1 — registry in DB)\n636: \n637: Replaces `registry.json`. Enables atomic CAS updates and FK references.\n638: \n639: ```sql\n640: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS projects (\n641:   id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n642:   project_name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n643:   cwd          TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n644:   registered_at TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n645:   last_seen_at  TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n646:   workspace_id  TEXT,\n647:   metadata      TEXT                                  -- JSON blob for extensible fields\n648: );\n649: \n650: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_projects_cwd ON projects(cwd);\n651: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_projects_workspace ON projects(workspace_id);\n652: ```\n653: \n654: ### 7.3 `memory_embeddings` (Phase 1 — split from `memories`)\n655: \n656: Isolates the BLOB from the hot row. MCP queries never join this table. Embedding provider writes here; recall only touches it during the semantic fallback path.\n657: \n658: ```sql\n659: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_embeddings (\n660:   memory_id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n661:   provider    TEXT    NOT NULL,                  -- e.g. 'local-hash', 'claude-tool', 'onnx'\n662:   model       TEXT,                              -- model id or version used to generate\n663:   dimensions  INTEGER NOT NULL,\n664:   vec         BLOB    NOT NULL,                  -- float32 array, length = dimensions\n665:   generated_at TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n666: );\n667: ```\n668: \n669: Migration: `0006_split_embeddings.sql` — copies `memories.embedding` into this table for all rows where it is not null, then drops the `embedding` column from `memories`.\n670: \n671: After this migration, the MCP compact formatter no longer needs to strip embeddings — they are unreachable via the standard recall join.\n672: \n673: ### 7.4 `hook_events` (Phase 1 — structured observability)\n674: \n675: Append-only log of hook and MCP tool invocations. Solves Architecture W1 and W5.\n676: \n677: ```sql\n678: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS hook_events (\n679:   id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n680:   event_type  TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(event_type IN (\n681:                 'session_start','pre_compact','evaluate_session','update_context',\n682:                 'ltm_recall','ltm_learn','ltm_forget','ltm_relate',\n683:                 'ltm_context','ltm_context_items','ltm_graph','janitor_run')),\n684:   project_name TEXT,\n685:   session_id  TEXT,\n686:   status      TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(status IN ('ok','error','warn')),\n687:   latency_ms  INTEGER,\n688:   result_count INTEGER,                          -- rows returned (for recall)\n689:   error_msg   TEXT,                              -- populated on status='error'\n690:   payload     TEXT,                              -- JSON, optional; truncated to 1 KB\n691:   created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n692: );\n693: \n694: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_type ON hook_events(event_type, created_at DESC);\n695: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_project ON hook_events(project_name, created_at DESC);\n696: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_status ON hook_events(status, created_at DESC);\n697: ```\n698: \n699: Retention: rows older than 90 days are pruned by the janitor. `/openltm:health` aggregates from this table for latency p50/p95, error rates, and recall hit rates.\n700: \n701: ### 7.5 `memory_provenance` (Phase 2 — C5)\n702: \n703: One-to-many: a memory may have multiple provenance entries (e.g., originally from a git commit, later confirmed by EvaluateSession).\n704: \n705: ```sql\n706: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_provenance (\n707:   id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n708:   memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n709:   source_type TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(source_type IN (\n710:                 'learn','git-backfill','evaluate-session','import-bundle',\n711:                 'user-promotion','janitor-rollup','legacy')),\n712:   source_ref  TEXT,                              -- session_id, git SHA, bundle_id, etc.\n713:   actor       TEXT,                              -- 'mcp:ltm_learn', 'hook:evaluate_session', etc.\n714:   created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n715:   metadata    TEXT                               -- JSON; e.g. {\"turn\": 7, \"score\": 0.92}\n716: );\n717: \n718: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_provenance_memory ON memory_provenance(memory_id);\n719: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_provenance_source_type ON memory_provenance(source_type, created_at DESC);\n720: ```\n721: \n722: Backfill: all existing memories get a single `legacy` provenance row at migration time.\n723: \n724: ### 7.6 `memory_audit` (Phase 2 — W11, C5, C9)\n725: \n726: Append-only audit log. Every write to the `memories` table (insert, update, forget/deprecate, redact) produces an audit row. Powers time-travel (Phase 7) and `/openltm:admin audit`.\n727: \n728: ```sql\n729: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_audit (\n730:   id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n731:   memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- NOT FK: must survive memory deletion\n732:   op          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(op IN (\n733:                 'insert','update','forget','deprecate','supersede','redact','restore')),\n734:   actor       TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- 'mcp:ltm_learn', 'hook:evaluate_session', etc.\n735:   session_id  TEXT,\n736:   before_json TEXT,                             -- JSON snapshot of row before op (null for insert)\n737:   after_json  TEXT,                             -- JSON snapshot of row after op (null for delete)\n738:   created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n739: );\n740: \n741: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_memory ON memory_audit(memory_id, created_at DESC);\n742: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_op ON memory_audit(op, created_at DESC);\n743: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_session ON memory_audit(session_id, created_at DESC);\n744: ```\n745: \n746: Note: `memory_id` is intentionally **not** a foreign key. A forgotten memory must still have an audit trail. The audit row survives `DELETE FROM memories`.\n747: \n748: `before_json` and `after_json` store a JSON snapshot of the relevant columns (excluding `embedding` BLOB to avoid bloat). The Phase 7 replay engine uses these to reconstruct past states.\n749: \n750: ### 7.7 `team_bundles` (Phase 6 — C3)\n751: \n752: Tracks imported and exported memory bundles.\n753: \n754: ```sql\n755: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS team_bundles (\n756:   id            INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n757:   bundle_id     TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,         -- UUID, assigned at export time\n758:   direction     TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(direction IN ('export','import')),\n759:   status        TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(status IN ('pending','accepted','rejected','partial')),\n760:   signer_key_id TEXT,                            -- fingerprint of the signing keypair\n761:   signature     TEXT,                            -- base64-encoded Ed25519 signature\n762:   memory_count  INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n763:   source_peer   TEXT,                            -- optional: who sent the bundle\n764:   bundle_path   TEXT,                            -- local path to the .ltm-bundle file\n765:   created_at    TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n766:   reviewed_at   TEXT,\n767:   metadata      TEXT                             -- JSON: schema_version, export_format, etc.\n768: );\n769: \n770: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_bundles_status ON team_bundles(status, created_at DESC);\n771: ```\n772: \n773: ### 7.8 `bundle_memories` (Phase 6 — C3)\n774: \n775: Join table linking an imported bundle to the memories it created or attempted to create.\n776: \n777: ```sql\n778: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS bundle_memories (\n779:   bundle_id TEXT    NOT NULL REFERENCES team_bundles(bundle_id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n780:   memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n781:   import_status TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(import_status IN ('accepted','rejected','merged')),\n782:   merge_target_id INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n783:   PRIMARY KEY (bundle_id, memory_id)\n784: );\n785: ```\n786: \n787: ### 7.9 `signing_keys` (Phase 6 — C3)\n788: \n789: Trusted public keys for bundle verification.\n790: \n791: ```sql\n792: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS signing_keys (\n793:   key_id      TEXT PRIMARY KEY,                 -- fingerprint (SHA-256 of public key)\n794:   public_key  TEXT NOT NULL,                    -- base64-encoded Ed25519 public key\n795:   label       TEXT,                             -- human name, e.g. \"Tara's MacBook\"\n796:   trusted     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,       -- 0 = revoked\n797:   added_at    TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n798:   revoked_at  TEXT\n799: );\n800: ```\n801: \n802: ### 7.10 `memory_conflicts` (Phase 6 — C4)\n803: \n804: Staged conflicts detected by the Learn Engine's similarity check. User resolves at next SessionStart.\n805: \n806: ```sql\n807: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_conflicts (\n808:   id              INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n809:   incoming_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n810:   conflicting_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n811:   similarity_score REAL    NOT NULL,\n812:   conflict_type   TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(conflict_type IN ('duplicate','contradiction','overlap')),\n813:   resolution      TEXT    CHECK(resolution IN ('accepted','rejected','superseded','coexist')),\n814:   resolved_at     TEXT,\n815:   created_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n816: );\n817: \n818: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_conflicts_incoming ON memory_conflicts(incoming_memory_id);\n819: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_conflicts_resolution ON memory_conflicts(resolution, created_at DESC);\n820: ```\n821: \n822: ### 7.11 `sync_state` (Phase 6 — C2)\n823: \n824: CRDT sync bookkeeping for multi-device sync.\n825: \n826: ```sql\n827: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sync_state (\n828:   device_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- UUID assigned at first sync setup\n829:   seq         INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- monotonic sequence per device\n830:   last_push_at TEXT,\n831:   last_pull_at TEXT,\n832:   relay_url   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- E2E relay endpoint\n833:   PRIMARY KEY (device_id)\n834: );\n835: \n836: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sync_ops (\n837:   id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n838:   device_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,\n839:   seq         INTEGER NOT NULL,\n840:   op_type     TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(op_type IN ('insert','forget','relate','tag')),\n841:   target_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- memory_id or relation_id\n842:   payload_enc TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- base64(AES-GCM(JSON op payload))\n843:   created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n844:   applied_at  TEXT,\n845:   UNIQUE(device_id, seq)\n846: );\n847: \n848: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sync_ops_device ON sync_ops(device_id, seq);\n849: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sync_ops_applied ON sync_ops(applied_at);\n850: ```\n851: \n852: ### 7.12 Versioning tables (Phase 7 — C9, C10)\n853: \n854: The `memory_audit` table (§7.6) is the primary source for time-travel. Phase 7 adds a\n855: snapshot mechanism for efficient point-in-time reconstruction.\n856: \n857: ```sql\n858: -- Named snapshots (created by /openltm:memory snapshot or by janitor nightly)\n859: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_snapshots (\n860:   id            INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n861:   label         TEXT,                           -- human-readable, e.g. \"before Phase 4 migration\"\n862:   snapshot_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n863:   memory_count  INTEGER NOT NULL,\n864:   created_by    TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(created_by IN ('janitor','user','migration'))\n865: );\n866: \n867: -- Memory state at snapshot time (for replay without replaying all audit ops)\n868: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS snapshot_memories (\n869:   snapshot_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memory_snapshots(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n870:   memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- not FK; memory may be deleted\n871:   state_json  TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- JSON of memories row at snapshot time\n872:   PRIMARY KEY (snapshot_id, memory_id)\n873: );\n874: \n875: CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_snapshots_at ON memory_snapshots(snapshot_at DESC);\n876: ```\n877: \n878: ---\n879: \n880: ## 8. Performance at Scale\n881: \n882: ### 8.1 Scale tiers\n883: \n884: | Tier | Memory count | Expected user | Risk |\n885: |------|-------------|--------------|------|\n886: | Small | 0–1 000 | Most users | None |\n887: | Medium | 1 000–10 000 | Power users, 1–2 years of dogfooding | Low |\n888: | Large | 10 000–100 000 | Enterprise devs, GitLearn backfill over large repos | W4 semantic fallback |\n889: | Extreme | 100 000–1 000 000 | Theoretical; team bundle accumulation | FTS5 limits |\n890: \n891: ### 8.2 Storage estimates\n892: \n893: | Component | Per-row cost | At 10k | At 100k |\n894: |-----------|-------------|--------|---------|\n895: | `memories` (text only, no embedding) | ~500 bytes avg | 5 MB | 50 MB |\n896: | `memories.embedding` (1536 float32) | ~6 KB | 60 MB | 600 MB |\n897: | `memories_fts` shadow tables | ~30% of content size | 1.5 MB | 15 MB |\n898: | `memory_audit` (2 JSON snapshots per op) | ~1 KB avg | 10 MB (if all ops logged) | 100 MB |\n899: | `hook_events` (90-day retention) | ~200 bytes | ~2 MB/90d | ~2 MB/90d |\n900: \n901: **Key insight:** the `embedding` BLOB dominates. After the Phase 1 split into `memory_embeddings`, the base `memories` table stays lean (5–50 MB range), and `memory_embeddings` is accessed only on the semantic fallback path.\n902: \n903: ### 8.3 Query plan at scale\n904: \n905: **FTS5 recall at 100k memories:**\n906: \n907: FTS5 uses an inverted index. A MATCH query on a common two-word phrase returns a sorted list of matching rowids in O(log T + k) where T is the total token count and k is the result count. At 100k memories the inverted index is ~15 MB (loaded pages). First query may incur page faults; subsequent queries benefit from OS page cache.\n908: \n909: Expected latency: 5–20 ms at 100k for the FTS5 phase. This is well within budget.\n910: \n911: **Semantic fallback at 100k memories (current):**\n912: \n913: Reads all `embedding` BLOBs: 600 MB of BLOB data. Typical SQLite read throughput: 200–500 MB/s from SSD. Estimate: 1.2–3 s for a full scan. Catastrophically slow.\n914: \n915: **Mitigation strategies:**\n916: \n917: 1. **Phase 1 (immediate):** Move embeddings to `memory_embeddings`. The fallback now requires an explicit join. Recall queries that do not trigger fallback never touch the table.\n918: 2. **Phase 3 (ANN index, stretch):** Integrate `sqlite-vss` or a comparable SQLite extension for approximate nearest-neighbour search over the embedding table. Reduces semantic search from O(N) to O(log N). This requires bundling a native extension — evaluate feasibility against the zero-dependency goal (ADR-001).\n919: 3. **Phase 4 (materialised decay_score):** Eliminates JS-side rank multiplication; the recall query is a single indexed SQL ORDER BY.\n920: \n921: **Fallback threshold tuning:**\n922: \n923: The semantic fallback triggers at < 3 FTS5 results. At 100k memories, queries that hit this threshold typically involve rare or paraphrased terms. Adding a configurable `settings.recall.fts_min_results` (default 3) allows users to disable semantic fallback entirely until Phase 3 ANN is ready.\n924: \n925: ### 8.4 Mitigation strategies summary\n926: \n927: | Problem | Phase | Mitigation |\n928: |---------|-------|-----------|\n929: | Embedding BLOB in hot row | 1 | Split to `memory_embeddings` |\n930: | O(N) semantic fallback scan | 3 | ANN index (stretch) or disable fallback |\n931: | O(N) JS decay multiply | 4 | Materialised `decay_score` |\n932: | FTS5 index growth | 4 | Janitor archival of deprecated memories |\n933: | `memory_audit` unbounded growth | 4 | Janitor prunes rows > 1 year; snapshots consolidate |\n934: | `hook_events` growth | 1 | 90-day retention enforced by janitor |\n935: \n936: ### 8.5 VACUUM and ANALYZE schedule\n937: \n938: SQLite auto-analyzes when a table changes significantly (controlled by `PRAGMA analysis_limit`). Manual schedule:\n939: \n940: - `PRAGMA ANALYZE;` — run by janitor weekly; updates query planner statistics.\n941: - `PRAGMA VACUUM;` — **not** scheduled automatically; recommended after large deletions (e.g., after a bulk `forget` or deprecated memory archival). Document in `/openltm:admin` as a manual command.\n942: - `PRAGMA wal_checkpoint(TRUNCATE);` — run by janitor after each pass to truncate the WAL file and reclaim disk space.\n943: \n944: ---\n945: \n946: ## 9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n947: \n948: This section maps each ROADMAP phase to its concrete DDL changes. Migration files live in `db/migrations/`. The Phase 0 `schema_migrations` table is the runner; subsequent migrations are executed by `src/migrator.ts`.\n949: \n950: ### Phase 0 — Foundation Hardening (v1.5.x)\n951: \n952: Goal: replace hand-rolled migrations, add hot-path indexes, advisory locking.\n953: \n954: | File | DDL summary |\n955: |------|-------------|\n956: | `0001_initial_schema_backfill.sql` | INSERT sentinel row into `schema_migrations`; records all existing hasColumn guards as applied |\n957: | `0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql` | `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_status_importance ON memories(status, importance DESC);` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_created_at ON memories(created_at);` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_last_recalled_at ON memories(last_recalled_at);` `CREATE INDEX idx_ctx_project_type_created ON context_items(project_name, type, created_at DESC);` |\n958: | `0003_schema_migrations_table.sql` | `CREATE TABLE schema_migrations (version, name, applied_at, checksum)` (self-bootstrapping) |\n959: \n960: Breaking: none. Backwards-compatible.\n961: \n962: Rollback: indexes can be dropped; `schema_migrations` can be dropped without data loss.\n963: \n964: ### Phase 1 — DAO + Observability (v1.6.x)\n965: \n966: Goal: split embeddings, add projects table, add hook_events log.\n967: \n968: | File | DDL summary |\n969: |------|-------------|\n970: | `0004_add_projects_table.sql` | `CREATE TABLE projects (id, project_name UNIQUE, cwd UNIQUE, ...)` with indexes; backfill from `registry.json` content |\n971: | `0005_add_hook_events.sql` | `CREATE TABLE hook_events (id, event_type, project_name, session_id, status, latency_ms, result_count, error_msg, payload, created_at)` with indexes |\n972: | `0006_split_embeddings.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_embeddings (memory_id PK, provider, model, dimensions, vec, generated_at);` `INSERT INTO memory_embeddings SELECT id, 'legacy', NULL, 0, embedding, datetime('now') FROM memories WHERE embedding IS NOT NULL;` `ALTER TABLE memories DROP COLUMN embedding;` (SQLite >= 3.35.0 required) |\n973: \n974: Note on `DROP COLUMN`: Bun ships SQLite 3.45+; this is safe. Add a version guard in the migration runner.\n975: \n976: Breaking: none at MCP contract level. Internal: the `embedding` column disappears from `memories`; any code reading it directly must be updated (DAO refactor happens in Phase 1 code work).\n977: \n978: Rollback: `0006` has a down migration that re-adds the column and copies data back from `memory_embeddings`.\n979: \n980: ### Phase 2 — Provenance + Audit (v1.7.x)\n981: \n982: Goal: every write auditable, every memory traceable.\n983: \n984: | File | DDL summary |\n985: |------|-------------|\n986: | `0007_add_memory_provenance.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_provenance (id, memory_id FK, source_type, source_ref, actor, created_at, metadata)` with indexes; backfill all existing memories with `source_type='legacy'` |\n987: | `0008_add_memory_audit.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_audit (id, memory_id, op, actor, session_id, before_json, after_json, created_at)` with indexes; no backfill (audit is forward-only) |\n988: \n989: Breaking: none. Optional fields added to recall results.\n990: \n991: ### Phase 3 — Embedding Provider Abstraction (v1.8.x)\n992: \n993: Goal: FTS5 gains category column; `memory_embeddings.provider` enables multi-provider.\n994: \n995: | File | DDL summary |\n996: |------|-------------|\n997: | `0009_fts_add_category.sql` | `DROP TABLE memories_fts;` Rebuild with `content, category` columns; rebuild triggers; full re-index via `INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content, category) SELECT id, content, category FROM memories WHERE status='active';` |\n998: \n999: Note: `DROP TABLE memories_fts` and rebuild requires exclusive access. The migrator wraps this in `BEGIN EXCLUSIVE; ...; COMMIT;`.\n1000: \n1001: Breaking: FTS trigger DDL changes; any code constructing raw FTS queries must update.\n1002: \n1003: ### Phase 4 — Janitor (v1.9.x)\n1004: \n1005: Goal: materialise decay_score; janitor archival.\n1006: \n1007: | File | DDL summary |\n1008: |------|-------------|\n1009: | `0010_add_decay_score.sql` | `ALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN decay_score REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0;` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_decay_score ON memories(decay_score DESC);` Initial backfill: `UPDATE memories SET decay_score = 1.0;` (janitor will compute real values on first run) |\n1010: | `0011_add_janitor_settings.sql` | `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('janitor.enabled', 'true', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('janitor.last_run_at', '', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('decay.half_life_days', '90', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('decay.immortal_importance', '5', datetime('now'));` |\n1011: \n1012: Breaking: none. `decay_score` defaults to 1.0 until janitor first runs.\n1013: \n1014: ### Phase 5 — Cross-Plugin Contract (v2.0.0, semver-major)\n1015: \n1016: Goal: stable versioned MCP write surface; registry fully in DB.\n1017: \n1018: | File | DDL summary |\n1019: |------|-------------|\n1020: | `0012_finalize_projects_table.sql` | Add `contract_version TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '1'` to `projects`; add index on `workspace_id`; make `cwd` the primary lookup for all hook code |\n1021: | `0013_drop_deprecated_columns.sql` | Drop any columns marked deprecated in earlier phases (post major-version gate only) |\n1022: \n1023: Breaking: major version. MIGRATION.md documents removed columns and renamed tools.\n1024: \n1025: ### Phase 6 — Sync + Bundles (v2.1.x)\n1026: \n1027: Goal: team bundles, signing, conflict detection, sync state.\n1028: \n1029: | File | DDL summary |\n1030: |------|-------------|\n1031: | `0014_add_team_bundles.sql` | `CREATE TABLE team_bundles (...)` as specified in §7.7; `CREATE TABLE bundle_memories (...)` as §7.8 |\n1032: | `0015_add_signing_keys.sql` | `CREATE TABLE signing_keys (...)` as §7.9 |\n1033: | `0016_add_memory_conflicts.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_conflicts (...)` as §7.10 |\n1034: | `0017_add_sync_tables.sql` | `CREATE TABLE sync_state (...)` as §7.11; `CREATE TABLE sync_ops (...)` |\n1035: \n1036: Breaking: none at contract level. New opt-in tables; existing users unaffected.\n1037: \n1038: ### Phase 7 — Time-Travel + Diffing (v2.2.x)\n1039: \n1040: Goal: snapshot mechanism for efficient replay and diff.\n1041: \n1042: | File | DDL summary |\n1043: |------|-------------|\n1044: | `0018_add_snapshots.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_snapshots (...)` as §7.12; `CREATE TABLE snapshot_memories (...)` |\n1045: | `0019_seed_initial_snapshot.sql` | Insert a snapshot row for the current DB state at migration time so that `/openltm:memory replay` has a baseline |\n1046: \n1047: Breaking: none.\n1048: \n1049: ### Backwards-compatibility ledger\n1050: \n1051: | Phase | Schema breaking | MCP contract breaking | Data loss risk |\n1052: |-------|----------------|-----------------------|---------------|\n1053: | 0 | No | No | None |\n1054: | 1 | Idempotent migration; `embedding` column dropped (DAO abstracts it) | No | None if `memory_embeddings` backfill runs first |\n1055: | 2 | Adds columns/tables | Adds optional recall fields | None |\n1056: | 3 | FTS rebuild required (downtime ~1s per 10k memories) | Adds optional FTS fields | None |\n1057: | 4 | Adds column; janitor controlled | No | None |\n1058: | 5 | Removes deprecated columns | **Yes — semver major** | Columns removed; data in superseding columns |\n1059: | 6 | Adds tables | Adds optional tools | None |\n1060: | 7 | Adds tables | Adds optional tools | None |\n1061: \n1062: ---\n1063: \n1064: ## Appendix A — Entity-Relationship Diagram (Target State)\n1065: \n1066: ```\n1067: memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n1068: tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n1069: memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source\"\n1070: memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"target\"\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-1070. Use offset=1071 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n\n**Version:** 1.0\n**Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n**Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n**Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n**Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n\nThis document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\nthe current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\nthe migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\nat scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n\n`ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\ndoc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\nin §9 below.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","text":"# DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n\n**Version:** 1.0\n**Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n**Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n**Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n**Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n\nThis document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\nthe current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\nthe migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\nat scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n\n`ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\ndoc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\nin §9 below.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. Current Schema — Annotated\n2. Index Strategy Analysis\n3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n4. Memory Decay Model\n5. Migration System\n6. Concurrency and Safety\n7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n8. Performance at Scale\n9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n\nThe entire data store is one SQLite file: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/OpenLtm-openltm/openltm.db`.\nAccessed exclusively through `src/shared-db.ts:getDb()`. WAL mode, foreign keys on,\nbusy_timeout 5 000 ms set on every connection.\n\nSchema source of truth: `src/schema.sql` (initial tables + FTS + triggers).\nMigration overlay: `src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` (idempotent column adds).\n\n### 1.1 `memories`\n\nThe core table. Every durable insight the plugin has stored, whether from `learn`,\nGitLearn backfill, EvaluateSession, or bundle import.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE memories (\n  id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  -- Content and classification\n  content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n                      'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n  importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n  confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n  source            TEXT,                       -- free-text provenance hint (pre-Phase 2)\n  project_scope     TEXT,                       -- NULL = global; else project_name\n  dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,             -- normalised hash; prevents repeat learns\n\n  -- Timestamps\n  created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n\n  -- Lifecycle (Phase 2 migration, now in schema.sql)\n  status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n                      'active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n\n  -- Embedding (Phase 1 split candidate)\n  embedding         BLOB,                       -- float32 vector; stripped from MCP responses\n\n  -- Recall telemetry (Phase 3 migration)\n  last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  first_recalled_at TEXT,\n  last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n  recall_count      INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n\n  -- Supersession chain (Phase 2 migration)\n  superseded_by     INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  superseded_at     TEXT,\n\n  -- Multi-agent metadata (T16 migration)\n  workspace_id      TEXT,\n  agent_id          TEXT\n);\n```\n\n**Column rationale**\n\n| Column | Rationale |\n|--------|-----------|\n| `category` | Six-value enum enforced by CHECK; drives the SessionStart injection filter (importance-5 + category) |\n| `importance` | 1–5 ordinal; 5 = immortal (no decay); drives every-session injection threshold |\n| `confidence` | Reserved for EvaluateSession and the future janitor's auto-demotion logic; not yet surfaced to users |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents a session that keeps re-learning the same fact from polluting the table; computed by the Learn Engine as a normalised content hash |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global (injected in all sessions); non-null = scoped to one project (joined against the `registry.json` project_name) |\n| `status` | Soft-delete / workflow state; recall queries filter to `status = 'active'` |\n| `embedding` | Stored as a raw BLOB (float32 array). At 1536 dimensions = ~6 KB per row; serialised to JSON over MCP it becomes ~260 KB. The compact formatter strips it before every MCP response. Phase 1 moves it to a separate table. |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Inputs to the recall-time decay calculation. `last_used_at` covers both learn-time touch and recall-time touch; `last_recalled_at` covers recall only. |\n| `superseded_by` | Self-referential FK; forms the supersession chain for time-travel (Phase 7) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | Multi-agent isolation (ROADMAP Phase 5 / T16); both indexed |\n\n### 1.2 `context_items`\n\nPer-project short-term context. Replaces the four Markdown files that existed before v1.0.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE context_items (\n  id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n  content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup across same session\n  permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-trim (decision, gotcha)\n  memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,  -- Phase 1 migration\n  status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n                 'active','pending_promotion','promoted')),          -- Phase 2 migration\n  created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  workspace_id TEXT,                          -- T16 multi-agent isolation\n  agent_id     TEXT                           -- T16\n);\n```\n\n**Lifecycle by type**\n\n| Type | `permanent` | Trim rule |\n|------|-------------|-----------|\n| `goal` | 0 | Replaced when a new goal is written |\n| `decision` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed; manual removal only |\n| `progress` | 0 | Trimmed to last 20 per project by UpdateContext hook |\n| `gotcha` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed |\n\n**`status` flow**\n\n```\nactive -> pending_promotion -> promoted\n                           (memory_id set once promoted to memories table)\n```\n\n### 1.3 `tags` and `memory_tags`\n\nMany-to-many tagging for memories. Tags are auto-created on use; the dictionary is normalised to avoid duplication.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE tags (\n  id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE memory_tags (\n  memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n);\n```\n\nNo additional indexes needed: the composite PK covers `(memory_id, tag_id)` lookup; `ON DELETE CASCADE` keeps the join table clean without a separate job.\n\n### 1.4 `memory_relations`\n\nKnowledge graph edges. Six typed relationship directions. Used by `relate` and traversed by `graph` (BFS via `src/graph.ts`).\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE memory_relations (\n  id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n                      'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n  created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n);\n```\n\nThe UNIQUE constraint on the triple prevents duplicate edges for the same relationship type. Cascade on both FKs means deleting a memory automatically prunes all edges.\n\n### 1.5 `memories_fts`\n\nFTS5 external-content virtual table. Shadows `memories.content`. Maintained by three triggers.\n\n```sql\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n  content,\n  content='memories',\n  content_rowid='id'\n);\n\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\nEND;\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\nEND;\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\nEND;\n```\n\nSee §3 for full FTS5 configuration analysis.\n\n### 1.6 `settings`\n\nKey-value store for janitor configuration, provider selection, decay parameters, and\nfeature flags.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE settings (\n  key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n  value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n  updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n```\n\nKnown keys (as of v1.4.20):\n\n| Key | Expected type | Purpose |\n|-----|--------------|---------|\n| `decay.half_life_days` | integer | Days before a non-recalled memory halves its rank boost |\n| `decay.immortal_importance` | integer | Importance threshold above which decay is skipped |\n| `embedding.provider` | string | `null` / `local-hash` / `claude-tool` / `onnx` |\n| `janitor.enabled` | boolean | Master switch for Phase 4 janitor |\n| `janitor.last_run_at` | ISO8601 | Timestamp of last janitor pass |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n\n### 2.1 Existing indexes\n\n| Index | Table | Columns | Rationale |\n|-------|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `idx_ctx_project` | `context_items` | `project_name` | SessionStart: `WHERE project_name = ?` |\n| `idx_ctx_type` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type)` | SessionStart per-type fetch; composite covers both equality predicates |\n| `idx_memories_category` | `memories` | `category` | Filter by category in recall and health commands |\n| `idx_memories_project` | `memories` | `project_scope` | Scoped recall: `WHERE project_scope = ? OR project_scope IS NULL` |\n| `idx_memories_importance` | `memories` | `importance DESC` | SessionStart global injection (`importance = 5`); importance ordering |\n| `idx_memories_confidence` | `memories` | `confidence DESC` | Future janitor demotion; currently unused on hot path |\n| `idx_memories_status` | `memories` | `status` | All read paths filter `status = 'active'` |\n| `idx_memories_last_used` | `memories` | `last_used_at` | Decay input; janitor staleness scan |\n| `idx_memories_superseded` | `memories` | `superseded_by` | Supersession chain traversal |\n| `idx_memories_recall_count` | `memories` | `recall_count DESC` | Health reporting: top-recalled memories |\n| `idx_memories_workspace` | `memories` | `workspace_id` | T16 multi-agent isolation |\n| `idx_memories_agent` | `memories` | `agent_id` | T16 |\n| `idx_relations_source` | `memory_relations` | `source_memory_id` | BFS forward traversal |\n| `idx_relations_target` | `memory_relations` | `target_memory_id` | BFS reverse traversal |\n\n### 2.2 Hot-path scan analysis\n\n**Hot path 1: `recall` (most frequent)**\n\nQuery skeleton:\n```sql\nSELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.last_recalled_at, m.recall_count\nFROM memories_fts\nJOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\nWHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n  AND m.status = 'active'\n  AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)\nORDER BY memories_fts.rank, m.importance DESC\nLIMIT 10;\n```\n\nHits: `memories_fts` (FTS5 own index), `idx_memories_status`, `idx_memories_project`.\nGap: the `ORDER BY` applies FTS5 BM25 rank then falls back to a table scan for `importance DESC`. A covering index on `(status, project_scope, importance DESC)` would eliminate the table scan for the secondary sort. This is a low-priority improvement since FTS5 already constrains the result set to a small rowid list.\n\n**Hot path 2: SessionStart context injection**\n\nQuery skeleton:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM context_items\nWHERE project_name = ? AND status = 'active'\nORDER BY type, created_at;\n\nSELECT * FROM memories\nWHERE status = 'active' AND importance = 5 AND project_scope IS NULL\nORDER BY importance DESC, last_recalled_at DESC\nLIMIT 15;\n```\n\nHits: `idx_ctx_type` (covers both predicates), `idx_memories_importance` + `idx_memories_status`.\nGap: the memories query uses a range scan on importance filtered by status. A compound index `(status, importance DESC)` would be a covering scan. Add in Phase 0.\n\n**Hot path 3: UpdateContext progress trim**\n\n```sql\nDELETE FROM context_items\nWHERE project_name = ? AND type = 'progress'\n  AND id NOT IN (\n    SELECT id FROM context_items\n    WHERE project_name = ? AND type = 'progress'\n    ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 20\n  );\n```\n\nHits: `idx_ctx_type`. Sub-select is a sequential scan of the progress partition per project. At <= 20 rows per project this is fine; the outer DELETE hit count is always near zero.\n\n### 2.3 Missing indexes (to add in migrations)\n\n| Index to add | Table | Columns | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `idx_memories_status_importance` | `memories` | `(status, importance DESC)` | Hot path 2: eliminates filter + sort split |\n| `idx_memories_created_at` | `memories` | `created_at` | Decay calculation, janitor oldest-first scan |\n| `idx_memories_last_recalled_at` | `memories` | `last_recalled_at` | Decay input; janitor stale scan |\n| `idx_ctx_project_type_created` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type, created_at DESC)` | UpdateContext trim sub-select; also SessionStart per-type ordered fetch |\n\nPhase 0 migration file: `0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n\n### 3.1 Current configuration\n\n```sql\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n  content,\n  content='memories',\n  content_rowid='id'\n);\n```\n\n- **Tokenizer:** SQLite default (`unicode61`). Handles Unicode casing and stemming at the Unicode 6.1 level. Adequate for English natural-language memories; does not do language-specific stemming.\n- **Content mode:** External-content (`content='memories'`). The FTS index does not store original text; it defers to the base table for snippets. This halves FTS storage cost at the price of a join on every snippet request.\n- **`content_rowid='id'`:** Maps FTS rowids directly to `memories.id`. The JOIN in recall queries is a rowid lookup — O(log N) on the B-tree.\n- **Triggers:** Three triggers keep the index in sync (insert, delete, update). These are synchronous — no async lag. They run inside the same transaction as the base table write.\n\n### 3.2 BM25 ranking\n\nFTS5's built-in `rank` function is BM25. Default parameters: `b=0.75, k1=1.2`. No column weights configured (single-column index).\n\nThe Recall Engine applies a post-BM25 multiplier in TypeScript:\n\n```\nfinal_score = bm25_rank * importance_weight * decay_factor * recency_boost\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `importance_weight` = 1.0 + (importance - 1) * 0.25 (range 1.0–2.0)\n- `decay_factor` = computed per §4\n- `recency_boost` = 1.0 + clamp(30 - days_since_recalled, 0, 30) / 30 * 0.5\n\n### 3.3 Query patterns\n\n**Primary (keyword):**\n```sql\nSELECT memories_fts.rowid, memories_fts.rank\nFROM memories_fts\nWHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\nORDER BY rank;\n```\n\nFTS5 MATCH operators in use: phrase search (`\"exact phrase\"`), prefix (`word*`), implicit AND for multi-word queries.\n\n**Semantic fallback (triggered when FTS5 returns < 3 results):**\n\nThe semantic path reads all active memories with an `embedding` BLOB, computes cosine similarity in TypeScript against the query embedding, and merges with the FTS5 results. This is an O(N) scan — see §4.2 for the scale problem and §7 for the Phase 1 `memory_embeddings` split that isolates this cost.\n\n**Merge and dedup:**\n\nResults from both paths are merged by `id`. Duplicates are resolved by taking the higher score. The combined list is re-ranked by `final_score` before top-N truncation.\n\n### 3.4 FTS5 integrity\n\nExternal-content tables are not self-healing: if the base table is modified outside the trigger path (e.g., a direct `UPDATE` via `sqlite3` CLI), the FTS index will drift. Detection:\n\n```sql\nINSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts) VALUES ('integrity-check');\n```\n\nReturns OK if the shadow tables are consistent. A Phase 0 `ltm:admin` sub-command should run this check on demand.\n\n### 3.5 Planned improvements\n\n- **Phase 0:** Add a `PRAGMA integrity_check` wrapper and an FTS integrity check to `/openltm:admin`.\n- **Phase 3:** Add a `category` column to `memories_fts` so category filtering can be pushed into the FTS query rather than applied as a post-filter join:\n  ```sql\n  CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n    content, category,\n    content='memories', content_rowid='id'\n  );\n  ```\n  This doubles the trigger complexity (both columns must be maintained) but enables:\n  ```sql\n  WHERE memories_fts MATCH 'category:gotcha AND <query>'\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Memory Decay Model\n\n### 4.1 Current implementation\n\nDecay is computed **at recall time** in TypeScript. No stored score. The inputs are columns already on `memories`:\n\n| Input | Column | Role |\n|-------|---------|------|\n| Age | `created_at` | Base staleness |\n| Last touched | `last_recalled_at` | Freshness signal |\n| Frequency | `recall_count` | Utility signal |\n| Weight | `importance` | Override signal |\n\n**Current rules (approximate, inferred from Recall Engine source):**\n\n1. If `importance == 5`, skip decay entirely. Score = BM25 * importance_weight.\n2. Else compute `days_stale = (now - last_recalled_at) in days`.\n3. If `days_stale > 90 AND importance < 3`:\n   ```\n   decay_factor = max(0.1, 1 - (days_stale - 90) / 365)\n   ```\n   Linear decay from 1.0 at day 90 to ~0.1 at day 455.\n4. If `days_stale <= 30`: apply recency boost (`+0 to +50%`).\n5. Else: `decay_factor = 1.0` (no decay for mid-range memories).\n\n**Decay function shape:** piecewise linear. The exact shape remains OQ3 (open question in ROADMAP §5) to be resolved in Phase 4 with real recall telemetry.\n\n### 4.2 The O(N) problem (Architecture W4)\n\nThe current implementation fetches the full FTS5 result set (typically up to 50 rows from a BM25 scan), then applies the decay multiplier in JavaScript for each row. At 10k memories the FTS5 result set is well-bounded; the JS multiplication is negligible.\n\nAt 100k+ memories, the semantic fallback path scans all rows with an embedding BLOB, computing cosine similarity for each. This is O(N) and breaks the 200 ms recall budget.\n\nThe problem has two distinct components:\n\n| Component | Current | At 100k |\n|-----------|---------|---------|\n| FTS5 BM25 scan | O(log N + k) rowids | Bounded; fast |\n| JavaScript decay multiply | O(k) where k = result set | Bounded; fast |\n| Semantic fallback (embedding scan) | O(N) across all rows | **Slow: ~500ms estimated** |\n| Final merge and sort | O(k log k) | Bounded |\n\n### 4.3 Fix spec: materialised `decay_score` (Phase 4)\n\nAdd a `decay_score REAL` column to `memories`. A low-frequency janitor process refreshes it on a schedule (nightly by default, configurable via `settings`).\n\n**Migration:** `0012_add_decay_score.sql`\n```sql\nALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN decay_score REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0;\nCREATE INDEX idx_memories_decay_score ON memories(decay_score DESC);\n```\n\n**Janitor refresh logic (pseudo-SQL):**\n```sql\nUPDATE memories\nSET decay_score = CASE\n  WHEN importance = 5 THEN 1.0\n  WHEN julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) > 90\n    AND importance < 3\n    THEN MAX(0.1,\n      1.0 - (julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) - 90.0) / 365.0\n    )\n  WHEN julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at) <= 30\n    THEN MIN(1.5,\n      1.0 + (30.0 - (julianday('now') - julianday(last_recalled_at))) / 30.0 * 0.5\n    )\n  ELSE 1.0\nEND\nWHERE status = 'active';\n```\n\n**Recall query after Phase 4:**\n```sql\nSELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.decay_score,\n       (memories_fts.rank * (1.0 + (m.importance - 1) * 0.25) * m.decay_score) AS final_score\nFROM memories_fts\nJOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\nWHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n  AND m.status = 'active'\n  AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)\nORDER BY final_score DESC\nLIMIT 10;\n```\n\nThe decay multiply moves into SQL, uses the pre-materialised `decay_score`, and the query becomes O(log N + k). The semantic fallback becomes the only O(N) path, resolved by the `memory_embeddings` split (Phase 1) and an ANN index (Phase 3 stretch goal).\n\n**Trade-off:** Write amplification. Every `learn` does not update `decay_score` — the janitor does. There is a staleness window of up to 24 hours. This is acceptable: decay is a rank modifier, not a hard filter. A freshly-learned memory has `decay_score = 1.0` (default) which is correct.\n\n**Janitor run record:** stored in `settings` as `janitor.last_run_at`. The `/openltm:health` command surfaces it.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Migration System\n\n### 5.1 Current risks (Architecture W3)\n\n`src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` is an imperative list of `hasColumn` guards followed by `ALTER TABLE` statements. Problems:\n\n1. **No migration history.** There is no record of which migrations have run against a given DB. If a migration is renamed or reordered, it may re-run or be skipped silently.\n2. **No version table.** Impossible to answer \"what schema version is this DB?\" from outside the code.\n3. **No rollback path.** Each migration is a one-way `ALTER TABLE`. There is no down-migration.\n4. **Order coupling.** Migrations are ordered by their position in a single function. Adding a migration in the middle risks breaking callers that depend on run order.\n5. **No checksum.** A migration can be silently edited after it has run; there is no detection.\n6. **Testing gap.** The migration function is tested only indirectly via integration tests on the full DB. No isolated migration unit test.\n\n### 5.2 Spec: `schema_migrations` table (Phase 0)\n\nAdd a `schema_migrations` table that is the source of truth for migration state.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n  version     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,             -- monotonic integer, e.g. 1, 2, 3\n  name        TEXT    NOT NULL,                -- human-readable slug, e.g. 'add_hot_path_indexes'\n  applied_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  checksum    TEXT    NOT NULL                 -- SHA-256 hex of the migration SQL file content\n);\n```\n\n**Migration file naming convention:**\n```\ndb/migrations/NNNN_<slug>.sql\n```\n\nWhere `NNNN` is a zero-padded four-digit integer. Example:\n```\ndb/migrations/0001_initial_schema.sql\ndb/migrations/0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql\ndb/migrations/0003_schema_migrations_table.sql\n```\n\nThe migration runner (`src/migrator.ts`, Phase 0):\n\n1. Ensure `schema_migrations` table exists (self-bootstrapping DDL).\n2. Read all `db/migrations/*.sql` files, sorted by version number.\n3. For each file: check if `version` exists in `schema_migrations`. If not:\n   - Compute SHA-256 of file content.\n   - Execute the SQL inside a transaction.\n   - INSERT into `schema_migrations(version, name, checksum)`.\n4. If `version` exists: compare stored checksum vs. current file checksum. If mismatch, log a warning (do not fail; the file may have been legitimately patched post-apply with a comment).\n5. Replace `runMigrations()` in `shared-db.ts` with a call to `runMigrator(db)`.\n\n**Backfill migration (0001):** represents the state after all current `hasColumn` guards have run. No SQL needed; just insert a sentinel row:\n```sql\nINSERT OR IGNORE INTO schema_migrations(version, name, checksum)\nVALUES (1, 'initial_schema_backfill', 'backfilled');\n```\n\n**Rollback posture.** SQLite does not support `DROP COLUMN` before version 3.35.0 and many embeddings use older versions. Rollback migrations are therefore not always possible. The policy:\n\n- Additive migrations (ADD COLUMN, CREATE TABLE, CREATE INDEX): always rollback-possible with a companion `_down.sql` file (not executed automatically; manual emergency only).\n- Destructive migrations (DROP TABLE, DROP COLUMN): must include an explicit \"data loss acknowledged\" comment in the migration file and must be gated on a major version bump.\n\n### 5.3 Migration runner location\n\n`src/migrator.ts` — called from `shared-db.ts:getDb()` after WAL mode and foreign keys are set, before `schema.sql` is executed. Sequence:\n\n```\ngetDb()\n  -> PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL; foreign_keys=ON; busy_timeout=5000;\n  -> runMigrator(db)           // versioned migrations first\n  -> exec(schema.sql)          // idempotent CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS (no-ops after first run)\n```\n\nThe `schema.sql` file must remain idempotent (`CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`, `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS`) so it is safe to re-execute after migrations.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Concurrency and Safety\n\n### 6.1 WAL mode\n\nSet at connection open:\n```sql\nPRAGMA journal_mode=WAL;\nPRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;\nPRAGMA busy_timeout=5000;\n```\n\nWAL mode permits concurrent readers with a single writer. Multiple readers never block each other. A writer blocks only other writers. The 5 000 ms busy timeout provides graceful retry for the second writer rather than an immediate `SQLITE_BUSY` error.\n\n### 6.2 Current race conditions\n\n**Race 1: Two Claude Code sessions starting simultaneously.**\n\nBoth spawn a `SessionStart` hook. Both call `runMigrations()` concurrently against the same DB. `ALTER TABLE` statements inside migrations are not atomic across processes.\n\nRisk: one process runs `ALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN workspace_id TEXT` while the other is mid-read. With WAL, the ALTER acquires an EXCLUSIVE lock momentarily; the reader retries. The busy_timeout absorbs this for 5 s. Actual risk of corruption: low. Actual risk of a 5 s stall on session start: real.\n\n**Fix (Phase 0):** Wrap `runMigrations()` (replaced by `runMigrator()`) in an advisory lock:\n```sql\nBEGIN IMMEDIATE;\n-- migration DDL here\nCOMMIT;\n```\n\n`BEGIN IMMEDIATE` acquires a RESERVED lock, blocking other writers without blocking readers. If a second migrator tries `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` concurrently, it waits up to `busy_timeout` (5 s). After Phase 0, migration runs are idempotent checks (row existence) so the critical section is tiny.\n\n**Race 2: Concurrent writes to `registry.json` (Architecture W2).**\n\nTwo sessions auto-registering different cwds simultaneously use a read-modify-write pattern with no file lock. Last writer wins; the other registration is silently lost.\n\nFix (Phase 0): Replace `fs.writeFileSync` with an atomic rename pattern:\n```typescript\nconst tmp = `${registryPath}.tmp.${process.pid}`;\nfs.writeFileSync(tmp, JSON.stringify(updated, null, 2));\nfs.renameSync(tmp, registryPath);  // atomic on POSIX\n```\n\n`rename()` is atomic on POSIX for files on the same filesystem. On Windows, `fs.renameSync` is not atomic; the fix there is to use a platform-specific file lock. Note: the long-term fix (Phase 1) moves the registry into the DB as a `projects` table, making this moot.\n\n**Race 3: Multiple MCP server instances (Architecture W12).**\n\nTwo Claude Code windows against the same project each start an MCP server. Each holds a connection. Both have WAL readers; writes are serialised by WAL automatically. Risk of data corruption: none (SQLite guarantees this). Risk of stale reads: possible if one writer commits while the other is mid-query. WAL snapshot isolation per transaction means neither session sees a partial write.\n\nAccepted posture (Phase 0): document WAL semantics; no application-level coordinator. Phase 1 DAO introduction is the natural place to add optional write queuing if metrics show contention.\n\n### 6.3 `withRetry` helper (already implemented)\n\n`src/shared-db.ts:withRetry<T>(fn, maxRetries=3)` wraps any DB operation with exponential backoff on `SQLITE_BUSY`. Spin-wait between retries: 50 ms, 100 ms, 200 ms. Sufficient for the single-developer concurrency model. Not sufficient for a team sharing a DB file over a network filesystem (that scenario is out of scope; cloud sync uses CRDT, not shared filesystem).\n\n### 6.4 Foreign key enforcement\n\n`PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON` is set on every connection. SQLite does not enforce FKs by default; this pragma must be set per-connection, not per-database. All cascade rules (`ON DELETE CASCADE`, `ON DELETE SET NULL`) depend on this being set before any write.\n\nRisk: a third-party tool (e.g., `sqlite3` CLI) that omits the pragma can silently break FK invariants. The Phase 2 audit table catches this after the fact; there is no pre-connection enforcement short of triggers.\n\n---\n\n## 7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n\nThis section specifies the target DDL for all new tables introduced across Phases 0–7.\nThese are not yet in `schema.sql`; they are introduced via numbered migrations (§9).\n\n### 7.1 `schema_migrations` (Phase 0)\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_migrations (\n  version     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  name        TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  applied_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  checksum    TEXT    NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n### 7.2 `projects` (Phase 1 — registry in DB)\n\nReplaces `registry.json`. Enables atomic CAS updates and FK references.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS projects (\n  id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  project_name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n  cwd          TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n  registered_at TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  last_seen_at  TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  workspace_id  TEXT,\n  metadata      TEXT                                  -- JSON blob for extensible fields\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_projects_cwd ON projects(cwd);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_projects_workspace ON projects(workspace_id);\n```\n\n### 7.3 `memory_embeddings` (Phase 1 — split from `memories`)\n\nIsolates the BLOB from the hot row. MCP queries never join this table. Embedding provider writes here; recall only touches it during the semantic fallback path.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_embeddings (\n  memory_id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  provider    TEXT    NOT NULL,                  -- e.g. 'local-hash', 'claude-tool', 'onnx'\n  model       TEXT,                              -- model id or version used to generate\n  dimensions  INTEGER NOT NULL,\n  vec         BLOB    NOT NULL,                  -- float32 array, length = dimensions\n  generated_at TEXT   NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n```\n\nMigration: `0006_split_embeddings.sql` — copies `memories.embedding` into this table for all rows where it is not null, then drops the `embedding` column from `memories`.\n\nAfter this migration, the MCP compact formatter no longer needs to strip embeddings — they are unreachable via the standard recall join.\n\n### 7.4 `hook_events` (Phase 1 — structured observability)\n\nAppend-only log of hook and MCP tool invocations. Solves Architecture W1 and W5.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS hook_events (\n  id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  event_type  TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(event_type IN (\n                'session_start','pre_compact','evaluate_session','update_context',\n                'ltm_recall','ltm_learn','ltm_forget','ltm_relate',\n                'ltm_context','ltm_context_items','ltm_graph','janitor_run')),\n  project_name TEXT,\n  session_id  TEXT,\n  status      TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(status IN ('ok','error','warn')),\n  latency_ms  INTEGER,\n  result_count INTEGER,                          -- rows returned (for recall)\n  error_msg   TEXT,                              -- populated on status='error'\n  payload     TEXT,                              -- JSON, optional; truncated to 1 KB\n  created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_type ON hook_events(event_type, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_project ON hook_events(project_name, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_hook_events_status ON hook_events(status, created_at DESC);\n```\n\nRetention: rows older than 90 days are pruned by the janitor. `/openltm:health` aggregates from this table for latency p50/p95, error rates, and recall hit rates.\n\n### 7.5 `memory_provenance` (Phase 2 — C5)\n\nOne-to-many: a memory may have multiple provenance entries (e.g., originally from a git commit, later confirmed by EvaluateSession).\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_provenance (\n  id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  source_type TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(source_type IN (\n                'learn','git-backfill','evaluate-session','import-bundle',\n                'user-promotion','janitor-rollup','legacy')),\n  source_ref  TEXT,                              -- session_id, git SHA, bundle_id, etc.\n  actor       TEXT,                              -- 'mcp:ltm_learn', 'hook:evaluate_session', etc.\n  created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  metadata    TEXT                               -- JSON; e.g. {\"turn\": 7, \"score\": 0.92}\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_provenance_memory ON memory_provenance(memory_id);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_provenance_source_type ON memory_provenance(source_type, created_at DESC);\n```\n\nBackfill: all existing memories get a single `legacy` provenance row at migration time.\n\n### 7.6 `memory_audit` (Phase 2 — W11, C5, C9)\n\nAppend-only audit log. Every write to the `memories` table (insert, update, forget/deprecate, redact) produces an audit row. Powers time-travel (Phase 7) and `/openltm:admin audit`.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_audit (\n  id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- NOT FK: must survive memory deletion\n  op          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(op IN (\n                'insert','update','forget','deprecate','supersede','redact','restore')),\n  actor       TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- 'mcp:ltm_learn', 'hook:evaluate_session', etc.\n  session_id  TEXT,\n  before_json TEXT,                             -- JSON snapshot of row before op (null for insert)\n  after_json  TEXT,                             -- JSON snapshot of row after op (null for delete)\n  created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_memory ON memory_audit(memory_id, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_op ON memory_audit(op, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_audit_session ON memory_audit(session_id, created_at DESC);\n```\n\nNote: `memory_id` is intentionally **not** a foreign key. A forgotten memory must still have an audit trail. The audit row survives `DELETE FROM memories`.\n\n`before_json` and `after_json` store a JSON snapshot of the relevant columns (excluding `embedding` BLOB to avoid bloat). The Phase 7 replay engine uses these to reconstruct past states.\n\n### 7.7 `team_bundles` (Phase 6 — C3)\n\nTracks imported and exported memory bundles.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS team_bundles (\n  id            INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  bundle_id     TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,         -- UUID, assigned at export time\n  direction     TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(direction IN ('export','import')),\n  status        TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(status IN ('pending','accepted','rejected','partial')),\n  signer_key_id TEXT,                            -- fingerprint of the signing keypair\n  signature     TEXT,                            -- base64-encoded Ed25519 signature\n  memory_count  INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n  source_peer   TEXT,                            -- optional: who sent the bundle\n  bundle_path   TEXT,                            -- local path to the .ltm-bundle file\n  created_at    TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  reviewed_at   TEXT,\n  metadata      TEXT                             -- JSON: schema_version, export_format, etc.\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_bundles_status ON team_bundles(status, created_at DESC);\n```\n\n### 7.8 `bundle_memories` (Phase 6 — C3)\n\nJoin table linking an imported bundle to the memories it created or attempted to create.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS bundle_memories (\n  bundle_id TEXT    NOT NULL REFERENCES team_bundles(bundle_id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  import_status TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(import_status IN ('accepted','rejected','merged')),\n  merge_target_id INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY (bundle_id, memory_id)\n);\n```\n\n### 7.9 `signing_keys` (Phase 6 — C3)\n\nTrusted public keys for bundle verification.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS signing_keys (\n  key_id      TEXT PRIMARY KEY,                 -- fingerprint (SHA-256 of public key)\n  public_key  TEXT NOT NULL,                    -- base64-encoded Ed25519 public key\n  label       TEXT,                             -- human name, e.g. \"Tara's MacBook\"\n  trusted     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,       -- 0 = revoked\n  added_at    TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  revoked_at  TEXT\n);\n```\n\n### 7.10 `memory_conflicts` (Phase 6 — C4)\n\nStaged conflicts detected by the Learn Engine's similarity check. User resolves at next SessionStart.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_conflicts (\n  id              INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  incoming_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  conflicting_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  similarity_score REAL    NOT NULL,\n  conflict_type   TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(conflict_type IN ('duplicate','contradiction','overlap')),\n  resolution      TEXT    CHECK(resolution IN ('accepted','rejected','superseded','coexist')),\n  resolved_at     TEXT,\n  created_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_conflicts_incoming ON memory_conflicts(incoming_memory_id);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_conflicts_resolution ON memory_conflicts(resolution, created_at DESC);\n```\n\n### 7.11 `sync_state` (Phase 6 — C2)\n\nCRDT sync bookkeeping for multi-device sync.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sync_state (\n  device_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- UUID assigned at first sync setup\n  seq         INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- monotonic sequence per device\n  last_push_at TEXT,\n  last_pull_at TEXT,\n  relay_url   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- E2E relay endpoint\n  PRIMARY KEY (device_id)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sync_ops (\n  id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  device_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  seq         INTEGER NOT NULL,\n  op_type     TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(op_type IN ('insert','forget','relate','tag')),\n  target_id   TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- memory_id or relation_id\n  payload_enc TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- base64(AES-GCM(JSON op payload))\n  created_at  TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  applied_at  TEXT,\n  UNIQUE(device_id, seq)\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sync_ops_device ON sync_ops(device_id, seq);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sync_ops_applied ON sync_ops(applied_at);\n```\n\n### 7.12 Versioning tables (Phase 7 — C9, C10)\n\nThe `memory_audit` table (§7.6) is the primary source for time-travel. Phase 7 adds a\nsnapshot mechanism for efficient point-in-time reconstruction.\n\n```sql\n-- Named snapshots (created by /openltm:memory snapshot or by janitor nightly)\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS memory_snapshots (\n  id            INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  label         TEXT,                           -- human-readable, e.g. \"before Phase 4 migration\"\n  snapshot_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  memory_count  INTEGER NOT NULL,\n  created_by    TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(created_by IN ('janitor','user','migration'))\n);\n\n-- Memory state at snapshot time (for replay without replaying all audit ops)\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS snapshot_memories (\n  snapshot_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memory_snapshots(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  memory_id   INTEGER NOT NULL,                 -- not FK; memory may be deleted\n  state_json  TEXT    NOT NULL,                 -- JSON of memories row at snapshot time\n  PRIMARY KEY (snapshot_id, memory_id)\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_snapshots_at ON memory_snapshots(snapshot_at DESC);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Performance at Scale\n\n### 8.1 Scale tiers\n\n| Tier | Memory count | Expected user | Risk |\n|------|-------------|--------------|------|\n| Small | 0–1 000 | Most users | None |\n| Medium | 1 000–10 000 | Power users, 1–2 years of dogfooding | Low |\n| Large | 10 000–100 000 | Enterprise devs, GitLearn backfill over large repos | W4 semantic fallback |\n| Extreme | 100 000–1 000 000 | Theoretical; team bundle accumulation | FTS5 limits |\n\n### 8.2 Storage estimates\n\n| Component | Per-row cost | At 10k | At 100k |\n|-----------|-------------|--------|---------|\n| `memories` (text only, no embedding) | ~500 bytes avg | 5 MB | 50 MB |\n| `memories.embedding` (1536 float32) | ~6 KB | 60 MB | 600 MB |\n| `memories_fts` shadow tables | ~30% of content size | 1.5 MB | 15 MB |\n| `memory_audit` (2 JSON snapshots per op) | ~1 KB avg | 10 MB (if all ops logged) | 100 MB |\n| `hook_events` (90-day retention) | ~200 bytes | ~2 MB/90d | ~2 MB/90d |\n\n**Key insight:** the `embedding` BLOB dominates. After the Phase 1 split into `memory_embeddings`, the base `memories` table stays lean (5–50 MB range), and `memory_embeddings` is accessed only on the semantic fallback path.\n\n### 8.3 Query plan at scale\n\n**FTS5 recall at 100k memories:**\n\nFTS5 uses an inverted index. A MATCH query on a common two-word phrase returns a sorted list of matching rowids in O(log T + k) where T is the total token count and k is the result count. At 100k memories the inverted index is ~15 MB (loaded pages). First query may incur page faults; subsequent queries benefit from OS page cache.\n\nExpected latency: 5–20 ms at 100k for the FTS5 phase. This is well within budget.\n\n**Semantic fallback at 100k memories (current):**\n\nReads all `embedding` BLOBs: 600 MB of BLOB data. Typical SQLite read throughput: 200–500 MB/s from SSD. Estimate: 1.2–3 s for a full scan. Catastrophically slow.\n\n**Mitigation strategies:**\n\n1. **Phase 1 (immediate):** Move embeddings to `memory_embeddings`. The fallback now requires an explicit join. Recall queries that do not trigger fallback never touch the table.\n2. **Phase 3 (ANN index, stretch):** Integrate `sqlite-vss` or a comparable SQLite extension for approximate nearest-neighbour search over the embedding table. Reduces semantic search from O(N) to O(log N). This requires bundling a native extension — evaluate feasibility against the zero-dependency goal (ADR-001).\n3. **Phase 4 (materialised decay_score):** Eliminates JS-side rank multiplication; the recall query is a single indexed SQL ORDER BY.\n\n**Fallback threshold tuning:**\n\nThe semantic fallback triggers at < 3 FTS5 results. At 100k memories, queries that hit this threshold typically involve rare or paraphrased terms. Adding a configurable `settings.recall.fts_min_results` (default 3) allows users to disable semantic fallback entirely until Phase 3 ANN is ready.\n\n### 8.4 Mitigation strategies summary\n\n| Problem | Phase | Mitigation |\n|---------|-------|-----------|\n| Embedding BLOB in hot row | 1 | Split to `memory_embeddings` |\n| O(N) semantic fallback scan | 3 | ANN index (stretch) or disable fallback |\n| O(N) JS decay multiply | 4 | Materialised `decay_score` |\n| FTS5 index growth | 4 | Janitor archival of deprecated memories |\n| `memory_audit` unbounded growth | 4 | Janitor prunes rows > 1 year; snapshots consolidate |\n| `hook_events` growth | 1 | 90-day retention enforced by janitor |\n\n### 8.5 VACUUM and ANALYZE schedule\n\nSQLite auto-analyzes when a table changes significantly (controlled by `PRAGMA analysis_limit`). Manual schedule:\n\n- `PRAGMA ANALYZE;` — run by janitor weekly; updates query planner statistics.\n- `PRAGMA VACUUM;` — **not** scheduled automatically; recommended after large deletions (e.g., after a bulk `forget` or deprecated memory archival). Document in `/openltm:admin` as a manual command.\n- `PRAGMA wal_checkpoint(TRUNCATE);` — run by janitor after each pass to truncate the WAL file and reclaim disk space.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n\nThis section maps each ROADMAP phase to its concrete DDL changes. Migration files live in `db/migrations/`. The Phase 0 `schema_migrations` table is the runner; subsequent migrations are executed by `src/migrator.ts`.\n\n### Phase 0 — Foundation Hardening (v1.5.x)\n\nGoal: replace hand-rolled migrations, add hot-path indexes, advisory locking.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0001_initial_schema_backfill.sql` | INSERT sentinel row into `schema_migrations`; records all existing hasColumn guards as applied |\n| `0002_add_hot_path_indexes.sql` | `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_status_importance ON memories(status, importance DESC);` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_created_at ON memories(created_at);` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_last_recalled_at ON memories(last_recalled_at);` `CREATE INDEX idx_ctx_project_type_created ON context_items(project_name, type, created_at DESC);` |\n| `0003_schema_migrations_table.sql` | `CREATE TABLE schema_migrations (version, name, applied_at, checksum)` (self-bootstrapping) |\n\nBreaking: none. Backwards-compatible.\n\nRollback: indexes can be dropped; `schema_migrations` can be dropped without data loss.\n\n### Phase 1 — DAO + Observability (v1.6.x)\n\nGoal: split embeddings, add projects table, add hook_events log.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0004_add_projects_table.sql` | `CREATE TABLE projects (id, project_name UNIQUE, cwd UNIQUE, ...)` with indexes; backfill from `registry.json` content |\n| `0005_add_hook_events.sql` | `CREATE TABLE hook_events (id, event_type, project_name, session_id, status, latency_ms, result_count, error_msg, payload, created_at)` with indexes |\n| `0006_split_embeddings.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_embeddings (memory_id PK, provider, model, dimensions, vec, generated_at);` `INSERT INTO memory_embeddings SELECT id, 'legacy', NULL, 0, embedding, datetime('now') FROM memories WHERE embedding IS NOT NULL;` `ALTER TABLE memories DROP COLUMN embedding;` (SQLite >= 3.35.0 required) |\n\nNote on `DROP COLUMN`: Bun ships SQLite 3.45+; this is safe. Add a version guard in the migration runner.\n\nBreaking: none at MCP contract level. Internal: the `embedding` column disappears from `memories`; any code reading it directly must be updated (DAO refactor happens in Phase 1 code work).\n\nRollback: `0006` has a down migration that re-adds the column and copies data back from `memory_embeddings`.\n\n### Phase 2 — Provenance + Audit (v1.7.x)\n\nGoal: every write auditable, every memory traceable.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0007_add_memory_provenance.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_provenance (id, memory_id FK, source_type, source_ref, actor, created_at, metadata)` with indexes; backfill all existing memories with `source_type='legacy'` |\n| `0008_add_memory_audit.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_audit (id, memory_id, op, actor, session_id, before_json, after_json, created_at)` with indexes; no backfill (audit is forward-only) |\n\nBreaking: none. Optional fields added to recall results.\n\n### Phase 3 — Embedding Provider Abstraction (v1.8.x)\n\nGoal: FTS5 gains category column; `memory_embeddings.provider` enables multi-provider.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0009_fts_add_category.sql` | `DROP TABLE memories_fts;` Rebuild with `content, category` columns; rebuild triggers; full re-index via `INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content, category) SELECT id, content, category FROM memories WHERE status='active';` |\n\nNote: `DROP TABLE memories_fts` and rebuild requires exclusive access. The migrator wraps this in `BEGIN EXCLUSIVE; ...; COMMIT;`.\n\nBreaking: FTS trigger DDL changes; any code constructing raw FTS queries must update.\n\n### Phase 4 — Janitor (v1.9.x)\n\nGoal: materialise decay_score; janitor archival.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0010_add_decay_score.sql` | `ALTER TABLE memories ADD COLUMN decay_score REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0;` `CREATE INDEX idx_memories_decay_score ON memories(decay_score DESC);` Initial backfill: `UPDATE memories SET decay_score = 1.0;` (janitor will compute real values on first run) |\n| `0011_add_janitor_settings.sql` | `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('janitor.enabled', 'true', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('janitor.last_run_at', '', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('decay.half_life_days', '90', datetime('now'));` `INSERT OR IGNORE INTO settings VALUES ('decay.immortal_importance', '5', datetime('now'));` |\n\nBreaking: none. `decay_score` defaults to 1.0 until janitor first runs.\n\n### Phase 5 — Cross-Plugin Contract (v2.0.0, semver-major)\n\nGoal: stable versioned MCP write surface; registry fully in DB.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0012_finalize_projects_table.sql` | Add `contract_version TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '1'` to `projects`; add index on `workspace_id`; make `cwd` the primary lookup for all hook code |\n| `0013_drop_deprecated_columns.sql` | Drop any columns marked deprecated in earlier phases (post major-version gate only) |\n\nBreaking: major version. MIGRATION.md documents removed columns and renamed tools.\n\n### Phase 6 — Sync + Bundles (v2.1.x)\n\nGoal: team bundles, signing, conflict detection, sync state.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0014_add_team_bundles.sql` | `CREATE TABLE team_bundles (...)` as specified in §7.7; `CREATE TABLE bundle_memories (...)` as §7.8 |\n| `0015_add_signing_keys.sql` | `CREATE TABLE signing_keys (...)` as §7.9 |\n| `0016_add_memory_conflicts.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_conflicts (...)` as §7.10 |\n| `0017_add_sync_tables.sql` | `CREATE TABLE sync_state (...)` as §7.11; `CREATE TABLE sync_ops (...)` |\n\nBreaking: none at contract level. New opt-in tables; existing users unaffected.\n\n### Phase 7 — Time-Travel + Diffing (v2.2.x)\n\nGoal: snapshot mechanism for efficient replay and diff.\n\n| File | DDL summary |\n|------|-------------|\n| `0018_add_snapshots.sql` | `CREATE TABLE memory_snapshots (...)` as §7.12; `CREATE TABLE snapshot_memories (...)` |\n| `0019_seed_initial_snapshot.sql` | Insert a snapshot row for the current DB state at migration time so that `/openltm:memory replay` has a baseline |\n\nBreaking: none.\n\n### Backwards-compatibility ledger\n\n| Phase | Schema breaking | MCP contract breaking | Data loss risk |\n|-------|----------------|-----------------------|---------------|\n| 0 | No | No | None |\n| 1 | Idempotent migration; `embedding` column dropped (DAO abstracts it) | No | None if `memory_embeddings` backfill runs first |\n| 2 | Adds columns/tables | Adds optional recall fields | None |\n| 3 | FTS rebuild required (downtime ~1s per 10k memories) | Adds optional FTS fields | None |\n| 4 | Adds column; janitor controlled | No | None |\n| 5 | Removes deprecated columns | **Yes — semver major** | Columns removed; data in superseding columns |\n| 6 | Adds tables | Adds optional tools | None |\n| 7 | Adds tables | Adds optional tools | None |\n\n---\n\n## Appendix A — Entity-Relationship Diagram (Target State)\n\n```\nmemories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\ntags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\nmemories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source\"\nmemories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"target\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":1070,"totalLines":1071,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","time":{"start":1780928491788,"end":1780928491820}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b38135ca386cce6016a26cfeb87088191a598b6546232dfd5"}},"id":"prt_ea79c3109001Fabm1D0PnoLapa","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780928491834,"sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Gqdw7jzHHWRzDAHBFJVbmaBj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ARCHITECTURE — OpenLTM Plugin\n2: \n3: * **Version:** 1.3 (against plugin v2.9.0)\n4: * **Owner:** Rohi Rikman\n5: * **Status:** Baseline architecture spec; companion to `docs/internal/PRD.md`\n6: * **Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n7: \n8: This document describes the as-built architecture of the OpenLTM plugin, an honest\n9: assessment of its weaknesses, and a target \"magnificent\" architecture with a phased\n10: migration path. It is the reference artifact for the `database-admin` agent (schema work),\n11: the `backend-developer` agent (server / hook work), and the `cloud-architect` agent (any\n12: future sync surfaces).\n13: \n14: The PRD (`docs/internal/PRD.md`) is the contract: §4 (feature inventory) is the as-built ground\n15: truth; §5 (user stories) the acceptance contract; §6 (gaps) the opportunity space this\n16: spec turns into a roadmap.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## Table of Contents\n21: \n22: 1. System Context (C4 L1)\n23: 2. Container Diagram (C4 L2)\n24: 3. Component Diagram (C4 L3)\n25: 4. Data Flow: Full Session Lifecycle\n26: 5. Data Model Overview\n27: 6. Architectural Decision Records\n28: 7. Current Architectural Weaknesses\n29: 8. Magnificent Future Architecture\n30: 9. Migration Path\n31: 10. Non-Goals\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 1. System Context (C4 Level 1)\n36: \n37: The LTM plugin is a sidecar process to the Claude Code harness. Everything it does is\n38: local to the developer's machine. There is no cloud dependency, no telemetry, no\n39: multi-tenant store. Two external integration surfaces exist: the MCP protocol (how\n40: Claude talks to the plugin) and Git (read-only, used by the GitLearn skill for backfill).\n41: \n42: ```mermaid\n43: C4Context\n44:   title LTM Plugin — System Context\n45: \n46:   Person(dev, \"Developer\", \"Solo dev, power user, team lead, enterprise dev, or onboarder\")\n47: \n48:   System_Boundary(host, \"Developer Machine\") {\n49:     System(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"CLI / agent runtime; loads plugins, runs hooks, brokers MCP\")\n50:     System(ltm, \"LTM Plugin\", \"Persistent semantic memory, context restore, decay, learn/recall\")\n51:     SystemDb(sqlite, \"openltm.db\", \"Local SQLite (WAL mode) under CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA\")\n52:     System_Ext(git, \"Git Repo\", \"Source of commits for GitLearn backfill\")\n53:     System_Ext(browser, \"Web Browser\", \"Renders graph-app for memory visualization\")\n54:   }\n55: \n56:   Rel(dev, claude, \"Types prompts, runs slash commands\")\n57:   Rel(claude, ltm, \"MCP STDIO + hook stdin/stdout\")\n58:   Rel(ltm, sqlite, \"Reads / writes (WAL)\")\n59:   Rel(ltm, git, \"Reads commit history (read-only)\")\n60:   Rel(dev, browser, \"Opens localhost graph UI\")\n61:   Rel(browser, ltm, \"HTTP to graph-server\")\n62: ```\n63: \n64: **Boundaries**\n65: \n66: - **Inside the boundary:** plugin code, the SQLite DB, the registry JSON, and the\n67:   cache directory the plugin loader reads from. All on the developer's filesystem.\n68: - **Outside:** the Claude Code harness itself (a black box that fires lifecycle events\n69:   and routes MCP calls). The browser, used only for the optional graph UI.\n70: - **Explicitly excluded:** any third-party API. The plugin makes **zero outbound\n71:   network calls** by default. Any future cloud sync (G-I) is opt-in and end-to-end\n72:   encrypted.\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 2. Container Diagram (C4 Level 2)\n77: \n78: The plugin decomposes into five runtime containers plus shared on-disk state. The MCP\n79: server is the tool surface; hooks are short-lived processes triggered by lifecycle\n80: events; the graph server is opt-in.\n81: \n82: ```mermaid\n83: C4Container\n84:   title LTM Plugin — Containers\n85: \n86:   Person(dev, \"Developer\")\n87:   System_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\")\n88: \n89:   System_Boundary(ltm, \"LTM Plugin\") {\n90:     Container(mcp, \"MCP Server\", \"Bun + TypeScript, STDIO transport\", \"Long-lived; serves recall, learn, forget, relate, context, context_items, graph\")\n91:     Container(hooks, \"Hook Runners\", \"Bun scripts invoked by Claude Code\", \"SessionStart, PreCompact, EvaluateSession, UpdateContext\")\n92:     Container(cmds, \"Command + Skill Layer\", \"Markdown specs in commands/ and skills/\", \"Slash commands (/openltm:*), skills (ContinuousLearning, GitLearn, Learned, session-context)\")\n93:     Container(graph, \"Graph Server\", \"Bun HTTP server (opt-in)\", \"Serves graph-app SPA + JSON memory/edge feed\")\n94:     Container(graphapp, \"Graph App\", \"Static SPA served by graph server\", \"Force-directed memory graph viz; Playwright E2E tests\")\n95: \n96:     ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\", \"SQLite WAL\", \"memories, context_items, tags, memory_relations, memories_fts, settings\")\n97:     ContainerDb(reg, \"registry.json\", \"JSON file under ~/.claude/projects/\", \"cwd → project name mapping\")\n98:     ContainerDb(summary, \"context-summary.md\", \"Markdown fallback file\", \"Human-readable context snapshot regenerated on PreCompact\")\n99:   }\n100: \n101:   Rel(dev, claude, \"Prompts, slash commands\")\n102:   Rel(claude, mcp, \"MCP STDIO (JSON-RPC)\")\n103:   Rel(claude, hooks, \"Spawn process, pipe JSON stdin/stdout\")\n104:   Rel(claude, cmds, \"Resolves slash command and skill markdown into prompts\")\n105:   Rel(mcp, db, \"SQL queries (single shared connection)\")\n106:   Rel(hooks, db, \"SQL queries (shared via shared-db.ts)\")\n107:   Rel(hooks, reg, \"Read / write project map\")\n108:   Rel(hooks, summary, \"Regenerate on PreCompact\")\n109:   Rel(dev, graph, \"/openltm:admin server start\")\n110:   Rel(graph, graphapp, \"Serves SPA\")\n111:   Rel(graphapp, graph, \"Fetch /api/memories, /api/relations\")\n112:   Rel(graph, db, \"Read-only queries\")\n113: ```\n114: \n115: **Notes on shared state**\n116: \n117: - A single SQLite connection is held by `shared-db.ts` and reused across MCP server,\n118:   hooks, and graph server within one process. WAL mode permits concurrent readers\n119:   with a single writer; cross-process safety relies on SQLite's file locking.\n120: - `registry.json` is a small JSON map. Concurrent writes are rare (only during\n121:   `/openltm:project register` or `SessionStart` first-touch) but unsynchronised — a\n122:   known weakness called out in §7.\n123: - `context-summary.md` is a write-mostly artifact regenerated by `PreCompact`. It is\n124:   never the source of truth; the DB is.\n125: \n126: ---\n127: \n128: ## 3. Component Diagram (C4 Level 3)\n129: \n130: This level breaks the **MCP server** and **hook runners** into their internal\n131: components. The command/skill layer is intentionally not decomposed — markdown specs\n132: have no internal components.\n133: \n134: ### 3.1 MCP Server components\n135: \n136: ```mermaid\n137: C4Component\n138:   title MCP Server — Components\n139: \n140:   Container_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"MCP client\")\n141:   ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\")\n142: \n143:   Container_Boundary(mcp, \"MCP Server (src/mcp-server.ts)\") {\n144:     Component(transport, \"STDIO Transport\", \"@modelcontextprotocol/sdk\", \"JSON-RPC over stdin/stdout\")\n145:     Component(toolreg, \"Tool Registry\", \"McpServer.tool()\", \"Declares recall, learn, forget, relate, context, context_items, graph with Zod schemas\")\n146:     Component(recall, \"Recall Engine\", \"src/db.ts:recall\", \"FTS5 query → semantic fallback → merge → rank by importance/recency/decay\")\n147:     Component(learn, \"Learn Engine\", \"src/db.ts:learn\", \"Validate → redact secrets → dedup-key check → insert → return id\")\n148:     Component(ctxmerge, \"Context Merge\", \"src/db.ts:getContextMerge + src/context.ts:getItems\", \"Build the goal+decisions+progress+gotchas envelope for SessionStart\")\n149:     Component(graphtrav, \"Graph Traversal\", \"src/graph.ts:traverseGraph\", \"BFS over memory_relations; powers graph and visualization feed\")\n150:     Component(formatter, \"Compact Formatter\", \"src/mcp-server.ts:compact/strip\", \"Strips embedding blob, truncates content to keep MCP responses small\")\n151:     Component(config, \"Config Reader\", \"src/config.ts\", \"Reads plugin config; respects mcp.enabled flag\")\n152:   }\n153: \n154:   Rel(claude, transport, \"JSON-RPC\")\n155:   Rel(transport, toolreg, \"dispatch\")\n156:   Rel(toolreg, recall, \"recall\")\n157:   Rel(toolreg, learn, \"learn\")\n158:   Rel(toolreg, ctxmerge, \"context, context_items\")\n159:   Rel(toolreg, graphtrav, \"graph\")\n160:   Rel(toolreg, formatter, \"shape response\")\n161:   Rel(toolreg, config, \"feature flag check\")\n162:   Rel(recall, db, \"FTS5 + base table queries\")\n163:   Rel(learn, db, \"INSERT memories, INSERT memories_fts via trigger\")\n164:   Rel(ctxmerge, db, \"SELECT context_items + memories\")\n165:   Rel(graphtrav, db, \"SELECT memory_relations\")\n166: ```\n167: \n168: ### 3.2 Hook Runners components\n169: \n170: ```mermaid\n171: C4Component\n172:   title Hook Runners — Components\n173: \n174:   Container_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"Spawns hooks per lifecycle event\")\n175:   ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\")\n176:   ContainerDb(reg, \"registry.json\")\n177:   ContainerDb(summary, \"context-summary.md\")\n178: \n179:   Container_Boundary(hooks, \"Hook Runners (hooks/*.ts)\") {\n180:     Component(start, \"SessionStart hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Resolve project from cwd → registry; rebuild context-summary.md; emit injection block\")\n181:     Component(pre, \"PreCompact hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Pull all 4 context types from DB; serialize to context-summary.md (~60 line cap)\")\n182:     Component(eval, \"EvaluateSession hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Score session; identify candidate insights; (proposes / auto-writes per OQ4)\")\n183:     Component(update, \"UpdateContext hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Append progress entries; trim to last 20; bump last-touched timestamps\")\n184:     Component(resolver, \"Project Resolver\", \"shared util\", \"cwd → project name via registry; auto-register on first touch\")\n185:     Component(injector, \"Context Injector\", \"shared util\", \"Compose ## Restored Project Context block; truncate to ~60 lines + footer\")\n186:     Component(redact, \"Secret Redactor\", \"shared util\", \"Pattern-match API keys, JWTs, AWS keys; replace with [REDACTED:type]\")\n187:   }\n188: \n189:   Rel(claude, start, \"spawn(SessionStart)\")\n190:   Rel(claude, pre, \"spawn(PreCompact)\")\n191:   Rel(claude, eval, \"spawn(EvaluateSession)\")\n192:   Rel(claude, update, \"spawn(UpdateContext)\")\n193:   Rel(start, resolver, \"resolve\")\n194:   Rel(start, injector, \"build block\")\n195:   Rel(start, db, \"SELECT context_items + globals\")\n196:   Rel(start, reg, \"read / auto-register\")\n197:   Rel(pre, db, \"SELECT all context types\")\n198:   Rel(pre, summary, \"write\")\n199:   Rel(eval, db, \"INSERT memories (or pending)\")\n200:   Rel(eval, redact, \"scrub before write\")\n201:   Rel(update, db, \"INSERT progress; UPDATE timestamps\")\n202: ```\n203: \n204: **Component responsibilities at a glance**\n205: \n206: | Component | Responsibility | Single source of truth for |\n207: |-----------|----------------|---------------------------|\n208: | Recall Engine | Search ranking | Merging FTS5 + semantic results, applying decay |\n209: | Learn Engine | Write path | Dedup, redaction, importance/category enforcement |\n210: | Context Merge | Read path for SessionStart | Envelope shape (goal + decisions + progress + gotchas) |\n211: | Project Resolver | cwd → project | Authoritative map; auto-registration |\n212: | Secret Redactor | Pattern scrub | Redaction policy, called from learn + EvaluateSession |\n213: | Context Injector | Format injection | 60-line budget, footer rendering |\n214: | Compact Formatter | MCP response shaping | Stripping embedding blob, content truncation |\n215: \n216: ---\n217: \n218: ## 4. Data Flow: Full Session Lifecycle\n219: \n220: This is the canonical end-to-end flow that ties every container and component together.\n221: A \"session\" spans from Claude Code launch in a project cwd through to clean exit (or\n222: compaction-triggered restart). The diagram shows one full cycle.\n223: \n224: ```mermaid\n225: sequenceDiagram\n226:   autonumber\n227:   actor Dev as Developer\n228:   participant Claude as Claude Code Harness\n229:   participant Start as SessionStart hook\n230:   participant Reg as registry.json\n231:   participant DB as openltm.db (SQLite)\n232:   participant MCP as MCP Server\n233:   participant Eval as EvaluateSession hook\n234:   participant Pre as PreCompact hook\n235:   participant Update as UpdateContext hook\n236:   participant Sum as context-summary.md\n237: \n238:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session start ---\n239:   Dev->>Claude: cd into project, launch Claude Code\n240:   Claude->>Start: spawn(SessionStart, stdin=cwd)\n241:   Start->>Reg: resolve(cwd) → project_name (auto-register if new)\n242:   Start->>DB: SELECT goal, decisions, gotchas, progress (project) + importance-5 globals\n243:   Start-->>Claude: stdout = \"## Restored Project Context\\n...\" (≤ 60 lines)\n244:   Claude-->>Dev: render injected block\n245: \n246:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Recall before deciding ---\n247:   Dev->>Claude: prompt that requires past context\n248:   Claude->>MCP: recall({ query, project })\n249:   MCP->>DB: FTS5(MATCH) → ranked rowids\n250:   alt FTS5 returns < 3 results\n251:     MCP->>DB: semantic fallback (embedding similarity)\n252:     MCP->>MCP: merge + dedup by id\n253:   end\n254:   MCP->>MCP: apply decay scoring + importance boost\n255:   MCP-->>Claude: top-N memories (compact, embedding-stripped)\n256:   Claude-->>Dev: answer informed by recalled context\n257: \n258:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Work + learn ---\n259:   Dev->>Claude: makes a decision; runs /openltm:memory learn\n260:   Claude->>MCP: learn({ content, category, importance, project })\n261:   MCP->>MCP: redact secrets; compute dedup_key\n262:   MCP->>DB: INSERT memories (trigger writes memories_fts)\n263:   MCP-->>Claude: { id }\n264: \n265:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Mid-session: compaction ---\n266:   Claude->>Pre: spawn(PreCompact)\n267:   Pre->>DB: SELECT all 4 context types for project\n268:   Pre->>Sum: write context-summary.md (~60 lines, fallback)\n269:   Pre-->>Claude: ack\n270:   Claude->>Claude: compact transcript\n271:   Note over Claude: Next assistant turn re-reads context-summary.md if needed\n272: \n273:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session end ---\n274:   Claude->>Update: spawn(UpdateContext)\n275:   Update->>DB: INSERT progress; trim oldest > 20; UPDATE last_touched\n276:   Update-->>Claude: ack\n277:   Claude->>Eval: spawn(EvaluateSession)\n278:   Eval->>DB: scan transcript-derived signals; propose / write candidate insights\n279:   Eval-->>Claude: ack\n280:   Claude-->>Dev: clean exit\n281: ```\n282: \n283: **Per-step contracts**\n284: \n285: | Step | Read from | Writes to | Failure mode |\n286: |------|-----------|-----------|--------------|\n287: | SessionStart | DB, registry | registry (auto-register only) | Hook silent-fail → no injection; `/openltm:doctor` detects |\n288: | recall | DB (FTS5 + base) | DB (last_recalled_at, recall_count) | Returns empty array; never throws into Claude |\n289: | learn | — | DB (memories, memories_fts via trigger) | Reject duplicate dedup_key; redact before write |\n290: | PreCompact | DB | context-summary.md | If write fails, post-compact session loses fallback only |\n291: | EvaluateSession | transcript signals, DB | DB (memories) | OQ4 — propose vs. auto-write is open |\n292: | UpdateContext | — | DB (context_items progress) | Trim ensures bounded growth |\n293: \n294: ---\n295: \n296: ## 5. Data Model Overview\n297: \n298: The persistent store is one SQLite file (`openltm.db`) under `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}`.\n299: Schema lives in `src/schema.sql` and is extended idempotently by migrations in\n300: `src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n301: \n302: ### 5.1 Tables\n303: \n304: | Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n305: |-------|---------|-----------|\n306: | `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n307: | `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n308: | `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n309: | `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n310: | `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n311: | `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n312: | `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n313: \n314: ### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n315: \n316: | Column | Purpose |\n317: |--------|---------|\n318: | `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n319: | `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n320: | `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n321: | `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n322: | `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n323: | `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n324: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n325: | `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n326: | `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n327: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n328: | `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n329: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n330: \n331: ### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n332: \n333: | Column | Purpose |\n334: |--------|---------|\n335: | `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n336: | `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n337: | `content` | Free text |\n338: | `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n339: | `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n340: | `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n341: \n342: ### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n343: \n344: - `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n345:   Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n346:   insert/update/delete.\n347: - Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n348:   `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n349: - BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n350:   decay factors before returning top-N.\n351: \n352: ### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n353: \n354: The current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n355: \n356: - **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n357: - **Rule sketch:**\n358:   - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n359:   - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n360:     by a decay factor (< 1).\n361:   - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n362: - **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n363:   (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n364: - **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n365:   and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n366: \n367: ### 5.6 Relationships\n368: \n369: ```mermaid\n370: erDiagram\n371:   memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n372:   tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n373:   memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n374:   memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n375:   memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n376:   memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)\n380: \n381: `~/.claude/projects/registry.json` holds the cwd → project_name map. It is a JSON\n382: file (not a table) for cross-plugin readability and trivial inspection. Concurrent\n383: write safety is **not** guaranteed — a known weakness (§7).\n384: \n385: ---\n386: \n387: ## 6. Architectural Decision Records\n388: \n389: Each ADR is short and load-bearing. Format: Status, Context, Decision, Alternatives,\n390: Consequences. Every ADR includes at least one rejected alternative.\n391: \n392: ---\n393: \n394: ### ADR-001 — SQLite as the storage engine\n395: \n396: **Status:** Accepted. In production since v1.0.\n397: \n398: **Context.** The plugin needs durable, queryable, low-latency storage on the\n399: developer's machine. It must survive Claude Code restarts, plugin upgrades, and\n400: machine sleep. Median write latency target: < 50 ms p95 (PRD §8.4 R3). Median recall\n401: < 200 ms (G2). Zero cloud dependency by default (PRD §7 N1).\n402: \n403: **Decision.** Use SQLite (via `bun:sqlite`) in WAL mode, single file at\n404: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/openltm.db`. FTS5 virtual table for full-text search.\n405: \n406: **Alternatives considered.**\n407: \n408: - **Postgres / managed DB.** Rejected. Adds an installation dependency, defeats the\n409:   zero-cloud promise, and is overkill for single-user data volumes (~10⁴–10⁶ rows\n410:   realistic ceiling).\n411: - **Flat JSON / Markdown files (the pre-1.0 design).** Rejected. No transactional\n412:   semantics, no FTS, no concurrent reader safety, O(N) scan per recall. The current\n413:   `context-summary.md` is the vestigial fallback; it is a *projection*, not the truth.\n414: - **DuckDB.** Considered. Better analytical perf, but heavier binary, weaker FTS\n415:   story, less Bun-native tooling, and write-heavy workloads (learn + decay updates)\n416:   favour SQLite.\n417: - **LevelDB / RocksDB key-value.** Rejected. No SQL, no FTS5, would need a hand-rolled\n418:   index for every query path.\n419: \n420: **Consequences.**\n421: \n422: - (+) One-file backup story; `cp openltm.db openltm.db.bak` is a complete export.\n423: - (+) FTS5 ships in SQLite — no extra dependency for full-text search.\n424: - (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process; no IPC overhead per query.\n425: - (–) Single-writer constraint (mitigated by WAL); cross-process locking is the\n426:   developer's responsibility to understand.\n427: - (–) Schema migrations must be hand-coded and idempotent (see `src/shared-db.ts`).\n428:   ADR-004 and §7 weakness W3 expand on this.\n429: - (–) Embedding column as BLOB grows the row size fast; the formatter strips it\n430:   before MCP transmission to avoid 260 KB-per-memory responses.\n431: \n432: ---\n433: \n434: ### ADR-002 — Hook-based lifecycle integration\n435: \n436: **Status:** Accepted.\n437: \n438: **Context.** Claude Code is a black-box harness. The plugin needs to (a) inject\n439: context at session start, (b) survive compaction without state loss, (c) record\n440: progress at session end, and (d) propose learnings post-session. MCP tools cover the\n441: \"on demand\" surface but not \"automatic on lifecycle event\".\n442: \n443: **Decision.** Use Claude Code's hook surface for four lifecycle events:\n444: `SessionStart`, `PreCompact`, `EvaluateSession`, `UpdateContext`. Hooks are\n445: short-lived Bun scripts in `hooks/`. They share the DB connection logic with the MCP\n446: server via `src/shared-db.ts`.\n447: \n448: **Alternatives considered.**\n449: \n450: - **MCP-only.** Rejected. There is no MCP equivalent to \"this is a fresh session,\n451:   inject context now\". Without hooks, the developer would have to manually call\n452:   `context` at every session start — defeats J1 and US-1.\n453: - **Background daemon.** Rejected. Long-lived process management on developer\n454:   machines is fragile (sleep/wake, terminal close). Also conflates \"react to event\"\n455:   with \"serve queries\".\n456: - **Polling cron.** Rejected. Not aligned with session boundaries; can't inject at\n457:   start.\n458: \n459: **Consequences.**\n460: \n461: - (+) Hook semantics align directly with PRD user stories US-1, US-4, US-13, US-17.\n462: - (+) Each hook is independently testable and replaceable.\n463: - (–) Hook failures are silent by default — drove the need for `/openltm:doctor` (US-9).\n464: - (–) Coupling to Claude Code's hook contract; if the harness changes the contract,\n465:   hooks break. Mitigated by the `update-wiring.ts` postinstall script that keeps\n466:   `settings.json` in sync.\n467: - (–) Four hook processes per session add some startup latency; offset by Bun's\n468:   fast cold start (~30 ms typical).\n469: \n470: ---\n471: \n472: ### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n473: \n474: **Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n475: \n476: **Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\n477: memories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\n478: single-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n479: \n480: **Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\n481: returns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n482: `embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\n483: boost, return top-N.\n484: \n485: **Alternatives considered.**\n486: \n487: - **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n488:   (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n489:   (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n490:   keyword-shaped.\n491: - **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n492:   dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n493: - **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n494:   queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n495:   patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n496: - **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n497:   beats raw similarity for natural language.\n498: \n499: **Consequences.**\n500: \n501: - (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n502: - (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n503: - (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n504:   to avoid bloat.\n505: - (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n506:   (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n507: - (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n508: \n509: ---\n510: \n511: ### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n512: \n513: **Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n514: \n515: **Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\n516: that low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n517: \n518: **Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n519: `importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n520: \n521: 1. `importance == 5` → no decay (immortal memories).\n522: 2. Else if `(now - last_recalled_at) > 90 days` AND `importance < 3` → multiply\n523:    rank by a decay factor < 1.\n524: 3. Recently-recalled memories receive a freshness boost.\n525: \n526: The exact function form (linear, exponential, recall-driven) is configurable via\n527: the `settings` table and remains an open experiment.\n528: \n529: **Alternatives considered.**\n530: \n531: - **Stored decay score updated on a schedule.** Rejected for v1. Adds a janitor\n532:   cron, a write-amplification problem, and a stale-score hazard. Recompute-on-read\n533:   is cheap at single-user scale.\n534: - **Hard expiry / auto-delete.** Rejected. Violates the developer's expectation that\n535:   memories are durable. Decay should rerank, not destroy.\n536: - **No decay.** Rejected. Long-running projects would drown new recalls under old\n537:   ones (PRD §1.1 — \"stale knowledge decays gracefully\").\n538: \n539: **Consequences.**\n540: \n541: - (+) Zero write amplification; decay costs only at read time.\n542: - (+) Tunable without a migration — settings table holds parameters.\n543: - (–) Recall latency is sensitive to N (rows scanned). At scale this becomes a\n544:   problem (W4 in §7) — addressed in the magnificent architecture by precomputed\n545:   decay buckets.\n546: - (–) Importance must be set correctly by the user / EvaluateSession or the model\n547:   is gameable.\n548: \n549: ---\n550: \n551: ### ADR-005 — Plugin cache vs. source-repo execution model\n552: \n553: **Status:** Accepted (with operational caveat).\n554: \n555: **Context.** Claude Code plugins are loaded from\n556: `~/.claude/plugins/cache/<plugin>/<version>/`, **not** from the source repo. A\n557: developer iterating on the plugin code locally must either (a) bump the version and\n558: trigger marketplace update, or (b) hot-patch the cache directory.\n559: \n560: **Decision.** Treat the cache directory as the runtime, the source repo as the\n561: source of truth. Document the dual-write requirement explicitly (see\n562: `CLAUDE.md` \"Cache Sync — MANDATORY\"). The `postinstall` script\n563: (`scripts/update-wiring.ts`) updates `settings.json` hook wiring at install time.\n564: \n565: **Alternatives considered.**\n566: \n567: - **Symlink cache → source repo.** Rejected. Fragile across plugin updates;\n568:   marketplace install would clobber it.\n569: - **Bundle plugin into a single file installed elsewhere.** Rejected. Loses Bun's\n570:   fast script execution and complicates the multi-file plugin layout (commands,\n571:   skills, hooks, src).\n572: - **Git submodule the source into the cache path.** Rejected. Fights the plugin\n573:   loader's expectations; the marketplace owns that directory.\n574: \n575: **Consequences.**\n576: \n577: - (+) Plays nicely with the marketplace update flow — one click bumps the version\n578:   and refreshes the cache.\n579: - (–) Two-place edits during local development (source repo + cache). Mitigated by\n580:   documentation but is a developer-experience tax.\n581: - (–) \"Why didn't my fix take effect?\" is a known foot-gun. Driver of the\n582:   `/openltm:doctor` checks for cache version vs. installed version.\n583: \n584: ---\n585: \n586: ### ADR-006 — Bun as runtime\n587: \n588: **Status:** Accepted.\n589: \n590: **Context.** The plugin is TypeScript end to end. It needs (a) fast cold-start for\n591: hooks (each hook spawns a fresh process), (b) native SQLite, (c) ESM-first with\n592: top-level await, (d) zero compile step in development.\n593: \n594: **Decision.** Bun is the runtime for the MCP server, hooks, and graph server.\n595: Dependencies: `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk`, `zod`. SQLite is `bun:sqlite` (built in,\n596: no native rebuild). TypeScript runs without a build step in development.\n597: \n598: **Alternatives considered.**\n599: \n600: - **Node.js + tsx / ts-node.** Rejected. Slower cold start (~150 ms vs. Bun's ~30 ms).\n601:   For four hooks per session this matters. Also requires `better-sqlite3` native\n602:   module, which breaks under Node version mismatches.\n603: - **Deno.** Considered. Fast, ESM-native, but plugin author's existing tooling and\n604:   the marketplace ecosystem assume Node-shaped runtimes; `bun:sqlite` is closer to\n605:   the Node ecosystem than Deno's Web-Crypto-flavoured world.\n606: - **Compiled Go / Rust binary.** Rejected. Loses the \"just edit a file\" hackability\n607:   PRD persona Pat values; complicates cross-platform distribution.\n608: \n609: **Consequences.**\n610: \n611: - (+) Cold-start matters: SessionStart hook completes inside a typical Claude Code\n612:   startup window without perceptible delay.\n613: - (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process and zero-config.\n614: - (–) Bun is younger than Node; some ecosystem packages may misbehave. Mitigated by\n615:   keeping the dependency surface tiny (2 prod deps).\n616: - (–) Bun must be installed on the developer's machine. This is documented as a\n617:   prereq.\n618: \n619: ---\n620: \n621: ## 7. Current Architectural Weaknesses\n622: \n623: An honest list. Each item names the symptom, the root cause, and a one-line direction.\n624: \n625: ### W1 — Silent hook failures\n626: \n627: **Symptom.** Hooks fail silently when stdin/stdout protocol breaks, settings.json\n628: loses a wiring entry, or the cache version drifts. The user notices only when\n629: context isn't injected.\n630: \n631: **Root cause.** Hooks are fire-and-forget; Claude Code does not surface stderr to\n632: the user prominently. There is no structured \"hook ran successfully\" telemetry.\n633: \n634: **Direction.** Add a per-hook structured log (DB table or local JSON), and have\n635: `/openltm:doctor` read it.\n636: \n637: ### W2 — Concurrent writes to `registry.json`\n638: \n639: **Symptom.** Two Claude Code sessions starting in different cwds at the same time\n640: can race on `registry.json` writes; last-writer-wins.\n641: \n642: **Root cause.** `registry.json` is a flat JSON file with no file lock or atomic\n643: rename. Auto-registration happens on first SessionStart per cwd.\n644: \n645: **Direction.** Move to atomic write (write-temp, rename) or push the registry into\n646: the DB as a `projects` table.\n647: \n648: ### W3 — Schema migrations are hand-rolled per column\n649: \n650: **Symptom.** Each new column needs a manual `hasColumn` check and an `ALTER TABLE`\n651: in `shared-db.ts`. There is no version table, no migration history, no rollback path.\n652: PRD US-10 (`/openltm:admin migrate`) sits on top of this fragile foundation.\n653: \n654: **Root cause.** No first-class migration framework. `shared-db.ts:runMigrations` is\n655: imperative and grew organically.\n656: \n657: **Direction.** Add a `schema_migrations` table with `version`, `applied_at`,\n658: `checksum`. Each migration is a numbered SQL file. Migrator runs in order in a\n659: transaction.\n660: \n661: ### W4 — Recall ranking is O(N) at recall time\n662: \n663: **Symptom.** Decay scoring re-ranks every FTS5 hit at query time. At 10⁵+ memories\n664: the 200 ms recall budget is at risk.\n665: \n666: **Root cause.** Decay is computed in JavaScript over the result set rather than\n667: expressed as a SQL `ORDER BY` over indexed columns.\n668: \n669: **Direction.** Materialise a `decay_score` column maintained by a low-frequency\n670: janitor; use it in `ORDER BY`. Trade write amplification for read latency.\n671: \n672: ### W5 — No structured observability\n673: \n674: **Symptom.** Latency, recall hit rate, learn frequency — none are recorded. PRD §8\n675: metrics are aspirational without instrumentation.\n676: \n677: **Root cause.** No metrics surface. No event log table. `/openltm:health` reads\n678: counts but not timings.\n679: \n680: **Direction.** Add an `events` table (append-only): event_type, latency_ms,\n681: result_count, timestamp. Aggregate in `/openltm:health`.\n682: \n683: ### W6 — Cache vs. source-repo dual-write\n684: \n685: **Symptom.** \"I fixed it but it didn't take effect.\" See ADR-005.\n686: \n687: **Direction.** Add a `dev mode` flag that, when set, makes the cache directory a\n688: symlink to the source repo. Off by default for end users.\n689: \n690: ### W7 — MCP response size pressure\n691: \n692: **Symptom.** `embedding` BLOBs serialise as `{\"0\":59,\"1\":...}` JSON objects of\n693: ~260 KB each over MCP. The `compact`/`strip` formatter exists *because* of this.\n694: \n695: **Root cause.** MCP responses are JSON; embeddings are binary. The strip is a\n696: band-aid, not a fix.\n697: \n698: **Direction.** Move embeddings out of the `memories` table into a sibling\n699: `memory_embeddings(memory_id, vec BLOB)` table; MCP queries never join it.\n700: \n701: ### W8 — Coupling between hooks and DB schema\n702: \n703: **Symptom.** A schema change requires updating hooks, MCP server, and graph server\n704: together. Versioning is per-plugin, not per-component.\n705: \n706: **Direction.** Define a small data-access layer (DAO) in `src/dao/` with stable\n707: function signatures; everything else calls through it. Schema changes are then\n708: isolated to the DAO.\n709: \n710: ### W9 — No memory provenance\n711: \n712: **Symptom.** A recalled memory tells you *what* but not *where it came from*\n713: (which conversation turn, which commit, which file). G-J in the PRD calls this out.\n714: \n715: **Direction.** Add a `provenance` table or columns: source_type\n716: (`session` / `git-backfill` / `manual` / `evaluate`), source_ref (session id, SHA,\n717: file path).\n718: \n719: ### W10 — `EvaluateSession` policy is unclear\n720: \n721: **Symptom.** PRD OQ4: should EvaluateSession auto-write or always propose? Today's\n722: behaviour is implementation-defined and not surfaced to the user.\n723: \n724: **Direction.** Add a config flag (`evaluate.auto_promote`); default to \"propose,\n725: require user confirmation via a banner at next SessionStart\".\n726: \n727: ### W11 — No write audit trail\n728: \n729: **Symptom.** A memory is wrong; the user can `forget` it but cannot answer\n730: \"who/what wrote this in the first place?\".\n731: \n732: **Direction.** Append-only `memory_audit` table: memory_id, op (insert/update/\n733: forget/redact), actor (mcp tool name / hook name), timestamp, before/after diff.\n734: \n735: ### W12 — Single SQLite connection assumes single-process plugin\n736: \n737: **Symptom.** Two MCP server instances against the same DB (e.g., from two Claude\n738: Code windows) rely solely on SQLite WAL for safety. There is no application-level\n739: write coordination.\n740: \n741: **Direction.** Either move writes through a single coordinator process (a daemon)\n742: or accept WAL semantics and document them. Surfaced in PRD OQ2.\n743: \n744: ---\n745: \n746: ## 8. Magnificent Future Architecture\n747: \n748: This is the bold target. It is **not** what we build next sprint — it is what we\n749: plan towards. Each capability ties back to a PRD §1.1 vision bullet and to a §6 gap.\n750: \n751: ### 8.1 Architectural pillars\n752: \n753: ```mermaid\n754: flowchart TB\n755:   subgraph Local[\"Developer Machine (canonical store)\"]\n756:     DB[(openltm.db v2: WAL, partitioned, audited)]\n757:     Embed[Embedding Service: pluggable provider]\n758:     Janitor[Janitor: decay materialiser, conflict detector, summariser]\n759:     DAO[Data-Access Layer / contract surface]\n760:     MCP[MCP Server v2: explainable recall]\n761:     Hooks[Hook Runners v2: structured logs]\n762:     Graph[Graph App v2: timeline + clusters]\n763:   end\n764: \n765:   subgraph Sync[\"Optional Sync Plane (E2E encrypted)\"]\n766:     Relay[Sync Relay: zero-knowledge blob store]\n767:     Bundle[Memory Bundle: signed, exportable]\n768:   end\n769: \n770:   subgraph Ecosystem[\"Cross-Plugin Memory Contract\"]\n771:     TaskTracker[task-tracker plugin]\n772:     CodeReview[code-review plugin]\n773:     Other[other plugins...]\n774:   end\n775: \n776:   Local <-- E2E encrypted blobs --> Relay\n777:   Local -- export / import --> Bundle\n778:   Bundle -- import --> Local\n779:   Ecosystem -- writes via DAO --> DAO\n780:   DAO --> DB\n781:   Janitor --> DB\n782:   MCP --> DAO\n783:   Hooks --> DAO\n784:   Embed --> DB\n785:   Graph --> DAO\n786: ```\n787: \n788: ### 8.2 Capability map\n789: \n790: | # | Capability | PRD link | Gap link |\n791: |---|------------|----------|----------|\n792: | C1 | Pluggable embedding provider | OQ1 | G-E |\n793: | C2 | Multi-device E2E sync | §1.1 portable | G-I |\n794: | C3 | Team memory bundles (signed) | persona Tara | G-A |\n795: | C4 | Conflict detection on learn | §1.1 self-curating | G-F |\n796: | C5 | Provenance chain per memory | safety / audit | G-J |\n797: | C6 | Memory compression / rollups | §1.1 sub-linear growth | G-L |\n798: | C7 | Cross-plugin memory contract | ecosystem | G-M |\n799: | C8 | Recall result explainer | trust | G-K |\n800: | C9 | Time-travel replay | retrospectives | G-G |\n801: | C10 | Memory diffing across versions | onboarding | G-B |\n802: \n803: ### 8.3 C1 — Pluggable embedding provider\n804: \n805: Today: single, ad-hoc embedding path. Future: an `EmbeddingProvider` interface\n806: selected at install time. Implementations: `null` (FTS5 only), `local-hash`\n807: (deterministic), `claude-tool` (calls back into Claude Code), `bundled-onnx`\n808: (opt-in, only if the user chooses to install a small model).\n809: \n810: ```mermaid\n811: flowchart LR\n812:   Learn[learn] --> EI[EmbeddingProvider Interface]\n813:   Recall[recall] --> EI\n814:   EI --> P1[null provider]\n815:   EI --> P2[local-hash provider]\n816:   EI --> P3[claude-tool provider]\n817:   EI --> P4[onnx local provider]\n818:   EI -- write/read --> DB[(memory_embeddings table)]\n819: ```\n820: \n821: Recall remains FTS5-first; the embedding step is a fallback **and** an enrichment\n822: (pre-rank pass for high-recall queries). Provider is hot-swappable: changing the\n823: provider triggers a one-time re-embed pass via the janitor.\n824: \n825: ### 8.4 C2 — Multi-device E2E encrypted sync\n826: \n827: The developer should have one memory across machines without trusting any cloud.\n828: \n829: ```mermaid\n830: sequenceDiagram\n831:   participant Laptop\n832:   participant Relay as Sync Relay (zero-knowledge)\n833:   participant Desktop\n834: \n835:   Laptop->>Laptop: derive symmetric key from passphrase (Argon2id)\n836:   Laptop->>Laptop: serialise CRDT delta of memory ops\n837:   Laptop->>Laptop: encrypt(delta, key)\n838:   Laptop->>Relay: PUT /blobs/{user-hash}/{seq}\n839:   Desktop->>Relay: GET /blobs/{user-hash}?since=N\n840:   Desktop->>Desktop: decrypt(blob, key)\n841:   Desktop->>Desktop: apply CRDT delta\n842: ```\n843: \n844: **Why CRDT.** Memories accrue independently on each device between syncs; conflict\n845: resolution must be deterministic. A simple op-based CRDT (insert/forget/relate)\n846: with last-writer-wins on `confirm_count` updates is sufficient.\n847: \n848: **Why E2E.** PRD persona Ezra; PRD §7 N1. The relay sees only ciphertext.\n849: \n850: **Opt-in.** Default off. Configurable via `/openltm:admin sync setup`.\n851: \n852: ### 8.5 C3 — Team memory bundles (signed export/import)\n853: \n854: A bundle is a JSON file: schema-version + array of memories + array of relations,\n855: signed with the exporter's keypair. Importer verifies signature, then enters a\n856: **review flow** (not auto-merge): each incoming memory is staged with status\n857: `pending`, surfaced at next SessionStart, accepted/rejected one by one.\n858: \n859: Bundles target the team-lead persona Tara without crossing into multi-tenant\n860: territory. Memory remains per-developer; bundles are a transport.\n861: \n862: ### 8.6 C4 — Conflict detection on learn\n863: \n864: When `learn` is called, the Learn Engine first runs a similarity check against\n865: existing memories. If `(similarity > 0.85) AND (polarity_opposite OR same_dedup_topic)`,\n866: the new memory is staged `pending` with a link to the conflicting memory. The user\n867: is asked at next SessionStart: *forget*, *supersede*, or *coexist*.\n868: \n869: This makes the LTM **self-curating** (PRD §1.1).\n870: \n871: ### 8.7 C5 — Provenance chain\n872: \n873: Every memory gets a `provenance` row chain:\n874: \n875: ```mermaid\n876: flowchart LR\n877:   M[Memory m_42] -- provenance --> P1[source: session sess_abc, turn 7]\n878:   M -- provenance --> P2[source: git-backfill, sha def123]\n879:   M -- provenance --> P3[source: evaluate-session, score 0.92]\n880:   M -- provenance --> P4[source: user-promotion, importance bumped 3 to 5]\n881: ```\n882: \n883: Recall results carry provenance; the explainer (C8) surfaces it inline.\n884: \n885: ### 8.8 C6 — Memory compression / rollups\n886: \n887: When memory count for a project exceeds a threshold (config), the janitor clusters\n888: related memories (by tag overlap + embedding similarity) and proposes a *rollup*:\n889: one new summary memory linked to N source memories via `supersedes` edges. Sources\n890: move to `status='deprecated'` but are retained for time-travel (C9).\n891: \n892: ### 8.9 C7 — Cross-plugin memory contract\n893: \n894: Today the LTM is a silo. Other plugins (`task-tracker`, `code-review`,\n895: `dev-team`, etc.) cannot write into it without bypassing the MCP server.\n896: \n897: The future contract: a published, semver'd MCP tool surface\n898: (`ltm.write_v1(content, category, importance, source_plugin, source_ref)`) that other\n899: plugins call. Writes carry `source_plugin` for provenance. The DAO enforces the\n900: contract. This is what makes LTM the *substrate* for the whole ecosystem.\n901: \n902: ### 8.10 C8 — Recall result explainer\n903: \n904: Each result returns a one-line `why_ranked` (e.g. \"FTS5 BM25=4.2 + recency boost +\n905: importance 4 → score 6.7\"). Powers debuggability; the user can teach the system\n906: by adjusting importance instead of guessing.\n907: \n908: ### 8.11 C9 — Time-travel replay\n909: \n910: A `memory_audit` append-only log (W11) plus a `--at <date>` flag on `recall`\n911: allows reconstructing the memory state at any past point. Boot a session as if it\n912: were a month ago: `/openltm:project replay --date 2026-03-15`.\n913: \n914: ### 8.12 C10 — Memory diffing across versions\n915: \n916: Pair to C9. `/openltm:memory diff --from 2026-01-01 --to 2026-04-01` returns\n917: *added*, *forgotten*, *superseded*, *importance-changed* memories between two\n918: points. Surfaces as a markdown report or a graph-app v2 view.\n919: \n920: ### 8.13 The magnificent container picture\n921: \n922: ```mermaid\n923: C4Container\n924:   title LTM v2 — Magnificent Architecture (target)\n925: \n926:   Person(dev, \"Developer (multi-device, optional team)\")\n927:   System_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\")\n928:   System_Ext(plugins, \"Other Plugins (task-tracker, code-review, ...)\")\n929:   System_Ext(relay, \"Sync Relay (E2E, zero-knowledge)\")\n930: \n931:   System_Boundary(ltm2, \"LTM Plugin v2\") {\n932:     Container(mcp, \"MCP Server v2\", \"Bun\", \"Stable read+write contract; explainable recall\")\n933:     Container(hooks, \"Hook Runners v2\", \"Bun\", \"Structured logs; conflict + rollup banners\")\n934:     Container(dao, \"DAO Layer\", \"Bun module\", \"Single point of DB access; isolates schema\")\n935:     Container(janitor, \"Janitor\", \"Bun scheduler\", \"Decay materialise, conflict detect, rollup propose, sync push/pull\")\n936:     Container(embed, \"Embedding Service\", \"Bun + provider plugins\", \"null / hash / claude-tool / onnx\")\n937:     Container(graph, \"Graph App v2\", \"SPA\", \"Timeline scrubber, cluster view, diff overlay\")\n938:     Container(sync, \"Sync Agent\", \"Bun\", \"CRDT delta serialise + E2E encrypt + relay client\")\n939:     ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db v2\", \"SQLite WAL + partitioned + audited\", \"memories, embeddings (split), provenance, audit, settings, schema_migrations\")\n940:   }\n941: \n942:   Rel(dev, claude, \"Prompts\")\n943:   Rel(claude, mcp, \"MCP\")\n944:   Rel(claude, hooks, \"Lifecycle events\")\n945:   Rel(plugins, mcp, \"Cross-plugin memory contract (C7)\")\n946:   Rel(mcp, dao, \"All access\")\n947:   Rel(hooks, dao, \"All access\")\n948:   Rel(janitor, dao, \"All access\")\n949:   Rel(embed, dao, \"embedding writes / reads\")\n950:   Rel(graph, dao, \"read-only API\")\n951:   Rel(dao, db, \"SQL\")\n952:   Rel(sync, relay, \"PUT/GET encrypted blobs (opt-in)\")\n953:   Rel(sync, dao, \"apply CRDT deltas\")\n954: ```\n955: \n956: ---\n957: \n958: ## 9. Migration Path\n959: \n960: Big-bang rewrites kill plugins. The migration is phased; each phase is shippable\n961: and backwards-compatible until the breaking-change phase, which is gated on a major\n962: version bump.\n963: \n964: ### Phase 0 — Foundation hardening (non-breaking, 1.5.x)\n965: \n966: Goal: fix the weaknesses that don't require schema or contract changes.\n967: \n968: - **W1, W5:** Add structured hook + MCP event log table. `/openltm:doctor` reads it.\n969: - **W3:** Replace ad-hoc `runMigrations` with a `schema_migrations` table and\n970:   numbered SQL files. Backfill from current state.\n971: - **W6:** Add a documented \"dev mode\" symlink helper to `/openltm:admin`.\n972: - **W2:** Atomic-write `registry.json` (tmp + rename).\n973: \n974: Backwards compatible. No schema rename. No MCP contract change.\n975: \n976: ### Phase 1 — DAO + observability (non-breaking, 1.6.x)\n977: \n978: - Introduce `src/dao/` as the single point of DB access (W8).\n979: - Refactor `mcp-server.ts`, hooks, and graph-server to call through DAO.\n980: - Add latency / recall-hit telemetry to the DAO; surface in `/openltm:health`.\n981: - Move `embedding` BLOB into `memory_embeddings` sibling table (W7); migration is a\n982:   copy + drop column. MCP responses naturally shrink.\n983: \n984: Backwards compatible at the MCP contract level. Schema migrates idempotently.\n985: \n986: ### Phase 2 — Provenance + audit (non-breaking, 1.7.x)\n987: \n988: - Add `memory_audit` (W11) and `memory_provenance` (W9, C5) tables.\n989: - Hooks and MCP write through DAO so audit is uniform.\n990: - New optional fields on recall results: `provenance`, `why_ranked` (C8).\n991: - Existing memories get a backfilled `provenance` row of type `legacy`.\n992: \n993: ### Phase 3 — Embedding provider abstraction (non-breaking, 1.8.x)\n994: \n995: - Introduce `EmbeddingProvider` interface (C1).\n996: - Default provider remains the current one; users can opt into `claude-tool` or\n997:   `local-hash`.\n998: - Recall logic gains a \"rerank with embeddings\" pass for high-recall queries.\n999: \n1000: ### Phase 4 — Janitor (non-breaking, 1.9.x)\n1001: \n1002: - Materialise `decay_score` on `memories` (W4); janitor refreshes on a schedule.\n1003: - Conflict detector (C4) runs on `learn` and stages conflicting memories\n1004:   `pending`.\n1005: - Rollup proposer (C6) runs nightly; user reviews via SessionStart banner.\n1006: \n1007: ### Phase 5 — Cross-plugin contract (semver-major, 2.0.0)\n1008: \n1009: - Publish stable, versioned MCP write surface (C7).\n1010: - Lock in DAO function signatures for external callers.\n1011: - Deprecate the last unversioned write paths.\n1012: \n1013: This is a **major version bump** because the published contract becomes a\n1014: compatibility commitment.\n1015: \n1016: ### Phase 6 — Sync + bundles (non-breaking on the contract, 2.1.x onward)\n1017: \n1018: - Sync agent + relay protocol (C2).\n1019: - Memory bundle export/import flow (C3).\n1020: - Both opt-in; default off; no impact on local-only users.\n1021: \n1022: ### Phase 7 — Time-travel + diffing (non-breaking, 2.2.x onward)\n1023: \n1024: - Replay (C9) and diff (C10) commands; both depend on the audit log from Phase 2.\n1025: \n1026: ### Backwards-compatibility ledger\n1027: \n1028: | Phase | Schema breaking? | MCP contract breaking? | User-visible CLI breaking? |\n1029: |-------|------------------|-----------------------|----------------------------|\n1030: | 0 | No | No | No |\n1031: | 1 | Migrates idempotently | No | No |\n1032: | 2 | Adds columns/tables | Adds optional fields | No |\n1033: | 3 | No | Adds optional fields | No (provider choice) |\n1034: | 4 | Adds column (decay_score) | No | New banners only |\n1035: | 5 | No | **Yes — semver major** | No |\n1036: | 6 | Adds tables (sync state) | Adds optional sync tools | New `/openltm:admin sync` group |\n1037: | 7 | No | Adds optional tools | New `/openltm:memory diff/replay` |\n1038: \n1039: ---\n1040: \n1041: ## 10. Non-Goals\n1042: \n1043: To keep scope honest:\n1044: \n1045: - **NG1.** Building an embedding model. Embedding is delegated to a provider;\n1046:   the plugin never trains.\n1047: - **NG2.** Multi-tenant cloud. Even with C2 sync, there is no shared multi-tenant\n1048:   store. Each user owns their relay namespace and their key.\n1049: - **NG3.** Replacing ADRs, PR descriptions, or design docs. LTM captures the\n1050:   *reasoning behind* the code; durable design docs (like this one) live in `docs/`.\n1051: - **NG4.** Online learning from raw transcripts. EvaluateSession proposes\n1052:   *distilled* insights; full transcripts never enter the DB (PRD N6).\n1053: - **NG5.** Cross-plugin **read-write coupling** that breaks the LTM if another\n1054:   plugin disappears. The cross-plugin contract (C7) is one-way (others write to\n1055:   LTM); LTM does not depend on any other plugin to function.\n1056: \n1057: ---\n1058: \n1059: ## Hand-off\n1060: \n1061: This spec unblocks:\n1062: \n1063: - **database-admin** — owns Phase 0 W3 (schema_migrations table), Phase 1 schema\n1064:   refactor (split `memory_embeddings`), Phase 2 audit/provenance tables. Uses §5\n1065:   (Data Model) as ground truth.\n1066: - **backend-developer** — owns DAO refactor (Phase 1), embedding provider\n1067:   interface (Phase 3), janitor (Phase 4). Uses §3 (components) and ADRs as\n1068:   guardrails.\n1069: - **devops-engineer** — owns the sync relay (Phase 6) deployment + key management\n1070:   if/when sync ships.\n1071: - **ui-ux-designer** — owns the surfaces called out in PRD §10 hand-off and the\n1072:   graph-app v2 (C9, C10 visualisation) in Phase 7.\n1073: \n1074: Every dev task created against this spec must `dependsOn` the originating\n1075: architecture task so the design ↔ implementation trace remains intact.\n\n(End of file - total 1075 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# ARCHITECTURE — OpenLTM Plugin\n\n* **Version:** 1.3 (against plugin v2.9.0)\n* **Owner:** Rohi Rikman\n* **Status:** Baseline architecture spec; companion to `docs/internal/PRD.md`\n* **Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n\nThis document describes the as-built architecture of the OpenLTM plugin, an honest\nassessment of its weaknesses, and a target \"magnificent\" architecture with a phased\nmigration path. It is the reference artifact for the `database-admin` agent (schema work),\nthe `backend-developer` agent (server / hook work), and the `cloud-architect` agent (any\nfuture sync surfaces).\n\nThe PRD (`docs/internal/PRD.md`) is the contract: §4 (feature inventory) is the as-built ground\ntruth; §5 (user stories) the acceptance contract; §6 (gaps) the opportunity space this\nspec turns into a roadmap.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"# ARCHITECTURE — OpenLTM Plugin\n\n* **Version:** 1.3 (against plugin v2.9.0)\n* **Owner:** Rohi Rikman\n* **Status:** Baseline architecture spec; companion to `docs/internal/PRD.md`\n* **Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n\nThis document describes the as-built architecture of the OpenLTM plugin, an honest\nassessment of its weaknesses, and a target \"magnificent\" architecture with a phased\nmigration path. It is the reference artifact for the `database-admin` agent (schema work),\nthe `backend-developer` agent (server / hook work), and the `cloud-architect` agent (any\nfuture sync surfaces).\n\nThe PRD (`docs/internal/PRD.md`) is the contract: §4 (feature inventory) is the as-built ground\ntruth; §5 (user stories) the acceptance contract; §6 (gaps) the opportunity space this\nspec turns into a roadmap.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. System Context (C4 L1)\n2. Container Diagram (C4 L2)\n3. Component Diagram (C4 L3)\n4. Data Flow: Full Session Lifecycle\n5. Data Model Overview\n6. Architectural Decision Records\n7. Current Architectural Weaknesses\n8. Magnificent Future Architecture\n9. Migration Path\n10. Non-Goals\n\n---\n\n## 1. System Context (C4 Level 1)\n\nThe LTM plugin is a sidecar process to the Claude Code harness. Everything it does is\nlocal to the developer's machine. There is no cloud dependency, no telemetry, no\nmulti-tenant store. Two external integration surfaces exist: the MCP protocol (how\nClaude talks to the plugin) and Git (read-only, used by the GitLearn skill for backfill).\n\n```mermaid\nC4Context\n  title LTM Plugin — System Context\n\n  Person(dev, \"Developer\", \"Solo dev, power user, team lead, enterprise dev, or onboarder\")\n\n  System_Boundary(host, \"Developer Machine\") {\n    System(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"CLI / agent runtime; loads plugins, runs hooks, brokers MCP\")\n    System(ltm, \"LTM Plugin\", \"Persistent semantic memory, context restore, decay, learn/recall\")\n    SystemDb(sqlite, \"openltm.db\", \"Local SQLite (WAL mode) under CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA\")\n    System_Ext(git, \"Git Repo\", \"Source of commits for GitLearn backfill\")\n    System_Ext(browser, \"Web Browser\", \"Renders graph-app for memory visualization\")\n  }\n\n  Rel(dev, claude, \"Types prompts, runs slash commands\")\n  Rel(claude, ltm, \"MCP STDIO + hook stdin/stdout\")\n  Rel(ltm, sqlite, \"Reads / writes (WAL)\")\n  Rel(ltm, git, \"Reads commit history (read-only)\")\n  Rel(dev, browser, \"Opens localhost graph UI\")\n  Rel(browser, ltm, \"HTTP to graph-server\")\n```\n\n**Boundaries**\n\n- **Inside the boundary:** plugin code, the SQLite DB, the registry JSON, and the\n  cache directory the plugin loader reads from. All on the developer's filesystem.\n- **Outside:** the Claude Code harness itself (a black box that fires lifecycle events\n  and routes MCP calls). The browser, used only for the optional graph UI.\n- **Explicitly excluded:** any third-party API. The plugin makes **zero outbound\n  network calls** by default. Any future cloud sync (G-I) is opt-in and end-to-end\n  encrypted.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Container Diagram (C4 Level 2)\n\nThe plugin decomposes into five runtime containers plus shared on-disk state. The MCP\nserver is the tool surface; hooks are short-lived processes triggered by lifecycle\nevents; the graph server is opt-in.\n\n```mermaid\nC4Container\n  title LTM Plugin — Containers\n\n  Person(dev, \"Developer\")\n  System_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\")\n\n  System_Boundary(ltm, \"LTM Plugin\") {\n    Container(mcp, \"MCP Server\", \"Bun + TypeScript, STDIO transport\", \"Long-lived; serves recall, learn, forget, relate, context, context_items, graph\")\n    Container(hooks, \"Hook Runners\", \"Bun scripts invoked by Claude Code\", \"SessionStart, PreCompact, EvaluateSession, UpdateContext\")\n    Container(cmds, \"Command + Skill Layer\", \"Markdown specs in commands/ and skills/\", \"Slash commands (/openltm:*), skills (ContinuousLearning, GitLearn, Learned, session-context)\")\n    Container(graph, \"Graph Server\", \"Bun HTTP server (opt-in)\", \"Serves graph-app SPA + JSON memory/edge feed\")\n    Container(graphapp, \"Graph App\", \"Static SPA served by graph server\", \"Force-directed memory graph viz; Playwright E2E tests\")\n\n    ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\", \"SQLite WAL\", \"memories, context_items, tags, memory_relations, memories_fts, settings\")\n    ContainerDb(reg, \"registry.json\", \"JSON file under ~/.claude/projects/\", \"cwd → project name mapping\")\n    ContainerDb(summary, \"context-summary.md\", \"Markdown fallback file\", \"Human-readable context snapshot regenerated on PreCompact\")\n  }\n\n  Rel(dev, claude, \"Prompts, slash commands\")\n  Rel(claude, mcp, \"MCP STDIO (JSON-RPC)\")\n  Rel(claude, hooks, \"Spawn process, pipe JSON stdin/stdout\")\n  Rel(claude, cmds, \"Resolves slash command and skill markdown into prompts\")\n  Rel(mcp, db, \"SQL queries (single shared connection)\")\n  Rel(hooks, db, \"SQL queries (shared via shared-db.ts)\")\n  Rel(hooks, reg, \"Read / write project map\")\n  Rel(hooks, summary, \"Regenerate on PreCompact\")\n  Rel(dev, graph, \"/openltm:admin server start\")\n  Rel(graph, graphapp, \"Serves SPA\")\n  Rel(graphapp, graph, \"Fetch /api/memories, /api/relations\")\n  Rel(graph, db, \"Read-only queries\")\n```\n\n**Notes on shared state**\n\n- A single SQLite connection is held by `shared-db.ts` and reused across MCP server,\n  hooks, and graph server within one process. WAL mode permits concurrent readers\n  with a single writer; cross-process safety relies on SQLite's file locking.\n- `registry.json` is a small JSON map. Concurrent writes are rare (only during\n  `/openltm:project register` or `SessionStart` first-touch) but unsynchronised — a\n  known weakness called out in §7.\n- `context-summary.md` is a write-mostly artifact regenerated by `PreCompact`. It is\n  never the source of truth; the DB is.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Component Diagram (C4 Level 3)\n\nThis level breaks the **MCP server** and **hook runners** into their internal\ncomponents. The command/skill layer is intentionally not decomposed — markdown specs\nhave no internal components.\n\n### 3.1 MCP Server components\n\n```mermaid\nC4Component\n  title MCP Server — Components\n\n  Container_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"MCP client\")\n  ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\")\n\n  Container_Boundary(mcp, \"MCP Server (src/mcp-server.ts)\") {\n    Component(transport, \"STDIO Transport\", \"@modelcontextprotocol/sdk\", \"JSON-RPC over stdin/stdout\")\n    Component(toolreg, \"Tool Registry\", \"McpServer.tool()\", \"Declares recall, learn, forget, relate, context, context_items, graph with Zod schemas\")\n    Component(recall, \"Recall Engine\", \"src/db.ts:recall\", \"FTS5 query → semantic fallback → merge → rank by importance/recency/decay\")\n    Component(learn, \"Learn Engine\", \"src/db.ts:learn\", \"Validate → redact secrets → dedup-key check → insert → return id\")\n    Component(ctxmerge, \"Context Merge\", \"src/db.ts:getContextMerge + src/context.ts:getItems\", \"Build the goal+decisions+progress+gotchas envelope for SessionStart\")\n    Component(graphtrav, \"Graph Traversal\", \"src/graph.ts:traverseGraph\", \"BFS over memory_relations; powers graph and visualization feed\")\n    Component(formatter, \"Compact Formatter\", \"src/mcp-server.ts:compact/strip\", \"Strips embedding blob, truncates content to keep MCP responses small\")\n    Component(config, \"Config Reader\", \"src/config.ts\", \"Reads plugin config; respects mcp.enabled flag\")\n  }\n\n  Rel(claude, transport, \"JSON-RPC\")\n  Rel(transport, toolreg, \"dispatch\")\n  Rel(toolreg, recall, \"recall\")\n  Rel(toolreg, learn, \"learn\")\n  Rel(toolreg, ctxmerge, \"context, context_items\")\n  Rel(toolreg, graphtrav, \"graph\")\n  Rel(toolreg, formatter, \"shape response\")\n  Rel(toolreg, config, \"feature flag check\")\n  Rel(recall, db, \"FTS5 + base table queries\")\n  Rel(learn, db, \"INSERT memories, INSERT memories_fts via trigger\")\n  Rel(ctxmerge, db, \"SELECT context_items + memories\")\n  Rel(graphtrav, db, \"SELECT memory_relations\")\n```\n\n### 3.2 Hook Runners components\n\n```mermaid\nC4Component\n  title Hook Runners — Components\n\n  Container_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\", \"Spawns hooks per lifecycle event\")\n  ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db\")\n  ContainerDb(reg, \"registry.json\")\n  ContainerDb(summary, \"context-summary.md\")\n\n  Container_Boundary(hooks, \"Hook Runners (hooks/*.ts)\") {\n    Component(start, \"SessionStart hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Resolve project from cwd → registry; rebuild context-summary.md; emit injection block\")\n    Component(pre, \"PreCompact hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Pull all 4 context types from DB; serialize to context-summary.md (~60 line cap)\")\n    Component(eval, \"EvaluateSession hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Score session; identify candidate insights; (proposes / auto-writes per OQ4)\")\n    Component(update, \"UpdateContext hook\", \"Bun script\", \"Append progress entries; trim to last 20; bump last-touched timestamps\")\n    Component(resolver, \"Project Resolver\", \"shared util\", \"cwd → project name via registry; auto-register on first touch\")\n    Component(injector, \"Context Injector\", \"shared util\", \"Compose ## Restored Project Context block; truncate to ~60 lines + footer\")\n    Component(redact, \"Secret Redactor\", \"shared util\", \"Pattern-match API keys, JWTs, AWS keys; replace with [REDACTED:type]\")\n  }\n\n  Rel(claude, start, \"spawn(SessionStart)\")\n  Rel(claude, pre, \"spawn(PreCompact)\")\n  Rel(claude, eval, \"spawn(EvaluateSession)\")\n  Rel(claude, update, \"spawn(UpdateContext)\")\n  Rel(start, resolver, \"resolve\")\n  Rel(start, injector, \"build block\")\n  Rel(start, db, \"SELECT context_items + globals\")\n  Rel(start, reg, \"read / auto-register\")\n  Rel(pre, db, \"SELECT all context types\")\n  Rel(pre, summary, \"write\")\n  Rel(eval, db, \"INSERT memories (or pending)\")\n  Rel(eval, redact, \"scrub before write\")\n  Rel(update, db, \"INSERT progress; UPDATE timestamps\")\n```\n\n**Component responsibilities at a glance**\n\n| Component | Responsibility | Single source of truth for |\n|-----------|----------------|---------------------------|\n| Recall Engine | Search ranking | Merging FTS5 + semantic results, applying decay |\n| Learn Engine | Write path | Dedup, redaction, importance/category enforcement |\n| Context Merge | Read path for SessionStart | Envelope shape (goal + decisions + progress + gotchas) |\n| Project Resolver | cwd → project | Authoritative map; auto-registration |\n| Secret Redactor | Pattern scrub | Redaction policy, called from learn + EvaluateSession |\n| Context Injector | Format injection | 60-line budget, footer rendering |\n| Compact Formatter | MCP response shaping | Stripping embedding blob, content truncation |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Data Flow: Full Session Lifecycle\n\nThis is the canonical end-to-end flow that ties every container and component together.\nA \"session\" spans from Claude Code launch in a project cwd through to clean exit (or\ncompaction-triggered restart). The diagram shows one full cycle.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n  autonumber\n  actor Dev as Developer\n  participant Claude as Claude Code Harness\n  participant Start as SessionStart hook\n  participant Reg as registry.json\n  participant DB as openltm.db (SQLite)\n  participant MCP as MCP Server\n  participant Eval as EvaluateSession hook\n  participant Pre as PreCompact hook\n  participant Update as UpdateContext hook\n  participant Sum as context-summary.md\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session start ---\n  Dev->>Claude: cd into project, launch Claude Code\n  Claude->>Start: spawn(SessionStart, stdin=cwd)\n  Start->>Reg: resolve(cwd) → project_name (auto-register if new)\n  Start->>DB: SELECT goal, decisions, gotchas, progress (project) + importance-5 globals\n  Start-->>Claude: stdout = \"## Restored Project Context\\n...\" (≤ 60 lines)\n  Claude-->>Dev: render injected block\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Recall before deciding ---\n  Dev->>Claude: prompt that requires past context\n  Claude->>MCP: recall({ query, project })\n  MCP->>DB: FTS5(MATCH) → ranked rowids\n  alt FTS5 returns < 3 results\n    MCP->>DB: semantic fallback (embedding similarity)\n    MCP->>MCP: merge + dedup by id\n  end\n  MCP->>MCP: apply decay scoring + importance boost\n  MCP-->>Claude: top-N memories (compact, embedding-stripped)\n  Claude-->>Dev: answer informed by recalled context\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Work + learn ---\n  Dev->>Claude: makes a decision; runs /openltm:memory learn\n  Claude->>MCP: learn({ content, category, importance, project })\n  MCP->>MCP: redact secrets; compute dedup_key\n  MCP->>DB: INSERT memories (trigger writes memories_fts)\n  MCP-->>Claude: { id }\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Mid-session: compaction ---\n  Claude->>Pre: spawn(PreCompact)\n  Pre->>DB: SELECT all 4 context types for project\n  Pre->>Sum: write context-summary.md (~60 lines, fallback)\n  Pre-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Claude: compact transcript\n  Note over Claude: Next assistant turn re-reads context-summary.md if needed\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session end ---\n  Claude->>Update: spawn(UpdateContext)\n  Update->>DB: INSERT progress; trim oldest > 20; UPDATE last_touched\n  Update-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Eval: spawn(EvaluateSession)\n  Eval->>DB: scan transcript-derived signals; propose / write candidate insights\n  Eval-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude-->>Dev: clean exit\n```\n\n**Per-step contracts**\n\n| Step | Read from | Writes to | Failure mode |\n|------|-----------|-----------|--------------|\n| SessionStart | DB, registry | registry (auto-register only) | Hook silent-fail → no injection; `/openltm:doctor` detects |\n| recall | DB (FTS5 + base) | DB (last_recalled_at, recall_count) | Returns empty array; never throws into Claude |\n| learn | — | DB (memories, memories_fts via trigger) | Reject duplicate dedup_key; redact before write |\n| PreCompact | DB | context-summary.md | If write fails, post-compact session loses fallback only |\n| EvaluateSession | transcript signals, DB | DB (memories) | OQ4 — propose vs. auto-write is open |\n| UpdateContext | — | DB (context_items progress) | Trim ensures bounded growth |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Data Model Overview\n\nThe persistent store is one SQLite file (`openltm.db`) under `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}`.\nSchema lives in `src/schema.sql` and is extended idempotently by migrations in\n`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n| `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n| `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n| `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n| `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n| `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n\n### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n| `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n| `content` | Free text |\n| `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n| `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n\n### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n\n- `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n  Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n  insert/update/delete.\n- Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n  `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n- BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n  decay factors before returning top-N.\n\n### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n\nThe current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n\n- **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n- **Rule sketch:**\n  - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n  - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n    by a decay factor (< 1).\n  - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n- **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n  (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n- **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n  and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n\n### 5.6 Relationships\n\n```mermaid\nerDiagram\n  memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n  tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n  memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n  memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n  memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n  memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n```\n\n### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)\n\n`~/.claude/projects/registry.json` holds the cwd → project_name map. It is a JSON\nfile (not a table) for cross-plugin readability and trivial inspection. Concurrent\nwrite safety is **not** guaranteed — a known weakness (§7).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Architectural Decision Records\n\nEach ADR is short and load-bearing. Format: Status, Context, Decision, Alternatives,\nConsequences. Every ADR includes at least one rejected alternative.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-001 — SQLite as the storage engine\n\n**Status:** Accepted. In production since v1.0.\n\n**Context.** The plugin needs durable, queryable, low-latency storage on the\ndeveloper's machine. It must survive Claude Code restarts, plugin upgrades, and\nmachine sleep. Median write latency target: < 50 ms p95 (PRD §8.4 R3). Median recall\n< 200 ms (G2). Zero cloud dependency by default (PRD §7 N1).\n\n**Decision.** Use SQLite (via `bun:sqlite`) in WAL mode, single file at\n`${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/openltm.db`. FTS5 virtual table for full-text search.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Postgres / managed DB.** Rejected. Adds an installation dependency, defeats the\n  zero-cloud promise, and is overkill for single-user data volumes (~10⁴–10⁶ rows\n  realistic ceiling).\n- **Flat JSON / Markdown files (the pre-1.0 design).** Rejected. No transactional\n  semantics, no FTS, no concurrent reader safety, O(N) scan per recall. The current\n  `context-summary.md` is the vestigial fallback; it is a *projection*, not the truth.\n- **DuckDB.** Considered. Better analytical perf, but heavier binary, weaker FTS\n  story, less Bun-native tooling, and write-heavy workloads (learn + decay updates)\n  favour SQLite.\n- **LevelDB / RocksDB key-value.** Rejected. No SQL, no FTS5, would need a hand-rolled\n  index for every query path.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) One-file backup story; `cp openltm.db openltm.db.bak` is a complete export.\n- (+) FTS5 ships in SQLite — no extra dependency for full-text search.\n- (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process; no IPC overhead per query.\n- (–) Single-writer constraint (mitigated by WAL); cross-process locking is the\n  developer's responsibility to understand.\n- (–) Schema migrations must be hand-coded and idempotent (see `src/shared-db.ts`).\n  ADR-004 and §7 weakness W3 expand on this.\n- (–) Embedding column as BLOB grows the row size fast; the formatter strips it\n  before MCP transmission to avoid 260 KB-per-memory responses.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-002 — Hook-based lifecycle integration\n\n**Status:** Accepted.\n\n**Context.** Claude Code is a black-box harness. The plugin needs to (a) inject\ncontext at session start, (b) survive compaction without state loss, (c) record\nprogress at session end, and (d) propose learnings post-session. MCP tools cover the\n\"on demand\" surface but not \"automatic on lifecycle event\".\n\n**Decision.** Use Claude Code's hook surface for four lifecycle events:\n`SessionStart`, `PreCompact`, `EvaluateSession`, `UpdateContext`. Hooks are\nshort-lived Bun scripts in `hooks/`. They share the DB connection logic with the MCP\nserver via `src/shared-db.ts`.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **MCP-only.** Rejected. There is no MCP equivalent to \"this is a fresh session,\n  inject context now\". Without hooks, the developer would have to manually call\n  `context` at every session start — defeats J1 and US-1.\n- **Background daemon.** Rejected. Long-lived process management on developer\n  machines is fragile (sleep/wake, terminal close). Also conflates \"react to event\"\n  with \"serve queries\".\n- **Polling cron.** Rejected. Not aligned with session boundaries; can't inject at\n  start.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Hook semantics align directly with PRD user stories US-1, US-4, US-13, US-17.\n- (+) Each hook is independently testable and replaceable.\n- (–) Hook failures are silent by default — drove the need for `/openltm:doctor` (US-9).\n- (–) Coupling to Claude Code's hook contract; if the harness changes the contract,\n  hooks break. Mitigated by the `update-wiring.ts` postinstall script that keeps\n  `settings.json` in sync.\n- (–) Four hook processes per session add some startup latency; offset by Bun's\n  fast cold start (~30 ms typical).\n\n---\n\n### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n\n**Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n\n**Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\nmemories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\nsingle-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n\n**Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\nreturns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n`embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\nboost, return top-N.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n  (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n  (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n  keyword-shaped.\n- **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n  dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n- **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n  queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n  patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n- **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n  beats raw similarity for natural language.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n- (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n- (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n  to avoid bloat.\n- (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n  (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n- (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n\n---\n\n### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n\n**Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n\n**Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\nthat low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n\n**Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n`importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n\n1. `importance == 5` → no decay (immortal memories).\n2. Else if `(now - last_recalled_at) > 90 days` AND `importance < 3` → multiply\n   rank by a decay factor < 1.\n3. Recently-recalled memories receive a freshness boost.\n\nThe exact function form (linear, exponential, recall-driven) is configurable via\nthe `settings` table and remains an open experiment.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Stored decay score updated on a schedule.** Rejected for v1. Adds a janitor\n  cron, a write-amplification problem, and a stale-score hazard. Recompute-on-read\n  is cheap at single-user scale.\n- **Hard expiry / auto-delete.** Rejected. Violates the developer's expectation that\n  memories are durable. Decay should rerank, not destroy.\n- **No decay.** Rejected. Long-running projects would drown new recalls under old\n  ones (PRD §1.1 — \"stale knowledge decays gracefully\").\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Zero write amplification; decay costs only at read time.\n- (+) Tunable without a migration — settings table holds parameters.\n- (–) Recall latency is sensitive to N (rows scanned). At scale this becomes a\n  problem (W4 in §7) — addressed in the magnificent architecture by precomputed\n  decay buckets.\n- (–) Importance must be set correctly by the user / EvaluateSession or the model\n  is gameable.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-005 — Plugin cache vs. source-repo execution model\n\n**Status:** Accepted (with operational caveat).\n\n**Context.** Claude Code plugins are loaded from\n`~/.claude/plugins/cache/<plugin>/<version>/`, **not** from the source repo. A\ndeveloper iterating on the plugin code locally must either (a) bump the version and\ntrigger marketplace update, or (b) hot-patch the cache directory.\n\n**Decision.** Treat the cache directory as the runtime, the source repo as the\nsource of truth. Document the dual-write requirement explicitly (see\n`CLAUDE.md` \"Cache Sync — MANDATORY\"). The `postinstall` script\n(`scripts/update-wiring.ts`) updates `settings.json` hook wiring at install time.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Symlink cache → source repo.** Rejected. Fragile across plugin updates;\n  marketplace install would clobber it.\n- **Bundle plugin into a single file installed elsewhere.** Rejected. Loses Bun's\n  fast script execution and complicates the multi-file plugin layout (commands,\n  skills, hooks, src).\n- **Git submodule the source into the cache path.** Rejected. Fights the plugin\n  loader's expectations; the marketplace owns that directory.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Plays nicely with the marketplace update flow — one click bumps the version\n  and refreshes the cache.\n- (–) Two-place edits during local development (source repo + cache). Mitigated by\n  documentation but is a developer-experience tax.\n- (–) \"Why didn't my fix take effect?\" is a known foot-gun. Driver of the\n  `/openltm:doctor` checks for cache version vs. installed version.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-006 — Bun as runtime\n\n**Status:** Accepted.\n\n**Context.** The plugin is TypeScript end to end. It needs (a) fast cold-start for\nhooks (each hook spawns a fresh process), (b) native SQLite, (c) ESM-first with\ntop-level await, (d) zero compile step in development.\n\n**Decision.** Bun is the runtime for the MCP server, hooks, and graph server.\nDependencies: `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk`, `zod`. SQLite is `bun:sqlite` (built in,\nno native rebuild). TypeScript runs without a build step in development.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Node.js + tsx / ts-node.** Rejected. Slower cold start (~150 ms vs. Bun's ~30 ms).\n  For four hooks per session this matters. Also requires `better-sqlite3` native\n  module, which breaks under Node version mismatches.\n- **Deno.** Considered. Fast, ESM-native, but plugin author's existing tooling and\n  the marketplace ecosystem assume Node-shaped runtimes; `bun:sqlite` is closer to\n  the Node ecosystem than Deno's Web-Crypto-flavoured world.\n- **Compiled Go / Rust binary.** Rejected. Loses the \"just edit a file\" hackability\n  PRD persona Pat values; complicates cross-platform distribution.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Cold-start matters: SessionStart hook completes inside a typical Claude Code\n  startup window without perceptible delay.\n- (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process and zero-config.\n- (–) Bun is younger than Node; some ecosystem packages may misbehave. Mitigated by\n  keeping the dependency surface tiny (2 prod deps).\n- (–) Bun must be installed on the developer's machine. This is documented as a\n  prereq.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Current Architectural Weaknesses\n\nAn honest list. Each item names the symptom, the root cause, and a one-line direction.\n\n### W1 — Silent hook failures\n\n**Symptom.** Hooks fail silently when stdin/stdout protocol breaks, settings.json\nloses a wiring entry, or the cache version drifts. The user notices only when\ncontext isn't injected.\n\n**Root cause.** Hooks are fire-and-forget; Claude Code does not surface stderr to\nthe user prominently. There is no structured \"hook ran successfully\" telemetry.\n\n**Direction.** Add a per-hook structured log (DB table or local JSON), and have\n`/openltm:doctor` read it.\n\n### W2 — Concurrent writes to `registry.json`\n\n**Symptom.** Two Claude Code sessions starting in different cwds at the same time\ncan race on `registry.json` writes; last-writer-wins.\n\n**Root cause.** `registry.json` is a flat JSON file with no file lock or atomic\nrename. Auto-registration happens on first SessionStart per cwd.\n\n**Direction.** Move to atomic write (write-temp, rename) or push the registry into\nthe DB as a `projects` table.\n\n### W3 — Schema migrations are hand-rolled per column\n\n**Symptom.** Each new column needs a manual `hasColumn` check and an `ALTER TABLE`\nin `shared-db.ts`. There is no version table, no migration history, no rollback path.\nPRD US-10 (`/openltm:admin migrate`) sits on top of this fragile foundation.\n\n**Root cause.** No first-class migration framework. `shared-db.ts:runMigrations` is\nimperative and grew organically.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `schema_migrations` table with `version`, `applied_at`,\n`checksum`. Each migration is a numbered SQL file. Migrator runs in order in a\ntransaction.\n\n### W4 — Recall ranking is O(N) at recall time\n\n**Symptom.** Decay scoring re-ranks every FTS5 hit at query time. At 10⁵+ memories\nthe 200 ms recall budget is at risk.\n\n**Root cause.** Decay is computed in JavaScript over the result set rather than\nexpressed as a SQL `ORDER BY` over indexed columns.\n\n**Direction.** Materialise a `decay_score` column maintained by a low-frequency\njanitor; use it in `ORDER BY`. Trade write amplification for read latency.\n\n### W5 — No structured observability\n\n**Symptom.** Latency, recall hit rate, learn frequency — none are recorded. PRD §8\nmetrics are aspirational without instrumentation.\n\n**Root cause.** No metrics surface. No event log table. `/openltm:health` reads\ncounts but not timings.\n\n**Direction.** Add an `events` table (append-only): event_type, latency_ms,\nresult_count, timestamp. Aggregate in `/openltm:health`.\n\n### W6 — Cache vs. source-repo dual-write\n\n**Symptom.** \"I fixed it but it didn't take effect.\" See ADR-005.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `dev mode` flag that, when set, makes the cache directory a\nsymlink to the source repo. Off by default for end users.\n\n### W7 — MCP response size pressure\n\n**Symptom.** `embedding` BLOBs serialise as `{\"0\":59,\"1\":...}` JSON objects of\n~260 KB each over MCP. The `compact`/`strip` formatter exists *because* of this.\n\n**Root cause.** MCP responses are JSON; embeddings are binary. The strip is a\nband-aid, not a fix.\n\n**Direction.** Move embeddings out of the `memories` table into a sibling\n`memory_embeddings(memory_id, vec BLOB)` table; MCP queries never join it.\n\n### W8 — Coupling between hooks and DB schema\n\n**Symptom.** A schema change requires updating hooks, MCP server, and graph server\ntogether. Versioning is per-plugin, not per-component.\n\n**Direction.** Define a small data-access layer (DAO) in `src/dao/` with stable\nfunction signatures; everything else calls through it. Schema changes are then\nisolated to the DAO.\n\n### W9 — No memory provenance\n\n**Symptom.** A recalled memory tells you *what* but not *where it came from*\n(which conversation turn, which commit, which file). G-J in the PRD calls this out.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `provenance` table or columns: source_type\n(`session` / `git-backfill` / `manual` / `evaluate`), source_ref (session id, SHA,\nfile path).\n\n### W10 — `EvaluateSession` policy is unclear\n\n**Symptom.** PRD OQ4: should EvaluateSession auto-write or always propose? Today's\nbehaviour is implementation-defined and not surfaced to the user.\n\n**Direction.** Add a config flag (`evaluate.auto_promote`); default to \"propose,\nrequire user confirmation via a banner at next SessionStart\".\n\n### W11 — No write audit trail\n\n**Symptom.** A memory is wrong; the user can `forget` it but cannot answer\n\"who/what wrote this in the first place?\".\n\n**Direction.** Append-only `memory_audit` table: memory_id, op (insert/update/\nforget/redact), actor (mcp tool name / hook name), timestamp, before/after diff.\n\n### W12 — Single SQLite connection assumes single-process plugin\n\n**Symptom.** Two MCP server instances against the same DB (e.g., from two Claude\nCode windows) rely solely on SQLite WAL for safety. There is no application-level\nwrite coordination.\n\n**Direction.** Either move writes through a single coordinator process (a daemon)\nor accept WAL semantics and document them. Surfaced in PRD OQ2.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Magnificent Future Architecture\n\nThis is the bold target. It is **not** what we build next sprint — it is what we\nplan towards. Each capability ties back to a PRD §1.1 vision bullet and to a §6 gap.\n\n### 8.1 Architectural pillars\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TB\n  subgraph Local[\"Developer Machine (canonical store)\"]\n    DB[(openltm.db v2: WAL, partitioned, audited)]\n    Embed[Embedding Service: pluggable provider]\n    Janitor[Janitor: decay materialiser, conflict detector, summariser]\n    DAO[Data-Access Layer / contract surface]\n    MCP[MCP Server v2: explainable recall]\n    Hooks[Hook Runners v2: structured logs]\n    Graph[Graph App v2: timeline + clusters]\n  end\n\n  subgraph Sync[\"Optional Sync Plane (E2E encrypted)\"]\n    Relay[Sync Relay: zero-knowledge blob store]\n    Bundle[Memory Bundle: signed, exportable]\n  end\n\n  subgraph Ecosystem[\"Cross-Plugin Memory Contract\"]\n    TaskTracker[task-tracker plugin]\n    CodeReview[code-review plugin]\n    Other[other plugins...]\n  end\n\n  Local <-- E2E encrypted blobs --> Relay\n  Local -- export / import --> Bundle\n  Bundle -- import --> Local\n  Ecosystem -- writes via DAO --> DAO\n  DAO --> DB\n  Janitor --> DB\n  MCP --> DAO\n  Hooks --> DAO\n  Embed --> DB\n  Graph --> DAO\n```\n\n### 8.2 Capability map\n\n| # | Capability | PRD link | Gap link |\n|---|------------|----------|----------|\n| C1 | Pluggable embedding provider | OQ1 | G-E |\n| C2 | Multi-device E2E sync | §1.1 portable | G-I |\n| C3 | Team memory bundles (signed) | persona Tara | G-A |\n| C4 | Conflict detection on learn | §1.1 self-curating | G-F |\n| C5 | Provenance chain per memory | safety / audit | G-J |\n| C6 | Memory compression / rollups | §1.1 sub-linear growth | G-L |\n| C7 | Cross-plugin memory contract | ecosystem | G-M |\n| C8 | Recall result explainer | trust | G-K |\n| C9 | Time-travel replay | retrospectives | G-G |\n| C10 | Memory diffing across versions | onboarding | G-B |\n\n### 8.3 C1 — Pluggable embedding provider\n\nToday: single, ad-hoc embedding path. Future: an `EmbeddingProvider` interface\nselected at install time. Implementations: `null` (FTS5 only), `local-hash`\n(deterministic), `claude-tool` (calls back into Claude Code), `bundled-onnx`\n(opt-in, only if the user chooses to install a small model).\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  Learn[learn] --> EI[EmbeddingProvider Interface]\n  Recall[recall] --> EI\n  EI --> P1[null provider]\n  EI --> P2[local-hash provider]\n  EI --> P3[claude-tool provider]\n  EI --> P4[onnx local provider]\n  EI -- write/read --> DB[(memory_embeddings table)]\n```\n\nRecall remains FTS5-first; the embedding step is a fallback **and** an enrichment\n(pre-rank pass for high-recall queries). Provider is hot-swappable: changing the\nprovider triggers a one-time re-embed pass via the janitor.\n\n### 8.4 C2 — Multi-device E2E encrypted sync\n\nThe developer should have one memory across machines without trusting any cloud.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n  participant Laptop\n  participant Relay as Sync Relay (zero-knowledge)\n  participant Desktop\n\n  Laptop->>Laptop: derive symmetric key from passphrase (Argon2id)\n  Laptop->>Laptop: serialise CRDT delta of memory ops\n  Laptop->>Laptop: encrypt(delta, key)\n  Laptop->>Relay: PUT /blobs/{user-hash}/{seq}\n  Desktop->>Relay: GET /blobs/{user-hash}?since=N\n  Desktop->>Desktop: decrypt(blob, key)\n  Desktop->>Desktop: apply CRDT delta\n```\n\n**Why CRDT.** Memories accrue independently on each device between syncs; conflict\nresolution must be deterministic. A simple op-based CRDT (insert/forget/relate)\nwith last-writer-wins on `confirm_count` updates is sufficient.\n\n**Why E2E.** PRD persona Ezra; PRD §7 N1. The relay sees only ciphertext.\n\n**Opt-in.** Default off. Configurable via `/openltm:admin sync setup`.\n\n### 8.5 C3 — Team memory bundles (signed export/import)\n\nA bundle is a JSON file: schema-version + array of memories + array of relations,\nsigned with the exporter's keypair. Importer verifies signature, then enters a\n**review flow** (not auto-merge): each incoming memory is staged with status\n`pending`, surfaced at next SessionStart, accepted/rejected one by one.\n\nBundles target the team-lead persona Tara without crossing into multi-tenant\nterritory. Memory remains per-developer; bundles are a transport.\n\n### 8.6 C4 — Conflict detection on learn\n\nWhen `learn` is called, the Learn Engine first runs a similarity check against\nexisting memories. If `(similarity > 0.85) AND (polarity_opposite OR same_dedup_topic)`,\nthe new memory is staged `pending` with a link to the conflicting memory. The user\nis asked at next SessionStart: *forget*, *supersede*, or *coexist*.\n\nThis makes the LTM **self-curating** (PRD §1.1).\n\n### 8.7 C5 — Provenance chain\n\nEvery memory gets a `provenance` row chain:\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  M[Memory m_42] -- provenance --> P1[source: session sess_abc, turn 7]\n  M -- provenance --> P2[source: git-backfill, sha def123]\n  M -- provenance --> P3[source: evaluate-session, score 0.92]\n  M -- provenance --> P4[source: user-promotion, importance bumped 3 to 5]\n```\n\nRecall results carry provenance; the explainer (C8) surfaces it inline.\n\n### 8.8 C6 — Memory compression / rollups\n\nWhen memory count for a project exceeds a threshold (config), the janitor clusters\nrelated memories (by tag overlap + embedding similarity) and proposes a *rollup*:\none new summary memory linked to N source memories via `supersedes` edges. Sources\nmove to `status='deprecated'` but are retained for time-travel (C9).\n\n### 8.9 C7 — Cross-plugin memory contract\n\nToday the LTM is a silo. Other plugins (`task-tracker`, `code-review`,\n`dev-team`, etc.) cannot write into it without bypassing the MCP server.\n\nThe future contract: a published, semver'd MCP tool surface\n(`ltm.write_v1(content, category, importance, source_plugin, source_ref)`) that other\nplugins call. Writes carry `source_plugin` for provenance. The DAO enforces the\ncontract. This is what makes LTM the *substrate* for the whole ecosystem.\n\n### 8.10 C8 — Recall result explainer\n\nEach result returns a one-line `why_ranked` (e.g. \"FTS5 BM25=4.2 + recency boost +\nimportance 4 → score 6.7\"). Powers debuggability; the user can teach the system\nby adjusting importance instead of guessing.\n\n### 8.11 C9 — Time-travel replay\n\nA `memory_audit` append-only log (W11) plus a `--at <date>` flag on `recall`\nallows reconstructing the memory state at any past point. Boot a session as if it\nwere a month ago: `/openltm:project replay --date 2026-03-15`.\n\n### 8.12 C10 — Memory diffing across versions\n\nPair to C9. `/openltm:memory diff --from 2026-01-01 --to 2026-04-01` returns\n*added*, *forgotten*, *superseded*, *importance-changed* memories between two\npoints. Surfaces as a markdown report or a graph-app v2 view.\n\n### 8.13 The magnificent container picture\n\n```mermaid\nC4Container\n  title LTM v2 — Magnificent Architecture (target)\n\n  Person(dev, \"Developer (multi-device, optional team)\")\n  System_Ext(claude, \"Claude Code Harness\")\n  System_Ext(plugins, \"Other Plugins (task-tracker, code-review, ...)\")\n  System_Ext(relay, \"Sync Relay (E2E, zero-knowledge)\")\n\n  System_Boundary(ltm2, \"LTM Plugin v2\") {\n    Container(mcp, \"MCP Server v2\", \"Bun\", \"Stable read+write contract; explainable recall\")\n    Container(hooks, \"Hook Runners v2\", \"Bun\", \"Structured logs; conflict + rollup banners\")\n    Container(dao, \"DAO Layer\", \"Bun module\", \"Single point of DB access; isolates schema\")\n    Container(janitor, \"Janitor\", \"Bun scheduler\", \"Decay materialise, conflict detect, rollup propose, sync push/pull\")\n    Container(embed, \"Embedding Service\", \"Bun + provider plugins\", \"null / hash / claude-tool / onnx\")\n    Container(graph, \"Graph App v2\", \"SPA\", \"Timeline scrubber, cluster view, diff overlay\")\n    Container(sync, \"Sync Agent\", \"Bun\", \"CRDT delta serialise + E2E encrypt + relay client\")\n    ContainerDb(db, \"openltm.db v2\", \"SQLite WAL + partitioned + audited\", \"memories, embeddings (split), provenance, audit, settings, schema_migrations\")\n  }\n\n  Rel(dev, claude, \"Prompts\")\n  Rel(claude, mcp, \"MCP\")\n  Rel(claude, hooks, \"Lifecycle events\")\n  Rel(plugins, mcp, \"Cross-plugin memory contract (C7)\")\n  Rel(mcp, dao, \"All access\")\n  Rel(hooks, dao, \"All access\")\n  Rel(janitor, dao, \"All access\")\n  Rel(embed, dao, \"embedding writes / reads\")\n  Rel(graph, dao, \"read-only API\")\n  Rel(dao, db, \"SQL\")\n  Rel(sync, relay, \"PUT/GET encrypted blobs (opt-in)\")\n  Rel(sync, dao, \"apply CRDT deltas\")\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Migration Path\n\nBig-bang rewrites kill plugins. The migration is phased; each phase is shippable\nand backwards-compatible until the breaking-change phase, which is gated on a major\nversion bump.\n\n### Phase 0 — Foundation hardening (non-breaking, 1.5.x)\n\nGoal: fix the weaknesses that don't require schema or contract changes.\n\n- **W1, W5:** Add structured hook + MCP event log table. `/openltm:doctor` reads it.\n- **W3:** Replace ad-hoc `runMigrations` with a `schema_migrations` table and\n  numbered SQL files. Backfill from current state.\n- **W6:** Add a documented \"dev mode\" symlink helper to `/openltm:admin`.\n- **W2:** Atomic-write `registry.json` (tmp + rename).\n\nBackwards compatible. No schema rename. No MCP contract change.\n\n### Phase 1 — DAO + observability (non-breaking, 1.6.x)\n\n- Introduce `src/dao/` as the single point of DB access (W8).\n- Refactor `mcp-server.ts`, hooks, and graph-server to call through DAO.\n- Add latency / recall-hit telemetry to the DAO; surface in `/openltm:health`.\n- Move `embedding` BLOB into `memory_embeddings` sibling table (W7); migration is a\n  copy + drop column. MCP responses naturally shrink.\n\nBackwards compatible at the MCP contract level. Schema migrates idempotently.\n\n### Phase 2 — Provenance + audit (non-breaking, 1.7.x)\n\n- Add `memory_audit` (W11) and `memory_provenance` (W9, C5) tables.\n- Hooks and MCP write through DAO so audit is uniform.\n- New optional fields on recall results: `provenance`, `why_ranked` (C8).\n- Existing memories get a backfilled `provenance` row of type `legacy`.\n\n### Phase 3 — Embedding provider abstraction (non-breaking, 1.8.x)\n\n- Introduce `EmbeddingProvider` interface (C1).\n- Default provider remains the current one; users can opt into `claude-tool` or\n  `local-hash`.\n- Recall logic gains a \"rerank with embeddings\" pass for high-recall queries.\n\n### Phase 4 — Janitor (non-breaking, 1.9.x)\n\n- Materialise `decay_score` on `memories` (W4); janitor refreshes on a schedule.\n- Conflict detector (C4) runs on `learn` and stages conflicting memories\n  `pending`.\n- Rollup proposer (C6) runs nightly; user reviews via SessionStart banner.\n\n### Phase 5 — Cross-plugin contract (semver-major, 2.0.0)\n\n- Publish stable, versioned MCP write surface (C7).\n- Lock in DAO function signatures for external callers.\n- Deprecate the last unversioned write paths.\n\nThis is a **major version bump** because the published contract becomes a\ncompatibility commitment.\n\n### Phase 6 — Sync + bundles (non-breaking on the contract, 2.1.x onward)\n\n- Sync agent + relay protocol (C2).\n- Memory bundle export/import flow (C3).\n- Both opt-in; default off; no impact on local-only users.\n\n### Phase 7 — Time-travel + diffing (non-breaking, 2.2.x onward)\n\n- Replay (C9) and diff (C10) commands; both depend on the audit log from Phase 2.\n\n### Backwards-compatibility ledger\n\n| Phase | Schema breaking? | MCP contract breaking? | User-visible CLI breaking? |\n|-------|------------------|-----------------------|----------------------------|\n| 0 | No | No | No |\n| 1 | Migrates idempotently | No | No |\n| 2 | Adds columns/tables | Adds optional fields | No |\n| 3 | No | Adds optional fields | No (provider choice) |\n| 4 | Adds column (decay_score) | No | New banners only |\n| 5 | No | **Yes — semver major** | No |\n| 6 | Adds tables (sync state) | Adds optional sync tools | New `/openltm:admin sync` group |\n| 7 | No | Adds optional tools | New `/openltm:memory diff/replay` |\n\n---\n\n## 10. Non-Goals\n\nTo keep scope honest:\n\n- **NG1.** Building an embedding model. Embedding is delegated to a provider;\n  the plugin never trains.\n- **NG2.** Multi-tenant cloud. Even with C2 sync, there is no shared multi-tenant\n  store. Each user owns their relay namespace and their key.\n- **NG3.** Replacing ADRs, PR descriptions, or design docs. LTM captures the\n  *reasoning behind* the code; durable design docs (like this one) live in `docs/`.\n- **NG4.** Online learning from raw transcripts. EvaluateSession proposes\n  *distilled* insights; full transcripts never enter the DB (PRD N6).\n- **NG5.** Cross-plugin **read-write coupling** that breaks the LTM if another\n  plugin disappears. The cross-plugin contract (C7) is one-way (others write to\n  LTM); LTM does not depend on any other plugin to function.\n\n---\n\n## Hand-off\n\nThis spec unblocks:\n\n- **database-admin** — owns Phase 0 W3 (schema_migrations table), Phase 1 schema\n  refactor (split `memory_embeddings`), Phase 2 audit/provenance tables. Uses §5\n  (Data Model) as ground truth.\n- **backend-developer** — owns DAO refactor (Phase 1), embedding provider\n  interface (Phase 3), janitor (Phase 4). Uses §3 (components) and ADRs as\n  guardrails.\n- **devops-engineer** — owns the sync relay (Phase 6) deployment + key management\n  if/when sync ships.\n- **ui-ux-designer** — owns the surfaces called out in PRD §10 hand-off and the\n  graph-app v2 (C9, C10 visualisation) in Phase 7.\n\nEvery dev task created against this spec must `dependsOn` the originating\narchitecture task so the design ↔ implementation trace remains intact.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":1075,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":false}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780928491799,"end":1780928491824}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b38135ca386cce6016a26cfeb870c8191a000442613b55e91"}},"id":"prt_ea79c310e001G7rVEIrgxJAA0V","sessionID":"ses_158648ad2ffeoI7GYKZ0HGX78G","messageID":"msg_ea79bf7bf001DIjVOHWhZ60TEN"}}
